<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Storm-O'Hare     10-17 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Storm-O'Hare,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Powerful Storm Rips Central Illinois, Snarls Air Traffic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fast-moving storm raked central and northern
Illinois with hail and high winds on Monday, delaying hundreds of
flights at Chicago airports, and forcing the evacuation of two
schools and a factory near Peoria.
   The storm forced delays of 225 jetliners flying into and out of
O'Hare International Airport, the nation's busiest, said Robert
Handschiegel, a spokesman for the Federal Aviation Administration.
   ``The average delay was an hour and 15 minutes and the maximum
was three hours,'' he said.
   Flights also were delayed at Midway airport as a tornado watch
was issued for the Chicago area Monday afternoon. A water spout was
reported on Lake Michigan about 2 p.m., weather service officials
said, but it caused no damage.
   The storm, caused by a collision between a warm front from the
south and a cold front from the north, was headed east, weather
officials said. Illinois was expecting mostly sunny skies Tuesday,
with highs in the 50s and 60s.
   Five people were reported struck by lightning in the Chicago
area, and one, an electrician, remained hospitalized in stable
condition Monday night.
   In Peoria County, the storm unleashed wind gusts up to 63 mph
and golf-ball-sized hail, causing extensive damage to buildings,
homes and several schools Monday morning.
   ``We got no warning, no sirens, no nothing,'' said William
Collier, school superintendent at Dunlap, about six miles northwest
of Peoria. ``It was a freak storm that blew up out of nowhere. I
was sitting here at my window and I saw it get dark.
   ``Within about 15 seconds it was really blowing and there was a
tremendous electrical storm. Car windows were popping out and
exploding, glass was breaking and trees and power lines went down.''
   Youngsters at the five Dunlap school buildings were unscathed,
although the 500 high school students were ushered outside and
classes canceled when officials smelled smoke and feared a fire.
Officials found roof damage but no fire.
   The Mossville Grade School, about 15 miles east of Dunlap, also
was closed because of roof damage.
   Assembly lines were shut down for about 30 minutes and employees
were evacuated from shops at Caterpillar Inc.'s Mossville engine
plant in a complex that employs about 5,000 people, said Gil Nolde,
company spokesman.
</TEXT>
