<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-Kappler 1stLd-Writethru a0647 10-17 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Kappler, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0647,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Italy Asks Widow of Nazi Criminal to Stay Away</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds 4 grafs on senators asking about government action,
possible legal penalties</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italy's justice minister on Monday urged the widow
of a Nazi war criminal not to come to Italy to promote a book on
how she helped her husband escape from a Rome military prison in
1977.
   Giuliano Vassalli said that such a visit solely for publicity
``is the cause of legitimate concern'' by relatives of those killed
in a massacre for which Herbert Kappler was judged responsibile.
   Kappler, an SS colonel in Rome during World War II, was
sentenced to life in prison for his role in the massacre of 335
Italians in 1944.
   He escaped in August 1977, reportedly concealed in a large
suitcase wheeled out of the prison by his wife. Kappler died of
cancer a year later in West Germany.
   His widow, Annelise, said last week she would come to Rome
Saturday to present her book ``I Will Bring You Home.''
   A Justice Ministry spokesman said Vassalli issued a statement in
response to a letter he received from Mrs. Kappler in which she
stated why she planned to come to Italy and asked his opinion.
   Three senators representing Italy's largest political parties,
the Christian Democrats, Communists and Socialists, asked the
government Monday to declare what measures it would take to keep
Mrs. Kappler out of the country.
   But the government did not say immediately if it might take
legal action.
   Law provides a prison term of up to 10 years for aiding the
escape of a convict sentenced to life.
</TEXT>
