<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--NorthwesternGift     10-17 0160</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Northwestern Gift,0164</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Patient Repays Doctors For Gift Of Life With $17 Million Donation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reuben Feinberg says he has a good reason for
giving $17 million to doctors at Northwestern University Medical
School _ they saved his life.
   Feinberg's gift, the third largest ever received by the
university, was announced Saturday, one year after his heart
surgery at Northwestern Memorial Hospital.
   ``I never had thought about giving money to a hospital before
then,'' said Feinberg, 70, president and director of the Jefferson
State Bank in Chicago.
   ``I was thinking more about a building or something,'' he said.
``But bricks don't accomplish much. People can.''
   Feinberg, whose father, Joseph, died of heart disease, is
donating the money to establish a cardiovascular research center at
the medical school.
   University president Arnold R. Weber said the planned Feinberg
Cardiovascular Research Institute ``has the promise to become the
finest center of excellence in cardiovascular research and
education in the nation.''
</TEXT>
