<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-88 0123EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-TrumanFever Bjt   10-17 0799</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Truman Fever, Bjt,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Time Running Out, Democrats Dream of a Truman
Upset</HEAD>
<BYLINE>An AP News Analysis</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN WOLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the modern age of presidential politics,
the Democrats have a lot of experience being given up for dead.
Generally, it's been a realistic enough presentiment, but Michael
Dukakis will surely look for inspiration to several remarkable
party heroes.
   Harry Truman and Hubert Humphrey are the Mr. Octobers of their
era. It was probably Truman foe Thomas Dewey whom Republican
front-runner George Bush was thinking about when he vowed over the
weekend to ``go the extra mile'' this month, and added, ``I'm not
going to mess up.''
   Lloyd Bentsen was using Truman and Kirk Gibson as his weekend
role models.
   ``Our party has a proud tradition of closing from behind,'' said
Dukakis' indefatigable running mate. He told a farmer's market in
St Louis, ``I can't help but remember Harry Truman out there when
the press had written him off.''
   Humphrey came up short, of course, but his 1968 October comeback
was still extraordinary, following as it did a divisive primary
campaign and a calamitous convention. He sought to succeed an
unpopular president _ Lyndon Johnson _ for whom the word albatross
comes to mind.
   But come back he did. After finally staking out some
independence from Johnson, Humphrey put together a high-energy
campaign in October and ended with 42.7 percent of the vote, nearly
scaring Richard Nixon out of his wits. (Nixon ended with 43.4
percent. George Wallace had 13.5 percent).
   Though a sitting president in 1948, Truman didn't win nomination
until well after midnight, at which time convention managers
released a flock of doves to celebrate. The doves, stifled by the
heat, promptly dropped dead on the convention floor, prompting one
party stalwart to reflect, ``Dead pigeons, just like Truman.''
   Except the year didn't end with Truman dead.
   Unpopular and far behind in the polls, Truman invented the
whistlestop, making an average of 10 speeches a day from the back
of a train and sparing the Republicans no ridicule in that blunt,
partisan ``Give `Em Hell'' manner of his. Dewey was no George Bush;
he stayed above the fray. On election day, Truman stood
expectations on their head, winning 49.5 percent of the vote to
Dewey's 45 percent.
   Dukakis enjoys the same mid-October expectations as Truman,
which is to say few outside his immediate family really believe
he'll win. But there are differences between the two men, and one
is half-tempted to look over at the cerebral and aloof Dukakis and
say, ``Governor, you're no Harry Truman.''
   Truman never had to say, ``I think I'm a reasonably likable
guy,'' and if you asked him to name his heroes in American life,
can you imagine Truman responding _ as did Dukakis last Thursday
night _ ``Some of them are in public life, in the Senate and the
Congress, some of my fellow governors ... are real heroes to me.''
   His fellow governors!
   Truman, like Dukakis, was not a commanding figure. Lots of
people looked down upon him, figuratively and literally.
   ``At first the critics referred to my (campaign) tour as a
`one-man circus,' and called it less efficient and less dignified
than the campaign being put on by the Republicans,'' Truman said in
his memoirs, describing his comeback this way:
   ``I simply told the people in my own language that they had
better wake up to the fact that it was their fight. If they did not
get out and help me win this fight, I emphasized, the Republicans
would soon be giving the farmers and the workers the little end of
the stick again.''
   The Dukakis command huddled in Boston and emerged to tell The
Washington Post they would, a la Truman, concentrate on economic
themes in the last-ditch drive for a miracle. They mapped out an
effort to concentrate on 18 states with 272 electoral votes.
   That doesn't leave any margin for error. It takes 270 electoral
votes to win the White House, and common sense says you can't win
every state you contest _ unless you're Ronald Reagan and you're
going to win them all anyway.
   By Sunday, Bentsen had merged his Truman reminisces with a World
Series theme, buoyed by the fact that the underdogs from Los
Angeles had won a first-game victory with the gimpy Gibson's
two-out homer in ninth.
   ``We're going to be like the Dodgers last night,'' he said. ``It
looked like they were down and out and all of a sudden they hit a
home run and won it. And I think we can do that in the next 24
days.''
   Of course this is Bentsen talking, not Dukakis.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Jonathan Wolman is AP's assistant bureau chief in
Washington.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
