<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Reagan'sLastCampaign     10-17 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan's Last Campaign,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Relishes Key Campaign Role</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, with little left on his
agenda but to keep the White House in Republican hands, is
relishing his high-profile role in George Bush's campaign.
   As he attends to the business of signing legislation passed by
Congress in its waning days, Reagan is continuing to stump for Bush
in key battleground states.
   He'll take his ``peace-and-prosperity'' message into the heart
of Ohio this Wednesday, and will increase the campaign pace after
Congress adjourns, possibly this week.
   ``I think the president's thriving. He's enjoying himself. He
thinks he's making a difference,'' White House chief of staff
Kenneth M. Duberstein said recently.
   By all accounts, Reagan's role in Bush's bid for the White House
has gone through an evolution in recent weeks. The president has
stepped up his appeal to the so-called ``Reagan Democrats'' in
Midwestern and Northeastern states, whereas it was once thought he
would play a smaller role.
   ``I was of the impression that they (the Bush campaign) were
going to say, `Go carry California,''' said Democratic consultant
Robert Keefe.
   Some inside both the Bush campaign and the White House had said
early on that Reagan's campaign activities would likely be focused
on California, his home state, and on southern and Sun Belt states,
where Reagan has been immensely popular, even during his hard times.
   One Republican strategist, discussing the changing campaign
route on grounds of anonymity, said it was decided that Reagan
should focus on the key battleground states where there are large
numbers of ethnics, conservative Democrats and independents. And so
Reagan has spent recent weeks in such places as Illinois, Michigan,
Pennsylvania and New Jersey.
   ``Some of the places where the president is strongest have just
solidified for Bush ... much faster than we expected,'' said this
Republican. ``So the question became, do you want to go to a state
where you're 20 points up. ... It obviously makes more sense to
look at the other states that are close.''
   ``I think the role is just right,'' said GOP consultant Eddie
Mahe. ``You're sending your biggest guns into the biggest battles,
and there's no surrogate bigger than Ronald Reagan.''
   Keefe, the Democrat, acknowledged that the strategy of having
Reagan follow Bush into states the vice president has visited
recently has been helpful to the GOP cause.
   ``They have had a marvelous campaign where they have integrated
the message themes very well,'' he said.
   Besides making campaign appearances for his vice president _
Reagan will likely put on a full-court press in California, for
example _ the president has used the trappings of his office to
Bush's benefit.
   Reagan frequently works a pro-Bush pitch into his official
chores, such as bill-signings, whenever he can connect the vice
president to the situation at hand, and throws pro-Bush statements
into his weekly radio addresses.
   Perhaps Reagan's all-out campaign for Bush can be traced to
conversations that both the president and Duberstein had with
former President Richard M. Nixon.
   Nixon is known to believe that the lukewarm support given him by
President Dwight D. Eisenhower in 1960 contributed to his loss to
Democrat John F. Kennedy.
   In an interview, Duberstein said that ``Nixon and I spoke
several months ago, and I asked him to give his historical
perspective _ what Eisenhower did and didn't do for him,'' and
Reagan entertained Nixon for a private White House dinner.
   The chief of staff said in an interview that because of these
and other factors, ``I think it's fair to say that Ronald Reagan
has campaigned for his vice president in an unprecedented manner.''
   Keefe agreed with that.
   ``What they have is an extremely commanding voice that can get
himself heard any time he wants to, day or night, and it's just
awfully handy to have someone who can do that,'' he said.
</TEXT>
