<DOCNO> AP881017-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-88 0042EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-UNITA Bjt   10-17 0728</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UNITA, Bjt,0749</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With South African Troops Gone, UNITA Finds New Friends</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW TORCHIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MAVINGA, Angola (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With South African troops out of southern
Angola, rebel leader Jonas Savimbi says his UNITA guerrillas face a
tougher military struggle but have gained support in the United
States and Africa.
   Guerrilla officers promise few prolonged battles of the kind
that UNITA and South African forces waged early this year in the
siege of Cuito Cuanavale.
   Angolan government units were temporarily driven out of the
southern town, they say. But, eight months later, UNITA is back in
defensive positions east of Cuito, awaiting an enemy campaign.
   The departure of several thousand South African soldiers seven
weeks ago, as part of regional peace negotiations, ``has weakened
our position,'' Savimbi said in a recent interview.
   But he said the South African move has bolstered UNITA's
credibility as an independent force and has increased diplomatic
pressure on the Angolan government to negotiate a settlement.
   The declared goal of UNITA _ the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola _ is to force the ruling Popular Movement
for the Independence of Angola into a power-sharing arrangement
leading to national elections.
   Savimbi expressed confidence that UNITA, relying on traditional
guerrilla advantages of speed and surprise, can maintain the
stalemate in Angola's 13-year civil war.
   ``We cannot come out without wounds. But we can sustain some
wounds,'' Savimbi said.
   ``For sure, Jamba will never fall,'' Savimbi said, referring to
UNITA's bush headquarters in southeastern Angola. ``They will pay
such a heavy price _ I think they will not try.''
   UNITA says it has 37,000 guerrillas and 28,000 regular soldiers,
nearly half as many as the government's more heavily armed 80,000
soldiers and the 50,000 Cuban troops on its side.
   Negotiations involving Angola, Cuba, South Africa and the United
States are aimed at an agreement by Nov. 1 for a Cuban withdrawal.
In return, South Africa would allow implementation of a United
Nations independence plan for South-West Africa, also known as
Namibia.
   The Marxist Angolan government ``cannot stand alone without the
Cubans,'' Savimbi said during the interview at an unmapped forest
supply camp near Mavinga, about 80 miles from forward UNITA
positions.
   ``African countries are giving much more sympathy since the
South Africans left,'' Savimbi said. He named Zambia, Togo,
Morocco, Senegal, Nigeria, Kenya, Cameroon, Chad, Guinea, Mali,
Egypt, Zaire and Ivory Coast as sympathetic to UNITA's cause.
   He said liberal U.S. Democrats, Sens. Paul Simon of Illinois and
Christopher Dodd of Connecticut, told him during a visit to the
United States this year that the main barrier to their
understanding ``was the direct involvement of South Africa.''
   ``Now we are working very well,'' he said of the Democrats.
   Brig. Peregrino Chindondo, UNITA's intelligence chief, said
guerrillas caused serious Cuban casualties and burned eight Cuban
vehicles in a raid Oct. 6 on a convoy near the central highlands
city of Huambo. He said 25 vehicles were seized Oct. 3 when UNITA
took Sanzo Pombo in the northern Uige Province.
   ``The morale of the enemy is very bad,'' Chindondo said. ``Most
are recruited in round-up operations. There is friction with the
Cubans. They have lost the support of the people.''
   During an 11-day tour of UNITA bases in southeastern Angola,
where the movement effectively governs one-third of the country,
reporters visited a guerrilla command post 3 miles from enemy lines
at Cuito Cuanavale. There they talked with Angolan prisoner of war
Julio Wango, 25, a few hours after he was captured in a skirmish.
   Wounds on Wango's head and elbows were bandaged. He was barefoot
and UNITA officers said it was customary to remove prisoners' boots
so they could not escape.
   Wango said he had fled his village near Ganda, in Benguela
Province, to avoid military service but was caught by a government
squad in a cornfield in March.
   ``They beat me and told me I was a crook for trying to escape,''
Wango said. ``They gave me three months' training and made me a
sergeant.''
   ``In the army, we don't have any food, no breakfast. People are
weak and fall while on duty,'' Wango said. ``The only ones getting
good food are Cubans.
   ``Once I ran away to another brigade to trade beads for
something to eat. They found me and put me in confinement for five
days.''
</TEXT>
