<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SoldiersFight     10-17 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soldiers Fight,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brawl Erupts Between Americans And Koreans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 40 U.S. soldiers brandishing
jacknives and broken bottles brawled with rock-throwing South
Koreans in the capital's shopping district. An American and a South
Korean were hospitalized, officials said today.
   News reports said one American and three Koreans were injured in
the clash early Sunday, and one of the Koreans was in critical
condition.
   According to a military press release, the incident in the
nightclub section of Itaewon was sparked by a verbal altercation
between a Korean taxi driver and an American soldier. The argument
escalated into an assault involving four Americans and a number of
Koreans.
   Itaewon is a a shopping district close to the U.S. Forces Korea
Headquarters in Seoul.
   South Korean police officials said the four Americans suddenly
began cursing at the taxi driver, Lee Ok-Chul, 51, and kicked his
cab on a street corner. Lee was quoted as saying that when he got
of his car and protested, the Americans punched him in the face and
some even climbed on top of his car.
   The officials said about 40 Koreans rushed to Lee's aid. The
Americans then fled, brandishing empty beer bottles and throwing
rocks at the pursuing crowd.
   When Korean passers-by jeered at the fleeing Americans, police
said about 40 other American soldiers joined in and brandished jack
knives and broken beer bottle at the Koreans, who countered by
throwing rocks.
   The Koreans, whose number had swelled to about 200 by then,
shouted ``Yankee go home,'' in front of a nightclub into which the
Americans had fled, the officials said.
   About 200 police who arrived at the scene dispersed the crowd of
Koreans. The four unidentified soldiers involved in the initial
altercation were booked for investigation and turned over to U.S.
miltiary authorities, the police said.
   Officials did not release the names of the injured and it was
not immediately clear when the injuries occurred.
</TEXT>
