<2ND_LINE>PM-Hirohito,0187</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hirohito Discharges More Blood, Court Festival Held</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito discharged more blood today but
his condition remains stable, officials said.
   The crown prince and other members of the imperial family
meanwhile attended an annual harvest festival.
   Hirohito, 87, discharged a small amount of blood ``on several
occasions'' Sunday night through this morning, Imperial Household
Agency spokesman Kenji Maeda told palace reporters.
   The world's longest-reigning monarch, who has discharged small
amounts of blood since Saturday, was given a transfusion of 0.84
pints of blood Sunday, bringing the total he has received since
vomiting blood Sept. 19 to 17.4 pints.
   The transfusions were administered to help the emperor combat
anemia and supplement blood lost in internal bleeding, according to
palace officials.
   The rite, called Kannamesai, includes offering prayers in the
direction of the Ise Shrine, where the sun goddess is worshipped,
and presenting sacred offerings at a small shrine on the palace
grounds, according to palace spokesman Chifuru Ashizawa.
   ``The Kannamesai is an imperial festival giving thanks to the
gods by offering newly harvested crops,'' Ashizawa said.
</TEXT>
