<1ST_LINE>r i PM-PhilippinesReax     10-17 0618</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines Reax,0635</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senator Warns Pact May Prompt Moves To Terminate Bases</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Philippines, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino urged the
public today to await details before judging a new agreement on
U.S. military bases, but lawmakers said the government had accepted
too little money.
   Groups opposed to the presence of U.S. troops branded the
agreement a ``sell-out,'' and one senator said he hoped the
agreement would respect a Philippine ban on nuclear weapons in its
territory.
   Another senator said an unsatisfactory agreement will speed up
legislation requiring the Aquino government to give Washington
notice it will close the six bases when their lease expires in 1991.
   In Washington on Sunday, Foreign Secretary Raul Manglapus said
the United States has agreed to pay $481 million annually and back
a bond program to help ease the country's foreign debt as part of a
lease agreement for the bases.
   Philippine sources said Manglapus originally asked for $1.2
billion over two years for use of the two largest U.S. bases abroad
_ Clark Air Base and Subic Navy Base _ and four smaller
installations.
   Manglapus said Mrs. Aquino gave him a ``go signal'' to sign the
pact in Washington today. Cash payments would be a big increase
over the current $180 million in U.S. military and economic aid
attached to the bases, but less than half that sought by the
Philippines when talks began in April.
   Mrs. Aquino was asked by reporters today whether she considered
the talks successful.
   ``Why don't we just wait until all the details are laid out and
expressed by Secretary Manglapus,'' she said.
   The left-wing Peoples Party denounced the agreement as a
``sell-out'' and said Manglapus should not have linked the
continued presence of foreign troops to the debt issue.
   Party spokesman Fidel Agcaoili said the two issues should have
been negotiated separately to strengthen the Philippine bargaining
stand.
   Sen. Ernesto Maceda, chairman of the Senate Defense Committee,
said the reported agreement ``is a confirmation of the fact that it
seems that this administration is not ready yet to stand up to
Washington.''
   Maceda said the Senate ``would be inclined'' to begin debate on
a proposal filed months ago by majority leader Sen. Orlando Mercado
to serve notice that the bases will be closed in 1991.
   Without such notification, Maceda said the bases agreement would
be automatically renewed. The new Constitution requires that any
extension beyond 1991 be approved by two-thirds of the 23-member
Senate, where anti-bases sentiment is strong.
   But Rep. Gualberto Lumauig, a member of the House of
Representatives Foreign Relations Committee, termed the agreement
``welcome news'' because it would mean more money for the country
as it tries to cope with a $28 billion foreign debt.
   The Manila Stock Exchange opened 4.54 points higher today than
Friday's close of 725.52. Traders said the increase was due in part
to reports the United States and the Philippines reached a bases
agreement.
   Sen. Wigberto Tanada, a leading bases opponent, said financial
compensation was not the only issue.
   ``I don't think it is enough to settle the issue of compensation
if the threat of national destruction due to nuclear weapons and
the derogation of national sovereignty is still there,'' Tanada
said.
   Tanada was chief sponsor of a bill approved by the Senate this
year which would ban nuclear weapons from Clark, Subic Bay and the
four smaller installations. The legislation is pending in the House.
   The agreement would cover only the final two years of the 1947
Military Bases Agreement, which expires in 1991. Mrs. Aquino has
refused to say whether she will support extending the agreement,
which runs out one year before her term expires.
</TEXT>
