<2ND_LINE>PM-Tall Stacks,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rain Fails To Dampen Tall Stacks Spirit</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CS1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people rode riverboats and lined
the Ohio River's shores on the closing day of the city's ``Tall
Stacks'' celebration in conjunction with the city's bicentennial.
   The weekend festival concluded Sunday evening with fireworks
displays after a friendly race between the Belle of Louisville and
the Delta Queen, which won.
   Jay Downie, events producer for the Greater Cincinnati
Bicentennial Commission, estimated Sunday's crowd at 300,000. He
and David Rager, assistant safety director for Cincinnati, said
about a million people attended the four-day ``Tall Stacks''
celebration.
   Fourteen riverboats and excursion boats gathered along the Ohio
River for the festival, which included tours, cruises and races.
The biggest race was Sunday between the Delta Queen and the Belle
of Louisville, the only two authentic steam-powered, paddlewheel
boats at the celebration.
   The riverboats have met in Louisville for annual Derby Week
races since 1963, when the excursion boat Avalon was restored and
christened Belle of Louisville. River historian C.W. Stoll said
with the Belle's most recent victory in May, it leads the races,
13-11.
   Atop her Hurricane Deck, the Belle sports a pair of deer
antlers, the trophy symbolizing the fastest boat on the river. The
antlers are up for grabs each year during Derby Week.
