<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua-Church     10-17 0629</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua-Church,0655</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nicaraguan Government Campaigns Against Church Leader</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government appears to be on a
campaign to discredit the head of the Roman Catholic Church in
Nicaragua, Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo, over the church's use of
U.S. funds.
   But the main issue seems to be the government's determination,
now that it feels it has defeated the U.S.-backed rebels
militarily, to stop the flow of U.S. funds to groups opposed to or
not supportive of the leftist Sandinista regime.
   Conservative estimates by political opposition sources in the
capital Managua say more than $50,000 arrive from the United States
monthly. The Sandinistas argue that most of the money comes from
the Central Intelligence Agency even if it is distributed by labor,
church or other groups.
   On Saturday, President Daniel Ortega accused Obando y Bravo and
Nicaraguan bishops of becoming ``instruments of Ronald Reagan's
politics of death'' by accepting U.S. funds.
   At the center of the controversy with the Catholic Church is the
role of the cardinal as one of the two members of the Verification
Commission agreed upon by the Sandinista government and the rebels,
known as Contras.
   The duty of the commission is to confirm that the two sides are
following the peace accords tentatively approved earlier this year.
   The other commission member is Joao Baena Soares,
secretary-general of the Organization of American States, or OAS.
   The tentative peace accords specified that Verification
Commission would be under the control of Baena Soares. The OAS
would pay for expenses, but to speed things up the U.S. Agency for
1nternational Development agreed to provide the $10 million needed.
   Managua Curia spokesman Monsignor Bismark Carballo explained
that nearly $1 million of the funds would be used by the church to
acquire equipment and pay salaries of members of local verification
commissionss set up by the church in cease-fire areas.
   The issue came to light a few days ago when the
government-controlled news media accused Obando y Bravo of trying
to bring in, duty-free, 17 four-wheel vehicles and a similar number
of generators reportedly to be used by the local verification
commissions.
   Assistant Foreign Minister Victor Hugo Tinoco said there is
nothing the local commissions can verify since there was no
concrete agreement between the government and the Contras.
   ``What are they verifying?'' Tinoco asked last week, adding the
gpvernment does not recognize the cardinal as being in charge of
the Verification Commission.
   According to the original accords, the commission would verify
the movement of the Contras into safe cease-fire areas, withdrawal
of Sandinista troops and the eventual disarming of the rebels and
their return to civilian life.
   The talks broke down in June, with both sides announcing
unilateral cease-fires.
   The local verification commissions were to be made up of the
Catholic bishops in the cease-fire areas and people they appointed
as well as foreign representatives named by the OAS
secretary-general.
   Baena Soares has remained quiet during the controversy, and
currently the commissions have only those members named by the
church.
   Church officials say they feel the commissions are also charged
with verification of respect for human rights and
``democratization'' in the cease-fire areas.
   ``We know what they are doing,'' Tinoco said.
   Church officials acknowledge the commissions have gathered
information harmful to the government.
   Tinoco said any funds for the Verification Commission ``may be
suspended until the government and the commission reach an
agreement on the way the commissions will work.''
   Church officials said privately they feel the government may be
trying to force Obando y Bravo to step down as a member of the
Verification Commission.
   The cardinal angered the government Oct. 9 when he publicly
criticized it for rejecting humanitarian aid approved by the U.S.
Congress.
</TEXT>
