<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-88 0303EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PledgeHistory Bjt   10-17 0750</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pledge History, Bjt,0771</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pledge Of Allegiance: Socialist Wrote It, Flag-selling Magazine
Published It</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush has portrayed Boston as
a hotbed of left-wing intellectuals who don't respect rituals like
the Pledge of Allegiance. But scholars say the pledge was born here.
   What's more, the Baptist minister generally credited with
composing it was a socialist.
   ``Most people don't know anything about the history of the
pledge ... and if you tell them, they don't want to believe you,''
said Louise Harris of Providence, R.I., who has written two books
on the subject.
   The Pledge of Allegiance was surrounded by controversy and
hucksterism after it first appeared in a Boston magazine, The
Youth's Companion, on Sept. 8, 1892.
   The magazine had pioneered the sale of subscription
``premiums,'' such as school uniforms and silver tea services. But
it achieved its greatest commercial success, and its enduring
legacy, with a drive to put a flag in every school.
   The flags were priced at $3.30 to $13, depending on size. To
help schools raise the money, the magazine provided ``flag
certificates'' that pupils could sell for 10 cents apiece.
   The magazine urged schoolchildren to prepare to celebrate the
400th anniversary of Columbus' voyage to America the next month,
and even published a suggested ceremony, most involving a flag.
   Sandwiched between a presidential proclamation and an ode to
Columbus, both long forgotten, was the original pledge: ``I pledge
allegiance to my flag and to the republic for which it stands: one
nation, indivisible, with liberty and justice for all.''
   At the words ``my flag,'' the students were instructed to
stretch out their right arms to the flag, similiar to the Nazi
salute.
   It was not until 1923 that the words ``my flag'' were replaced
by ``the flag of the United States of America'' out of concern that
immigrant children might think they were pledging allegiance to
their native lands.
   Thirty-one more years passed until ``under God'' was inserted at
the the behest of President Dwight D. Eisenhower, who said that
``in this way we shall constantly strengthen those spiritual
weapons which forever will be our country's most powerful resource
in peace and war.''
   The original version of the pledge was unsigned. But once it had
caught on, competing claims to authorship quickly emerged. One
group pushed for James B. Upham, an editor of The Youth's
Companion. The other favored the Rev. Francis Bellamy, who had
served as pastor of two Boston churches before joining the
magazine's staff.
   Harris and some other scholars say Upham was the author.
   But two formal investigations _ by the U.S. Flag Association in
1939 and by the Library of Congress in 1957 _ concluded Bellamy was
responsible.
   That is now the dominant view, even though Bellamy was a vice
president of the Society of Christian Socialists and once gave a
lecture entitled ``Jesus the Socialist.'' According to his
daughter-in-law, Rachel Bellamy of Rochester, N.Y., he left the
ministry ``because he felt the church wasn't doing enough to help
the working man.''
   ``The Nationalist Movement, which he belonged to, wanted to
nationalize chunks of the American economy but have them controlled
at the municipal level,'' said researcher David Whitman of
Washington, D.C. ``He did not practice or preach violent overthrow
of the government by any means.''
   Controversy over the pledge erupted during the 1988 presidential
elections when Bush criticized his Democratic rival, Gov. Michael
Dukakis, for vetoing a 1977 bill that would have mandated that
teachers lead the students in the Pledge the beginning of every
school day.
   That wasn't the first controversy surrounding the Pledge. In the
1940s, Jehovah's Witnesses objected to reciting it in schools,
saying it violated their religious principles of pronouncing
allegiance only to God.
   The U.S. Supreme Court initially rejected their arguments,
ruling in a 1940 case that public schools could expel children who
did not recite the pledge. Then, in 1943, the court reversed itself
and said children could not be compelled to pledge.
   Meantime, Jehovah's Witnesses had been the targets of attacks in
dozens of communities. In Richwood, Va., for example, members of
the sheriff's department and American Legion forced seven members
to drink large quantities of castor oil, then tied them together
and paraded them through town.
   ``Bellamy was an avid fan of saying the pledge,'' said Whitman,
``but I can't imagine how he would have felt about it if he had
lived to see the mob violence of the '40s.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881017-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-88 0314EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Extradition     10-17 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Extradition,0530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Extradition Hearings To Begin For Accused California Mass Murderer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man wanted in California for
allegedly carrying out a string of sex slayings won't be returning
to the United States soon even though he faces extradition
proceedings, his lawyer has predicted.
   Hearings will begin today to determine whether Charles Ng,
currently serving a 4{-year jail sentence here for armed robbery,
should be extradited to the United States.
   But Ng's Calgary-based lawyer, Don MacLeod, said it could be a
long time before his 27-year-old client heads south. If Ng loses
the case, there will likely be an appeal, he said.
   Ng was convicted in Canada in December 1985 after a botched
shoplifting attempt in Calgary in which a security guard was shot
in the hand.
   But the United States wants Ng back to face 25 felony counts in
Calfornia, including the murders of 12 people. Eleven of the deaths
involved grisly sex slayings at a rural cabin in Calaveras county,
120 miles east of San Francisco.
   The other murder case involves the death of a San Francisco disc
jockey, and other charges include burglary, kidnapping and false
imprisonment.
   Ng, a native of Hong Kong and a former marine, came to Canada
after his companion, Leonard Lake, was picked up for shoplifting in
San Francisco and committed suicide.
   Lake later was linked to the deaths or disappearances of 22
people. That investigation led to the charges against Ng.
   
   If extradited and convicted, Ng faces possible execution in
California.
   Canada has a policy against extraditing anyone facing the death
penalty, but the final decision will ultimately rest with Federal
Justice Minister Ray Hnatyshyn.
   The hearings, which are being held to determine if there is
enough evidence to send Ng back to the United States, are expected
to last up to five weeks.
   Not all evidence will be available to the public. Madame Justice
Marguerite Trussler of Alberta's Court of Queen's Bench ordered in
May that anything said in open court could be reported but the
courtroom would be cleared when certain sensitive material was
discussed.
   Among observers at the hearings will be some family members of
Ng's alleged victims, who were given financial aid by the
Edmonton-based Victims of Violence for their trip.
   Sharon Sellitto, whose 39-year-old brother Paul Cosner is one of
Ng's alleged victims, said she wanted to see the accused killer for
herself.
   ``I want to hate him in person,'' Sellitto said recently from
her San Francisco home. She plans to attend the hearings.
   Allegations of torture and mass murder in the California deaths
have caused many to question Canada's extradition procedure. As
recently as May, California Gov. George Deukmejian urged Prime
Minister Brian Mulroney to speed up the process.
   In a letter, Deukmejian said denying the extradition ``could
have the unfortunate consequence of making Canada a haven for death
penalty fugitives.''
   But Ng's Calgary-based lawyer, Don MacLeod, predicted it could
be a long time before Ng heads south. Regardless of the outcome of
the extradition hearings, he said, there will likely be an appeal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
