<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-88 0335EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Soviet     10-17 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Soviet,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deng Says He Wrote Letter To Gorbachev Three Years Ago</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's senior leader Deng Xiaoping said today he
wrote a letter to Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev three years
ago and that the letter was now bearing fruit.
   Deng revealed at the beginning of a meeting with Romanian
President Nicolae Ceausescu that he had entrusted Ceausescu with
the letter, apparently calling for an improvement in Sino-Soviet
relations.
   ``You can see the letter you carried three years ago has
achieved results,'' Deng said to the Romanian president as they
posed for photographers. ``It's happening later than we thought,
but don't worry.''
   Deng also repeated his prediction, made in talks with Finnish
President Mauno Koivisto last week, that ``it is possible that next
year there could be a summit.''
   It would be the first summit between the two countries in 30
years.
   China's Foreign Minister Qian Qichen is to travel to Moscow
later this year to discuss details of the first summit since Nikita
Khrushchev visited Beijing in 1959.
   The first foreign minister working-level talks since 1956 are
expected to focus on the Cambodian question, the last major
stumbling block to normalizing relations strained by an ideological
split in 1960.
   China has demanded that Moscow use its influence to force
Vietnam to withdraw its troops from Cambodia. The Soviet Union is
Vietnam's main financial backer and arms supplier.
   Ceausescu, who last met Deng in October 1985, said it ``doesn't
matter'' that the rapprochement process between Moscow and Beijing
has been slow. ``History is long and the route we are taking is
long.''
   China has insisted that Deng, and not the Soviets, first
suggested the holding of a summit, although Gorbachev has grabbed
the initiative in recent years by saying he was ready to meet
Chinese leaders without any pre-conditions.
   Ceausescu told Deng he had visited Moscow the previous week
``and now I convey greetings to you from Gorbachev.''
   Deng replied, ``you can also convey my greetings to Gorbachev.''
   Romania's position as a independent maverick among the Warsaw
Pact has contributed to Ceausescu's acting as an intermediary
between disputing nations. Romania was the only Soviet-bloc country
to maintain normal political and party-to-party ties with China
after the split between Moscow and Beijing.
   He is currently making his sixth visit to China.
</TEXT>
