<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     10-17 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0214</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Plunges, Then Breaks Its Fall; Stocks Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar opened sharply lower against the
Japanese yen today but recovered some of the loss before closing
time, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange eased slightly.
   The dollar closed at 127.20 yen, 1.05 yen lower than its close
Friday. It began trading today at 126.30 and moved in a wide range
of 126.25 and 127.50 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues closed 37.83
points lower at 27,268.74. The 0.14 percent drop erased the
Nikkei's morning gain of 53.72 points in thin, directionless
trading. Volume on the main first section was a light 400 million
shares.
   Currency dealers attributed the dollar's partial recovery to the
market's wariness about the speed of its recent decline. Following
setbacks on world markets last week, the U.S. currency opened today
at 126.30 yen, its lowest starting level since the 125.84 yen
opening recorded June 20.
   ``The dollar was bought back at a considerable amount by
Japanese investors,'' said Shinya Hirota of the Bank of Tokyo.
   On the stock exchange, the Nikkei seesawed in a narrow range
amid lackluster trading. Dealers said a lack of incentives was
keeping market players on the sidelines.
</TEXT>
