<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Brite--WeddingBells     10-17 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brite--Wedding Bells,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Housing Crackdown May Lead Tenants' Lovers to the Altar</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Men who found themselves barred from staying at
their girlfriends' housing project homes because of a curfew on
visitors say they may have to get married to beat the ban.
   The Chicago Housing Authority instituted the ban last month and
employed guards around the clock at the Rockwell Gardens
development to reclaim the building from marauding gang members.
   Residents who are on the lease must show housing authority
identity cards to enter and leave the 138-unit building on
Chicago's West Side. Visitors must leave by midnight, and that
includes men who live with their girlfriends.
   When the ban went into effect in September, Patrick Page boarded
himself up in his girlfriend's apartment and has refused to answer
the door.
   ``It's been like a prison,'' said Page, who has not left the
building since Sept. 20. ``The only difference is, they don't bring
your food up.''
   Like a few other men in the building, Page said the eviction of
non-leaseholders has accelerated his plans to marry the woman he's
been living with for three years.
   ``We had a serious talk and decided to get married,'' said Page,
24, whose girlfriend is pregnant with their second child.
   Greg Johnson, 24, also has been hiding in his girlfriend's
apartment since the Sept. 20 crackdown. He's still pondering what
to do: get married, stay in hiding or leave and run the risk of
being homeless.
   ``Hopefully, these guys who are hiding and ducking and dodging
may be able to step forward and be men,'' said Vincent Lane,
chairman of the housing authority.
</TEXT>
