<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-88 0523EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Flooding     10-17 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Flooding,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dozens Evacuated in Washington State Flooding</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SULTAN, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unseasonably heavy rains flooded much of
western Washington, forced about 45 people to be evacuated from
homes and campgrounds, and stranded two hikers shivering under a
tree for a night.
   ``We had just about lost hope. We thought we were going to die
out there,'' said Steve Winsel, 28, of Fairfield, Calif., who was
hiking with his 30-year-old brother, Mike, of Everett.
   Rain tapered off and floodwaters were receding late Sunday in
the Cascade Mountains foothills east of Seattle, but more rain was
predicted for tonight and early Tuesday with the approach of
another storm system, the National Weather Service said.
   The Winsels were trapped in the Vesper Peak area about 20 miles
south of Sultan, a town of 1,500 residents 30 miles northeast of
Seattle. The brothers were dressed in boots and jackets and had
some food, but said it was icy cold and only one of them had gloves.
   ``We were awake all night shivering,'' Steve Winsel said. ``In
the morning, we tried to return on the logging road, but we found
the (Skykomish) river had risen overnight and had wiped out the
road in three places.''
   The only bridge they found was impassable, so the brothers had
to swim across the river, where they were picked up by a truck
driver and taken back to Sultan.
   ``We probably wouldn't have been able to survive if we'd have
stayed outdoors another night,'' Steve Winsel said.
   ``We'd already spent 24 hours in hell.''
   The Skykomish crested in Sultan on Sunday three feet above flood
stage, Fire Chief Roger Knowlton said.
   About 15 residents had to be evacuated by boat from the town
Sunday morning, according to Karl Christian, a dispatch supervisor
for the Snohomish County sheriff's office. Residents were allowed
to return home Sunday night.
   Red Cross volunteers fed 30 people and arranged for emergency
housing after evacuating them from trailers in the Snoqualmie River
Campground on Sunday, said relief worker Hope Tuttle. The contents
of two or three trailers were believed destroyed, she said.
   The Skagit and Stillaguamish rivers also reached flood stage at
upper elevations Sunday, the weather service reported. A flood
warning for the Nooksack River was canceled late Sunday.
   The floodwaters closed numerous roads throughout the Cascade
foothills. No damage estimate was immediately available.
   Heavy rain washed enough logging debris down the Skagit River to
cause a partial dam to form at a Burlington Northern railroad
bridge, but no major problems were anticipated, said Tom Sheahan,
management director of the Skagit County Department of Emergency
Services.
   During the 48 hours ending at 5 p.m. Sunday, the weather service
reported 1.64 inches of rain in Bellingham, 1.39 in Olympia, 1.04
at Seattle-Tacoma International Airport _ and 6.25 at Stampede
Pass, just south of Snoqualmie Pass and about 50 miles
south-southeast of Seattle.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
