<HEAD>Thunderstorms Lash Midwest, Southwest; Flooding in Washington</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms that lashed the nation's midsection and the
Sunbelt with hail and high winds weakened early today, while
unseasonably heavy rains in Washington state caused flooding that
forced dozens of evacuations.
   Showers and a few thunderstorms extended across western Lake
Erie and northwestern Ohio into central Indiana early this morning,
but there were no reports of severe weather since dime-size hail
pelted northeastern Indiana on Sunday.
   In western Washington, another storm system was expected to
bring rain tonight and early Tuesday. Flooding on Sunday prompted
the evacuation of about 45 people from homes in Snohomish County
and a campground in King County.
   No damage estimates were immediately available while the waters
of the Snoqualmie, Skykomish, Skagit and Stillaguamish rivers were
still receding late Sunday.
   In Arizona, a series of thunderstorms abated today after
producing one-inch hail along with high winds, knocking down trees
and power lines in the town of Bisbee on Sunday. The storms also
produced local flooding.
   Showers were scattered from northern Idaho across southern South
Dakota into northwestern Illinois early this morning. Other showers
continued over North Dakota and the Tennessee Valley.
   Dense fog developed in Rhode Island and along the coast of
southern California. Generally fair skies prevailed across the rest
of the nation.
   Today's forecast called for rainshowers from the upper
Mississippi Valley through the Great Lakes region; scattered
showers and thunderstorms over the Ohio Valley, the middle
Mississippi Valley, eastern Oklahoma, the lower Great Lakes and the
central and northern Appalachians; and cloudy skies with widely
scattered showers over parts of the Pacific Northwest.
   High temperatures were expected in the 40s over eastern North
Dakota and northern Minnesota; the 50s from northern Washington
State through the northern Rockies and northern Plains into upper
Michigan, and in northern Maine; the 80s across the central and
southern Pacific Coast through the southern Rockies, the southern
Plains and the Gulf Coast states into Florida; the 90s over the
northern California valleys, inland southern California and the
Southwest desert southwest; and the 60s and 70s across the rest of
the nation.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 35
degrees at Hibbing, Minn., to 78 degrees at Phoenix.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 56 fair; Boston 50 foggy; Buffalo 58 partly
cloudy; Charleston, S.C. 56 foggy; Cincinnati 58 hazy; Cleveland 58
showery; Detroit 57 foggy; Miami 71 fair; New York 59 foggy;
Philadelphia 53 fair; Pittsburgh 51 fair; Portland, Maine 53 foggy;
Washington 55 partly cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 47 cloudy; Chicago 51 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
69 fair; Denver 54 partly cloudy; Des Moines 55 partly cloudy;
Indianapolis 59 cloudy; Kansas City 67 windy; Minneapolis-St. Paul
46 cloudy; Nashville 60 fair; New Orleans 59 fair; St. Louis 65
partly cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 56 fair; Anchorage 30 cloudy; Las Vegas 66
fair; Los Angeles 64 foggy; Phoenix 79 partly cloudy; Salt Lake
City 59 fair; San Diego 63 foggy; San Francisco 65 fair; Seattle 50
partly cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 55 fair; Toronto 57 cloudy.
