<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthAfrica-Botha     10-17 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-Botha,0593</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pro-Government Press Hails Botha's Trip As Breakthrough</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pro-government newspapers
today hailed President P.W. Botha's trip to Europe and the Ivory
Coast as a rousing success although no agreements were announced
and Botha declined to divulge details.
   Botha returned Sunday following a 10-day trip, the latest in a
series of foreign journeys aimed at easing the country's diplomatic
isolation.
   Botha attended the funeral of Bavarian governor Franz Josef
Strauss in West Germany, then went to Switzerland where he met with
bankers and businessmen.
   En route back to South Africa, Botha stopped briefly Saturday in
Portugal and the Ivory Coast. In Portugal, Botha met with Prime
Minister Anibal Cavaco Silva, and in the Ivory Coast with President
Felix Houphouet-Boigny.
   According to the French news agency Agence France-Presse, Botha
made a brief statement in the Ivory Coast, saying his conversations
with Houphouet covered African problems in general and southern
Africa in particular, but he did not elaborate.
   ``It is always a privilege to meet him,'' Botha said of
Houphouet according to the AFP report. ``We didn't want to pass by
without stopping in this country of goodwill.''
   None of the officials who met Botha have issued public
statements regarding the talks.
   The Ivory Coast stopover marked Botha's fourth visit to a
black-ruled African country since mid-September. Botha declined to
discuss the specifics of his talks with Houphouet-Boigny, one of
Africa's longest-serving leaders.
   ``We discussed matters concerning Africa and especially southern
Africa. We decided not to make statements,'' Botha said.
   The Citizen, a pro-government newspaper, said Botha's recent
travels have focused world attention onto South Africa.
   ``At a time when one might have expected the world to
demonstrate an obsession with the American presidential election,
the spotlight has instead been turned on South Africa,'' the
newspaper said today in an editorial.
   The Afrikaans-language daily Beeld said: ``What clearly began as
a visit to pay homage to a dead friend (Strauss) turned into a
noteworthy trip. ... Perhaps these moves could be followed up by
one or two dramatic developments internally that will show the
world that we are earnest about reform.''
   The newspaper suggested the government could release jailed
African National Congress leader Nelson Mandela and scrap pending
legislation designed to strengthen the Group Areas Act, which
segregates neighborhoods by race.
   The government-run South African Broadcasting Corp. said Botha's
travels herald a ``fundamental change'' in South Africa's
relationship with the rest of the continent.
   ``By the end of last week even the most hardened cynics were
having to concede that a new spirit of conciliation was abroad,''
the SABC said.
   Botha, who has held power since 1978, never held a summit
meeting in a black-ruled African nation until he traveled to
Mozambique last month. He also has visited Malawi and Zaire in
recent weeks.
   South Africa says Presidents Joaquim Chissano of Mozambique and
Mobutu Sese Seko of Zaire are likely to visit South Africa in
coming months.
   The Citizen, quoting unidentified government officials, said
there was a ``possibility'' that Botha would meet with Angolan
President Eduardo dos Santos.
   South Africa in August withdrew its troops from Angola, where
they fought alongside the anti-Marxist UNITA rebels.
   South Africa and Angola, along with Cuba and U.S. mediators,
have been attempting to negotiate an agreement on the withdrawal of
50,000 Cuban troops supporting the Angolan government and
independence for South-West Africa, the territory ruled by South
Africa.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
