<2ND_LINE>PM-Northern Ireland, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0493,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Car Bomb Planted By IRA Kills A Man</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout with IRA claiming responsibility, saying
victim supplied materials to security forces, other details. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The IRA said it planted a car
bomb that killed a man early today as he was driving near Belfast.
   The Irish Republican Army said in a statement to the news media
that Norman McKeown, 39, died because he worked for a company that
did building maintenance for the Royal Ulster Constabulary,
Northern Ireland's security forces.
   McKeown, sales manager for James Anderson Ltd., had driven about
200 yards from his home in Dundonald, just east of Belfast, when a
two-pound bomb attached to his car blew up, police said.
   McKeown's wife, who was in the car at the time of the explosion,
was treated in a hospital for minor injuries and released,
according to a police spokesman. He spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The IRA said the company supplied security window shutters and
fireproof materials to police stations and British army bases
throughout Northern Ireland and to court buildings in Belfast.
   The firm also did maintenance work at the Belfast-area offices
of Northern Ireland Secretary Tom King, the IRA said. King is the
British Cabinet minister responsible for Northern Ireland.
   The IRA statement said McKeown was ``an associate'' of the
Ulster Volunteer Force, an outlawed Protestant group.
   ``The (Ulster Volunteer Force) with the active cooperation of
management, which included Norman McKeown, have been using
Anderson's premises ... for the storage of weapons and munitions,''
the statement said.
   The IRA alleged James Anderson had continued to do work for the
security forces despite repeated warnings to stop.
   The IRA's campaign to stop construction work for the security
forces began in August 1985 when a supplier of portable structures
to replace bombed buildings was shot and killed in his Dublin home.
Since then, several other contractors have been killed.
   The outlawed Irish Republican Army is fighting to end British
rule in the predominantly Protestant province and unite it with the
mainly Roman Catholic Republic of Ireland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
