<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDS-Fathers 1stLd-Writethru a0457 10-17 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS-Fathers, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0457,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AIDS Victims' Sperm Is Free Of Virus</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to add full name of school.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Men with the AIDS virus have AIDS-free sperm,
raising the possibility that infected males may be able to father
children through artificial insemination without passing the
disease to the fetus, researchers say.
   Dr. Bernard Poiesz and colleagues at the State University of New
York Health Science Center at Syracuse found that the AIDS virus is
present in the seminal fluid in which the sperm is suspended but
not in the sperm cells themselves, The New York Times reported
today.
   Poiesz and researchers at the University of Southern California
working independently found that most men with AIDS do not even
have the virus in their semen, the Times said.
   Researchers are baffled by this finding because theoretically,
if AIDS is present in the blood, it should be present in semen,
since that fluid contains the white cells that the virus attacks.
   Poiesz reported the virus is present in about 20 percent of the
semen samples of infected men, while the virus is present in
virtually 100 percent of their blood samples.
   In contrast, several years ago Poiesz detected AIDS in 70
percent of semen samples from infected men.
   Dr. Suraiya Rasheed of USC also reported that researchers in her
laboratory were no longer able to detect the AIDS virus in most
semen samples from men whose blood samples show an infection rate
of virtually 100 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
