<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TropicalWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0504 10-17 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tropical Weather, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0504,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Joan Strengthens Over Colombian Peninsula _ Bound For Open Water</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `At 6...', to UPDATE with 9 a.m. advisory.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tropical Storm Joan's winds strengthened to 60 mph
today as it skimmed over the Colombian peninsula on a westward path
back out over the warm waters of the Caribbean, forecasters say.
   ``This storm has defied what it's supposed to do,'' said Miles
Lawrence, a forecaster at the National Hurricane Center in Miami.
``Any storm that passes that close to land should be weakening, not
strengthening.''
   At 9 a.m. EDT today, Joan's center was located near latitude
12.0 north and longitude 72.1 west, putting it over the Guajira
Peninsula of Colombia. The storm was moving west near 12 mph on a
path that would take it over the southwestern Caribbean Sea later
today.
   Although little additional strengthening was expected today,
Lawrence said the storm could become more powerful during the next
day or two as it moved over warm water.
   Joan, whose winds diminished Sunday to 45 mph, roared back to 60
mph today with gale-force gusts extending 50 miles. Four to 8
inches of rain was recorded along the storm's path.
   Tropical storm warnings remained in effect for the Guajira
Peninsula and Venezuela's Paraguana Peninsula and Monjes Islands.
Small craft in the area were asked to remain in port.
   On Tuesday, Joan became the 10th named system of the 1988
Atlantic hurricane season when top winds passed 39 mph. It would be
upgraded to a hurricane if its winds hit 74 mph.
   There have been four hurricanes during the six-month season that
ends Nov. 30. The worst was Hurricane Gilbert, which killed more
than 300 people and caused billions of dollars damage as it tore
through Jamaica, the Cayman Islands and Mexico's Yucatan peninsula.
</TEXT>
