<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Vietnam-SiameseTwins     10-17 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vietnam-Siamese Twins,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Separated 7-Year_Old Siamese Twins Recovering</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Siamese twins Viet and Duc were recovering well
today, 13 days after they were separated in an operation at a
Vietnamese hospital, a Japanese Red Cross official said.
   Yoshiaki Nemoto quoted Yoji Araki, a Japanese doctor observing
the Vietnamese boys at Tu Du hospital in Ho Chi Minh City, as
saying the twins were doing ``very well.''
   Viet and Duc were separated Oct. 4 by a 72-member Vietnamese
medical team and have recovered without complications, Nemoto
quoted Araki as saying.
   The 7-year-old Vietnamese boys are believed to be the oldest
Siamese twins ever separated.
   Viet and Duc were joined at the pelvis and shared genitals and a
single pair of legs, as well as one bowel, an anus, a bladder and a
pair of kidneys.
   The Japan Red Cross donated most of the medical equipment and
medicine for the operation.
   Vietnamese officials have attributed the reported increase in
births of Siamese twins in Vietnam to the U.S. use of defoliants
during the Vietnam War, including in the central highlands where
Viet and Duc were born in February 1981.
   The defoliants included Agent Orange, which contains a compound,
dioxin, known to produce birth defects in animals.
</TEXT>
