<HEAD>Fraternity Apologizes For `Ghetto Party,' Faces Disciplinary
Proceedings</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>GREENCASTLE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An all-white DePauw University
fraternity that held a ``ghetto party'' has apologized for
decorating its house with racist graffiti that offended black
guests and led to a protest march.
   University President Robert G. Bottoms said the Alpha Tau Omega
fraternity house will face disciplinary proceedings that could lead
to punishment. Five other fraternities and sororities that
co-sponsored the party also face action.
   ``Certainly, the administration doesn't support or condone any
behavior that's offensive to our minority students, and we'll do
everything to get to the bottom of it,'' Bottoms said.
   The graffiti included disparaging remarks about blacks, the Rev.
Jesse Jackson and South Africa. In addition, some partygoers wore
black face and dressed as pimps and prostitutes.
   ``We now understand that the events in question were done in
poor taste,'' said fraternity president Jay Hoffman. ``The
decorations in question contained expressions that do not reflect
the opinions of any member of this living unit.''
   ``We are very, very sorry,'' he said. ``We feel great remorse
because of this.''
   The fraternity has no black members, but Hoffman said today that
it has no policy excluding blacks.
   Several black students who attended the party Friday found the
graffiti offensive, said officials at the private school that has
fewer than 5,000 students.
   During halftime of DePauw's homecoming football game Saturday,
members of the Association of Afro-American Students held a silent
march carrying signs protesting the party in front of students and
alumi.
   Following the game, more than 200 people, including Bottoms,
marched around the campus to the six fraternities and sororities
involved, peacefully protesting and singing ``We Shall Overcome.''
</TEXT>
