<2ND_LINE>PM-Barricaded Nuns,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five Rebel Nuns Continue Their Vigil, Await News From Rome</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORRIS TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five nuns who have spent nearly two
weeks barricaded inside the infirmary of their monastery to protest
modernization have called off talks with a priest sent by the
Vatican to end the impasse.
   The nuns rejected the Rev. Kevin Culligan, a friar from
Wisconsin, on Sunday because of his friendship with the monastery's
prioress, against whom they are rebelling, said Sister Bernadette,
one of the protesting nuns.
   They also challenge his legitimacy because he failed to show a
Vatican seal on his credentials, the nuns said. Talks Saturday
produced no agreement.
   ``He said he came here to assess whether this is an authentic
Carmelite monastery,'' Sister Bernadette said. ``We kept telling
him we have a case in Rome.''
   The Carmelite nuns today entered their 14th day in
self-segregation. Their actions have brought international
attention to the Roman Catholic Monastery of the Most Blessed
Virgin Mary of Mount Carmel.
   On Oct. 4, the five sisters of the Order of Discalced Carmelites
isolated themselves in the monastery's infirmary.
   They say they acted out of fear that the Diocese of Paterson
would evict them. The five oppose liberalization efforts that
include the introduction of sweets, radio and television that they
say detract from the life of prayer and austerity they vowed to
lead.
   They have said they will not give up their vigil until their
case is considered by the Vatican in Rome, which under canon law is
the official arbitrator in disputes within a religious order.
   Bishop Frank Rodimer, head of the diocese, has said the nuns
could be relieved of their vows for their defiance.
</TEXT>
