<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Scientologists     10-17 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Scientologists,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court to hear Appeal in California Case on Tax-Fraud
Investigations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to hear a
Reagan administration appeal aimed at making it easier for the
government to conduct tax-fraud investigations.
   The justices said they will use a California case involving the
Church of Scientology to settle a dispute over the power of the
Internal Revenue Service to obtain and use confidential documents,
particularly communications between lawyers and clients.
   The government, which has had numerous legal battles with the
Scientologists, began an investigation in 1984 of the tax returns
of the church's founder, L. Ron Hubbard, who died on Jan. 24, 1986.
   The IRS said it suspected that millions of dollars in church
funds were transferred to Hubbard in the late 1970s and early 1980s
in a scheme to protect the church's tax-exempt status and avoid
paying taxes on the money.
   The IRS issued a summons in October 1984 for 13 confidential
documents held by a California state court in connection with a
private lawsuit involving the church.
   A federal judge ruled that five of the documents should be
turned over to the IRS but only on condition the IRS not disclose
the contents to any other governmental agency except in connection
with a criminal tax prosecution.
   The judge blocked the IRS from obtaining the other eight
documents, particularly taped conversations of confidential
lawyer-client communications.
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld the judge's ruling
in 1986.
   The appeals court said barring the IRS from turning over
documents to other agencies is a ``wise exercise of control'' by
the courts to protect the rights of citizens.
   The appeals court also said the government is not entitled to
see attorney-client communications unless it can produce
independent evidence that the lawyer is taking part in a fraud.
   The Justice Department, appealing on behalf of the IRS, proposed
that a federal judge examine the confidential documents to
determine whether there is evidence of fraud.
   The department said the appeals court ruling will
``significantly impair IRS investigations'' because ``the actual
contents of an attorney-client communication will often be the best
evidence'' of whether a lawyer has participated in fraud.
   The department also said the 9th Circuit court ruling is in
conflict with decisions by other federal appeals courts. The 9th
Circuit has jurisdiction in Arizona, Alaska, California, Hawaii,
Idaho, Montana, Nevada, Oregon and Washington.
   The case is U.S. vs. Zolin, 88-40.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
