<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Scarfo     10-17 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Scarfo,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reputed Philadelphia-Area Crime Boss Loses Appeal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reputed Philadelphia-area crime boss Nicodemo
Scarfo lost a Supreme Court appeal today to overturn his
extortion-conspiracy conviction.
   The court, without comment, rejected arguments that Scarfo did
not receive a fair trial.
   Scarfo, described as the head of organized crime in eastern
Pennsylvania and parts of New Jersey, is serving a 14-year prison
term for scheming to extort $1 million from a developer of the
Penn's Landing redevelopment project on the Philadelphia waterfront.
   The developer, Rouse & Associates, told the FBI of the extortion
plan that called for it to pay $1 million in exchange for backing
from Philadelphia city Councilman Leland Beloff for the project.
   Beloff and his administrative aide, Robert Rego, were tried
separately and convicted in the kickback scheme.
   Scarfo said he did not receive a fair trial in part because the
jurors' names were withheld when they were selected. They were
identified only by number.
   Also, the trial judge in explaining the reason for the anonymity
told the jurors he wanted to assure them that they or their
families had no reason to fear.
   ``There will be a lot of testimony concerning organized crime,''
the judge said. ``I have never heard of a case where any defendant
ever tried to cause harm to a juror or a member of the juror's
family. But we all watch television. We all read newspapers. We see
the Godfather movies. I wanted to make sure that no member of the
jury would worry about it.''
   Also, Scarfo said the jury was influenced improperly by
testimony about extraneous crimes presented with ``frightening
imagery and detail.''
   For example, the prosecutor summed up the case by saying Scarfo
``is a shrewd, clever and dangerous man. He rules his criminal army
with a deadly iron fist. He keeps his soldiers in mortal fear.''
   The 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld the conviction last
July.
   The appeals court said anonymity for the jurors and the
explanation the trial judge gave for the procedure may have helped
dispel the jurors' fears and served ``the ideal of dispassionate
judgment.''
   The appeals court also upheld the use of testimony by mob hit
men who testified for the government that they carried out murders
at Scarfo's behest.
   The prosecution used the testimony to try and prove that the
witnesses cooperated with the government for fear they would meet
the same fate, the appeals court said.
   The case is Scarfo vs. U.S., 88-498.
</TEXT>
