<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0506 10-17 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0506,0574</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede JERUSALEM</HEAD>
<HEAD>Peres Proposes Elections In Occupied Territories</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Peres proposing elections in
West Bank and Gaza, eight Palestinians wounded in clashes. Edits to
trim. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Labor Party leader Shimon Peres today
proposed elections in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip to
select Palestinians who would negotiate peace with Israel.
   The call was part of a policy statement issued by Peres and
Labor's Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin in the campaign for Israel's
general elections Nov. 1.
   Polls indicate Labor and the governing Likud bloc are running
neck-and-neck.
   In the occupied Gaza Strip today, troops shot and wounded eight
Palestinians, including two 13-year-old boys, during clashes in the
towns of Rafah and Khan Yunis, hospital officials said.
   On Sunday, Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, head of the Likud
bloc, vowed that ``nothing will remain'' of Palestinians who carry
out threats to use firearms against Israel.
   Peres and Rabin told reporters today that any Palestinian living
in the occupied territories should be permitted to run in
elections, even if they supported the banned Palestine Liberation
Organization.
   The Labor leaders said a cessation of anti-Israeli violence for
a period of three to six months was a precondition for such
elections.
   ``If the violence is restrained, we will hold free elections in
Judea, Samaria and Gaza so that a Palestinian ... delegation can be
elected (to) represent the Palestinian side in negotiations,''
Peres said, using the biblical names for the West Bank.
   He said that if efforts to arrange formal peace negotiations
fail, a Labor-led government would transfer control of municipal
and local affairs to elected leaders from the territories, with the
Israeli army only in charge of security. The army now runs daily
municipal affairs in the occupied lands.
   Elections were last held in the West Bank in 1976, when mayors
were chosen in major towns and cities. The officials all supported
the PLO and refused to act as representatives in peace negotiations.
   Shamir made his remark against Palestinian use of firearms
Sunday to more than 2,000 supporters in the southern town of
Sderot, according to his spokesman, Yossi Ahimeir.
   Ahimeir said Shamir was responding to Arab news reports that
Hani Hassan, an aide to PLO chief Yasser Arafat, had said
Palestinians would exchange their stone-throwing methods against
Israeli troops for firearms if Shamir is re-elected prime minister.
   ``If the Arabs of Judea, Samaria and Gaza start fighting the
army with firearms, nothing will remain of those terrorists, and
there is no doubt that an end will come to the intefadeh (Arabic
for uprising),'' Shamir said, according to Ahimeir.
   So far, Palestinians have primarily confronted Israeli troops
and civilians with stones, bottles and firebombs.
   However, the recent use of firearms by Palestinians included two
grenades hurled at army vehicles in Gaza last week, injuring two
soldiers.
   The 10-month-old Palestinian uprising against Israel, in which
299 Arabs have been killed and about 7,000 wounded, has emerged as
the primary issue in the national elections. Six Israelis have been
killed in the unrest.
   Army figures show 896 Israelis have been injured in the
rebellion, including 575 troops and 321 civilians, Israel radio
reported.
   The Likud bloc opposes withdrawal from the lands Israel captured
in the 1967 Middle East War.
</TEXT>
