<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Nobel-USReax 2ndLd-Writethru a0557 10-17 0729</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nobel-US Reax, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0557,0741</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Winner More Disbelieving Than Surprised</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with comment from Hitchings,
picking up 4th graf pvs, `The work...'. INSERTS 2 grafs after 15th
graf, `The drugs...', with further background.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Nobel, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A researcher who shared the Nobel Prize for
medicine today said the best reward is still knowing his work has
saved lives, while his longtime colleague says she was more
disbelieving than anything after journalists gave her the news.
   ``The phone keeps ringing and I can't seem to finish getting
dressed or anything else,'' said Gertrude Elion, a researcher at
Burroughs Wellcome Co. since 1944, from her home in Chapel Hill.
``I think I'm going to have trouble getting to work on time.''
   Elion, 70; George H. Hitchings, 83, another longtime Wellcome
researcher; and a British scientist shared the award and will split
a prize worth $390,000.
   ``It's wonderful for my descendents,'' joked Hitchings, a former
Burroughs Wellcome vice president. ``I've had many awards, but my
real awards have come from patients whose lives have been saved by
the drugs I've invented.''
   The work of Elion and Hitchings led to a series of drugs for the
treatment of cancer and a variety of other diseases. Burroughs
Wellcome is a major pharmaceutical company.
   Elion said she first got the news at 6:30 a.m. from a reporter
and had not yet heard from Nobel officials.
   ``Surprised is not exactly the word,'' she said, when asked her
reaction to the prize. ``Disbelieving is the right word. As I say,
I haven't heard from the Nobel people, and until they confirm it, I
won't believe it. I did not even know I had been nominated for it.''
   She said a reporter had read her parts of the citation, ``but it
was fairly vague. I don't even know exactly what the award is for
at this point.''
   She said she had collaborated with Hitchings for more than 40
years.
   ``That's why it's so surprising when something like this happens
after so many years,'' she said.
   ``I haven't been able to use the phone to call him,'' she said
of Hitchings. ``But other people who have called have told me they
talked to him, so I know he knows about it. I think I'll have to go
use a phone somewhere else, but first I've got to run a comb
through my hair.''
   Hitchings, who was born in Hoquiam, Wash., received a doctorate
in biochemistry from Harvard in 1933 and holds more than 80
American patents. He joined Burroughs Wellcome in 1942 as a
biochemist and retired in 1975 as vice president for research.
   Elion, a native of New York City, received a bachelor's degree
from Hunter College in 1937, and a master's degree in chemistry
from New York University in 1941. She joined Burroughs Wellcome in
1944 as a biochemist. In 1967, she was appointed head of the
department of experimental therapy, a position she held until her
retirment in 1983.
   Hitchings and Elion followed a line of nucleic acid research
that led to the discovery of new drugs for malaria, leukemia, gout,
bacterial infections and the first immune suppressant to make
kidney transplants possible, the company said.
   The drugs developed by the two scientists include Imuran, for
kidney transplants; Purinethol, a cancer drug used to treat
leukemia patients; Zyloprim, for gout; and Zovirax, the first drug
developed for the treatment of herpes virus infections, said
Burroughs Wellcome spokeswoman Kathy Bartlett.
   The researchers hold the title of scientist emeritus at
Burroughs Wellcome, signifying that they are retired. Despite their
retirement, both have continued to work on projects, said another
company spokesman, Thack Brown.
   ``Both of them still come to work every day,'' Brown said.
``They both have their own research projects, but they were so
involved in so many things that were going on in research that
they're still consulted.''
   This is the third Nobel Prize for Burroughs Wellcome, Ms.
Bartlett said.
   In 1936, Sir Henry Dale, an early director of research and
chairman of the Wellcome Trust, was awarded a Nobel in medicine for
his studies of chemical transmission of nerve impulses. In 1982,
Sir John Vane, group research and development director, won a Nobel
in medicine for his role in discovering the way in which aspirin
works to reduce pain and inflammation.
</TEXT>
