<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChristianCenterDeath     10-17 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Christian Center Death,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State To Seek Continued Custody Of Children</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE SCHULA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OREGON CITY, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifty-nine children found crowded in a
four-bedroom farmhouse should remain in state custody while
authorities investigate the beating death of an 8-year-old girl,
officials said.
   Four people have been charged with murder in the death of Dayna
Lorea Broussard, the daughter of the founder of a Los Angeles-based
Christian center established to train and discipline inner-city
youngsters.
   George Coleman, chief deputy state medical examiner, said Sunday
the girl had been ``whipped severely'' and suffered fatal
``blunt-force injuries.''
   There also was evidence of an old injury on her body, Coleman
said.
   Police said several adults from the rural home near Sandy, which
once served as the headquarters for the now-defunct Ecclesia
Athletic Association, brought the dead child to a fire station 25
miles east of Portland early Friday.
   Investigators later found the other children in the four-bedroom
farmhouse, some with scars that might indicate physical abuse, said
sheriff's Capt. Pat Detloff.
   The children, ranging in age from 1{ months to 16 years, were
hungry but otherwise healthy, according to officials who admitted
them to state juvenile facilities over the weekend. All reportedly
were from Los Angeles.
   ``Based on everything we know right now, we'll recommend
continued (state) custody,'' said Bart Wilson, a branch manager of
the state Children's Services Division.
   The division planned to ask authorities to approve the custody
extension at a juvenile court hearing in Oregon City this afternoon.
   ``We've had little contact with the parents,'' Wilson said.
``We've not heard from very many of them.''
   The father of the dead girl, Eldridge Broussard Jr., leader of
the Watts Christian Center, arrived from Los Angeles and was
interviewed Sunday by sheriff's investigators.
   Broussard, 35, has said that his group has been trying to
promote spiritual and moral values through athletics, but has
complained that the media have portrayed him as a ``crackpot.''
   Last year, Ecclesia officials claimed to have established a camp
at the Sandy site to train children for the Olympics. But it was
unclear if the children found last week were engaged in a similar
training program.
   Charged with murder in the girl's death were Brian James
Brinson, 30; Constance Zipporah Jackson, 37; Frederick Paul
Doolittle, 28; and Willie K. Chambers, 35, all of Los Angeles. They
remain in custody in the county jail.
   Two other adults connected with Broussard's group were charged
with hindering prosecution and were jailed pending $100,000 bail
each.
</TEXT>
