<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Afghanistan 2ndLd-Writethru a0508 10-17 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghanistan, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0508,0544</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrilla Says Soviets Want Direct Talks; Afghanistan Says
Americans Killed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4 grafs for grafs 10-12 pvs to ADD background on
Americans killed in earlier attacks and Soviet charges of U.S.
assistance; PICKS up 13th graf pvs, `The Pakistani ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Afghan guerrilla leader said today
the Soviet Union wants direct talks with the Moslem forces fighting
the Moscow-backed Afghan government. Official Afghan radio said
troops killed two Americans who were helping guerrillas.
   ``The green lights have been shown'' for direct negotiations,
said Burhanuddin Rabbani, current chairman of a seven-party Afghan
guerrilla alliance headquartered in Peshawar, Pakistan. He did not
elaborate.
   ``The negotiations and how they will happen will be seen in the
future,'' Rabbani told reporters after returning from a five-week
trip to northern Afghanistan.
   No comment to the report was immediately available from the
Soviet Union.
   In negotiating a U.N.-mediated agreement in April to withdraw
Soviet troops, Moscow did not meet with the U.S.-backed guerrillas
and spoke instead with Pakistani officials.
   Rabbani ruled out any coalition government that included
communists but he said there was room in a guerrilla-controlled
government for ``some elements from Kabul.''
   ``Non-communist elements working in Kabul could be included,''
he said.
   Official Radio Kabul on Sunday did not identify the Americans
reportedly killed in the attack a day earlier, but a Western
diplomat in Islamabad denied U.S. citizens were in Afghanistan on
government business. The broadcast contended the Americans were
helping the guerrillas.
   The diplomat, speaking on condition of anonymity, said he had
heard nothing of American citizens being killed in Afghanistan.
   Soviet officials often have alleged that U.S. personnel trains
guerrilla forces near the Afghan border in Pakistan. American
reporters often travel to the Afghan capital, Kabul, and to other
areas.
   Radio Kabul, in a broadcast monitored in Islamabad, said the
Americans and two Pakistani officers died Saturday when government
forces attacked Moslem guerrilla positions near Gardez city, about
60 miles southeast of Kabul.
   In Washington, State Department spokeswoman Nancy Beck said she
knew nothing of the report and said she could not even say whether
any Americans were in Afghanistan.
   In recent years, three Americans have been killed in Afghanistan
_ Charles Thornton, a reporter for the Arizona Republic newspaper,
and independent filmmakers Lee Shapiro of North Bergen, N.J., and
Jim Landiloff of Sacramento, Calif.
   The Pakistani government had no immediate comment on the report.
   In other developments, the Afghan Foreign Ministry sent its
100th note of protest alleging Pakistani violations of the
U.N.-mediated agreement aimed at ending the fighting in
Afghanistan, Tass said.
   The accord, signed April 14 in Geneva, requires the Soviet Union
to withdraw its armed forces from Afghanistan by February. The
Soviets say half of their more than 100,000 troops are back home.
   The Soviets and the Afghans accuse Pakistan of violating the
agreement by allowing its territory to be used as a base by
U.S.-backed rebel groups and by permitting arms and munitions to
cross Pakistan to the insurgents.
   The Soviets intervened in Afghanistan in December 1979 to
preside over the replacement of one Marxist ruler by another and
stayed on to fight the insurgency.
</TEXT>
