<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WyoFires-Claims     10-17 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wyo Fires-Claims,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Claim Filed Over Yellowstone Fire Damage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who lost a cabin to
this summer's fires in the Yellowstone National Park area has filed
a claim with the U.S. Forest Service and expects others to join in
his legal action.
   Dr. Glenn Watters, whose $60,000, nearly finished cabin in Cooke
Pass north of Powell was one of four destroyed when a backfire
started by firefighters roared out of control, predicts a rash of
lawsuits against the government unless it properly reimburses
property owners for their losses.
   ``There will be the darnedest class-action lawsuit you ever saw
in your life,'' he told the Denver Post.
   Fires charred more than 1.6 million acres in the worst fire
season in the park's history.
   ``I think we were betrayed,'' said Charlotte Ficken of Powell,
whose mobile home southeast of Cooke City, Mont., was destroyed by
fires despite firefighters' assurances it would be protected. ``I
just don't think we got any help. So we just burned.''
   Federal policies call for claims to be paid only if government
negligence can be proven, but Watters said he does not believe that
will be a problem.
   ``The (National) Park Service realizes they blew it,'' he said.
``They tell you now that they were suppressing those fires, but
they weren't. They were as proud as peacocks of those natural fires
that they were letting burn _ and then they let things get away
from them.''
   Under National Park Service and Forest Service policies,
naturally caused fires in parks or wilderness areas were allowed to
burn unless they threatened structures or safety. Both agencies
switched to the offensive against fires in July because of
extremely dry conditions.
   A number of business owners around the park have claimed they
lost money because the fires discouraged travelers from visiting
the Yellowstone area.
   Four Wyoming counties have been declared disaster areas,
clearing the way for low-interest loans, but the loans are not
expected to help those who lost summer or permanent homes or
outfitters who lost business because of the fires.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
