<HEAD>Bush Resumes Attack on Dukakis on Defense</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 10 grafs new with speech today; pick up 6th graf pvs bgng
``Bush enjoyed...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush today resumed his attack on
presidential rival Michael Dukakis as weak on defense, accusing the
Democrat of spreading ``misinformation'' about the state of U.S.
military forces.
   The Republican vice president, in remarks prepared for delivery
at a Martin Marietta defense contractor plant, said Dukakis is
``trying desperately to jump into the mainstream'' by acknowledging
a need to modernize land-based defenses.
   ``But there is strong reason to doubt that he would do it,
especially when it comes to modernizing our land-based missiles. He
still opposes the MX and he thinks the Midgetman costs too much. So
he says he's going to work with Congress to find another way.
   ``Wake up, governor, we've done all that,'' Bush said, adding
that in 1983 the bipartisan Scowcroft Commission was formed to
study national defense issues.
   Bush called on Dukakis to stop spreading what he called
``misinformation'' about the state of U.S. forces.
   ``It's not 1980 anymore. Our divisional war fighting
capabilities have improved by an average of 60 percent since
1980,'' Bush said. ``Notwithstanding my opponents' claims, only a
few of the A-6's are grounded because of wing cracks _ not one
third. We've got the money to fix them as fast as the manufacturer
can do it.
   ``Governor, it's time to stop running down our defenses,'' Bush
said.
   In his first news conference in more than two weeks, Bush said
Sunday that questions such as a query about his agenda for the
first 60 days in office ``are putting me beyond where I want to
be.''
   ``So if I don't answer some of them from here on in it is
because I'm focusing on November 8 and I don't want to be dragged
beyond that because things seem to be going well now,'' Bush said.
   The GOP nominee has a solid lead in many national polls and
Electoral College surveys.
   Bush enjoyed a low-key Sunday, joining family members at a
football game between the Denver Broncos and the Atlanta Falcons.
The vice president, who viewed the game from a private box, was
introduced at halftime to a mixture of cheers and boos.
   At the news conference, the GOP nominee declined to say what
budget cuts he would make to balance the budget, and was unspecific
when asked how he would deal with funding for the Nicaraguan rebels
and whether the homeless problem warrants special Cabinet-level
supervision.
   Bush said he already has a team studying the transition to a
Bush presidency and that he is ready to name his Cabinet quickly.
Former Navy Undersecretary Chase Untermeyer heads the Bush
transition team.
   ``He has drawn up wiring diagrams, what we should do if we
win,'' Bush said. ``You have to hit the ground running.''
   The vice president, however, scoffed at suggestions that he
already had decided on most of the Cabinet members he would choose.
   ``I can't let myself think about that. ... I'm not going to do
something that dumb and shift gears,'' Bush said.
   Referring to his escalating poll ratings since Thursday's
debate, he said, ``I can tell you I've been encouraged _ certainly
not one scintilla of overconfidence.''
   Bush did not disclose where he would make deficit-reducing
budget cuts, because that is something he will work out with
Congress when the times comes, according to his staff.
   ``You have to sit down and know the facts at the time,'' Bush
said at the news conference.
   On how he would handle the Contra situation in light of the
rebels' diminished military capacity, Bush said, ``I can't give you
what I'll do after I become president, but I'm a strong believer
that we made a big mistake, the Congress did, in not supporting the
resistance ... I would simply take a hard look when I got there,
see what the facts were at the time, and try to help the forces
that want democracy.''
   Bush said he would put his vice president in charge of a
national anti-drug program, but when asked what other duties he
would give him, Bush said only that it would be ``a wide area of
assignments based on the model of the last two administrations.''
   As to whether the homeless problem might merit special oversight
by the vice president, he replied: ``There's a lot of problems of
sufficient severity to require the attention of the president and
vice president. Whether that means setting up some special
operation, I couldn't possibly say.''
   Bush maintained that he can balance the budget by 1992 under his
``flexible freeze'' plan to limit federal spenfing to the rate of
inflation, with cuts off-setting each new spending item.
   He has listed some areas where he would spend more money,
including education, child care and cleaning up the environment,
but has refused to list cuts.
   Bush conceded that, for his idea to work, interest rates would
have to decline by several percentage points from current levels.
</TEXT>
