<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-88 1146EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 2ndLd-Writethru a0556 10-17 0927</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0556,920</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Accuses Bush of Inaction While Industry Suffers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede BOSTON</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 15 grafs new with Dukakis speech; picks up pvs 4th graf
bgng, While the.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EUCLID, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Underdog Michael Dukakis, trying to reverse
his slide in pre-election polls, declared in the industrial Middle
West today that Republican rival George Bush ``sat on his hands
while America's industrial heartland has been fighting for its
life.''
   In a speech at the North Coast Brass and Copper Co., the
Democratic presidential nominee said that ``here in Ohio you've
lost thousands of manufacturing jobs. And just last week we learned
that we had more imports coming into the United States in August
than in any month in history.''
   Aides said that in the final three weeks of the campaign,
Dukakis would sharpen the differences between him and Bush,
particularly on economic issues.
   Dukakis arrived in Ohio shortly after publication of a new poll
by the Akron Beacon Journal which showed him trailing Bush in this
critical state by 11 points.
   Political aide Charles Baker dismissed the poll, saying the Ohio
electorate is ``volatile.''
   Ohio, he said, ``is winnable.'' Baker said Dukakis was spending
a full day in Ohio to be followed by a similar all-day foray into
Michigan.
   ``The sense is that you want to create a bigger impact on a
state by putting a lot of attention on it in one day,'' he said.
   Asked in which major states Dukakis is now trailing, Baker would
only reply, ``They're all competitive.''
   In his Euclid speech, Dukakis said that while Bush talks about
``a kinder, gentler nation,'' his record contradicts that message.
   ``His record tells the people of Ohio, `We don't care enough
about you to protect you from the nuclear weapons facilities that
are poisoning your water and threatening the safety of your
workers','' he said.
   ``And I`m here to tell you that in a Dukakis-Bentsen
administration, we'll have an Energy Department that makes sure
that its citizens and communities are never again threatened by
nuclear waste and deadly radioactive clouds,'' he said.
   On foreign trade, Dukakis said Bush ``has not given the American
people a clue as to what he would do. Mr. Bush's trade policy is
like a rerun of `Let's Make a Deal,' letting the voters guess
what's behind door No. 1, door No. 2 and door No. 3.''
   The Massachusetts governor said he would ``open the doors of
foreign markets to American products, because I want an America
more concerned with selling American goods abroad than selling
American debt abroad.''
   At a hometown rally in Boston on Sunday, Dukakis cast the Nov. 8
election as a contest between his middle-class work ethic and
penthouse Republicans who support Bush.
   ``I enter the last three weeks of this campaign as an underdog,
fighting for the values I believe in,'' he said.
   While the emphasis in Boston was on values, Dukakis aide Leslie
Dach said the Democratic nominee would concentrate on spelling out
``two different visions of our economic future'' during appearances
in Ohio, Michigan and Illinois over the next three days.
   ``The close of the campaign is going to be headed by a focus on
the economic issues,'' said Dach.
   Dukakis told supporters in historic Faneuil Hall, where leaders
of the American Revolution often met, that Republicans were
``already celebrating; they're popping champagne corks in their
penthouses. But I've got news for those Republicans; we're going to
be the ones celebrating on election night.''
   Emphasizing the differences between himself and Bush, the
Democratic nominee said, ``I believe in an America that's in
command of its destiny and takes charge of its future.''
   He said the vice president ``sat on the sidelines for eight
years while America got beaten in world markets, while they
mortgaged our children's future to a mountain of debt, and a piece
of America was being sold off every day at bargain basement
prices.''
   Said Dukakis: ``I believe America's leaders must strive to do
the right thing; but we must admit it _ and correct it _ when we do
the wrong thing. ... I've taken responsibility for my mistakes. But
Mr. Bush takes responsibility for nothing.''
   ``I believe in the value of work,'' said Dukakis, while Bush
``saw nothing, said nothing and did nothing while his Republican
colleagues in the Congress used every trick in the book to keep the
minimum wage a poverty wage.''
   ``Ask Mr. Bush,'' he went on ``if he can look a woman in the eye
who scrubs floors for a living to support her family on $3.35 an
hour.''
   Dukakis campaign manager Susan Estrich and Dach denied the
accuracy of a Washington Post story on Sunday that said he would
concentrate his efforts on 18 states and the District of Columbia
with 272 electoral votes _ two more than needed for election.
   The list contained most of the major states _ New York,
California, Michigan, Ohio, Illinois and Pennsylvania _ that both
sides describe as key battlegrounds.
   Also on the list were Minnesota, Massachusetts, Vermont,
Connecticut, Rhode Island, Maryland, West Virginia, the District of
Columbia, Iowa, Wisconsin, Oregon, Washington and Hawaii.
   Given lower priority, according to the Post, were Texas, home
state of Democratic vice presidential nominee Lloyd Bentsen, and
New Jersey.
   ``It is not (accurate),'' said Estrich.
   ``We are not writing off whole regions of the country,'' she
said.
   She noted that while the story put Georgia and Louisiana among
the states being given less priority, Dukakis would be in both this
week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
