<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-88 1311EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-OfficialEnglish     10-17 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Official English,0593</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Reagan Aide Linda Chavez Quits U.S. English Group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former White House aide Linda Chavez said today
she is quitting as president of U.S. English after being told that
at least one major contributor to the group has advocated forced
sterilization.
   ``I am resigning,'' she said. ``To me, it is just not consistent
with the views I hold.''
   Veteran CBS newsman Walter Cronkite resigned from the group's
advisory board last week after being told of a 1986 memo by U.S.
English Chairman John Tanton that raised the spectre of the United
States becoming overwhelmed by foreign-speaking have-nots.
   Ms. Chavez, the Republican candidate for the U.S. Senate from
Maryland in 1986 and a former aide in the Reagan administration,
told The Associated Press last week that she might follow suit if
Tanton did not step down following a weekend board meeting.
   On Monday, she said she had since learned that at least one
major contributor had helped reprint ``an awful, awful book''
called ``Coup of the Saints'' which she described as ``a paranoid
fantasy'' about ``undesirables of the Third World'' taking over
developed nations.
   At least one major contributor has given money to ``groups that
may be involved in eugenics research,'' she added.
   Ms. Chavez did not identify the contributor or contributors
about whom she was speaking but said she asked Tanton whether he
knew of the contributors' other activities. He told her he wasn't
aware of them.
   A proposition bankrolled by U.S. English that is on the Arizona
ballot next month would change the Arizona Constitution to
designate English as the state's official language and limit
government use of foreign languages in courts, meetings and schools.
   Similar measures are on the ballot in Colorado and Florida.
   Ms. Chavez said she had planned to leave the group anyway
following the weekend board meeting but decided after hearing about
the contributors that ``I don't feel that I wish to wait until
other details are worked out.''
   At their meeting in Alexandria, Va., the U.S. English board of
directors decided to review Tanton's activities in
immigration-reform and population-control groups and his 1986 memo
before taking any action.
   Tanton did not immediately return a call seeking comment, and an
operator at U.S. English in Washington said no one else was
available.
   Ms. Chavez said she had sought assurances about the type of
backers the organization had before she joined it and had given up
administrative control of U.S. English several weeks ago because
the organization's financial records weren't being kept in
Washington.
   ``I feel that there were some misrepresentations made,'' she
said in a telephone interview from her home in Maryland.
   In Phoenix, a spokesman for opponents of the ballot proposition
said word of her resignation would help his efforts.
   ``This resignation confirms what we have been saying,'' said
spokesman Perry Baker. ``It is hard for anyone to support John
Tanton and Proposition 106 when the facts are known. One shadowy
figure from Michigan is pushing his grisly vision upon the people
of Arizona.''
   Ms. Chavez said she still supported the idea behind U.S. English
and believed the proposition could stand on its own merit no matter
who supported or opposed it.
   Supporters of Proposition 106 say it would unify the state and
help minorities join the mainstream more quickly. Critics claim it
would disrupt the operation of civil courts, English-proficiency
classes, tourism and commerce with other countries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
