<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-88 1334EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-YellAndTell     10-17 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yell And Tell,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boy Scouts Told To Yell And Tell When Threatened With Abuse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boy Scout leaders seeking to ward off child
molesters are telling their troops in a ``yell and tell'' campaign
that it's okay for a Scout to be rude and even to holler ``no'' if
someone tries to do something wrong.
   The assertiveness training is part of a nationwide Youth
Protection Training program unveiled this year by the Boy Scouts of
America.
   ``We know that perverted individuals seek out youth
organizations such as Scouts, choirs and teams. What we have done
is sharpen our scrutiny and make the Boy Scouts of America very
uncomfortable for pedophiles,'' said Bill Kephart, Denver area
scouting director.
   In his eight years as executive director of Denver scouting
headquarters, Kephart said he had heard only four official
complaints of molestation. In 24 years of scouting work before that
he recalls only one complaint, he said.
   But Ted Accus, spokesman for the Boy Scouts national
headquarters in Irving, Texas, said at least 100 official
accusations of sexual assault have been registered in the past
decade nationwide. The program has 1.5 million leaders operating
each year.
   In the past year, Explorer Scout posts in the Denver area have
been involved in two sexual assault cases.
   A former Douglas County sheriff's deputy was sentenced in May to
nine years in prison for sexual assault on a minor. Three Scouts
testified he used his position to gain their trust and manipulated
their loyalty to seduce them.
   Last month a former Explorer Scout accused a Cherry Hills
Village patrolman of sexually abusing her in 1984. The case has not
yet come to trial.
   Kephart has scheduled a Youth Protection workshop Oct. 22 for
leaders of nearly 150 metro-area Explorer Scout Posts.
   Effective last month, anyone wanting to become a Boy Scout
leader must submit an application that lists any drug, child abuse
or other felony charges.
   Scouting adminstrators also are teaching leaders to avoid being
accused, Kephart said.
   ``At one time, Scout leaders counseling a kid could shut the
door and sit down to talk with him. But now we tell them not to get
alone with Scouts,'' Kephart said.
   In addition to the ban on one-on-one contact, new rules require
that at least two supervising adults accompany outings such as
campouts.
   ``It is a great dilemma,'' Kephart said. ``There are plenty of
kids out there who really need an arm around their shoulder and
some affection. I don't really think that hugging is completely out.
   ``But if I want to put an arm around a Scout who has done well,
I do it in public and standing in the middle of the room.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
