<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--Fatal-Suicide     10-17 0161</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Fatal-Suicide,0166</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Motorist Commits Suicide After Fatal Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RUMNEY, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A motorist involved in a fatal head-on
traffic collision committed suicide at the scene while medics were
treating people injured in the wreck, police said.
   An autopsy completed Sunday showed that Ronald Paquette, 42, of
Plymouth, shot himself in the head, police said. They declined to
speculate on a motive.
   State Police Capt. Ernest Loomis said blood tests had not been
completed on Paquette. Loomis said he had several drunken driving
convictions.
   Loomis said Paquette apparently tried to pass several cars on a
two-lane highway and struck an oncoming car Saturday evening.
   Loomis said Paquette turned a pistol on himself while sitting
alone in his car as medical attendants were treating people injured
in the other car. State police also were nearby. One person in the
other car was killed.
   Paquette had been treated minutes earlier for multiple head and
chest injuries that were not life-threatening, Loomis said.
