<2ND_LINE>PM-Egypt-Farida, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0588,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Simple Funeral for Egypt's Former Queen</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS name of newspaper in 9th graf ``Women in Egypt...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MAURICE GUINDI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Safinaz Zulficar, who reigned as Queen
Farida of Egypt for 11 years before being divorced by her husband
King Farouk, was buried today after a simple funeral.
   Farida, 67, died on Sunday, almost two weeks after being
admitted to a hospital for pneumonia. She spent four days in a coma
before her death.
   President Hosni Mubarak assigned his first chamberlain to join
about 700 mourners at the funeral. Although it was not a state
affair, several senior government officials walked at the head of
the procession.
   The funeral was a far cry from Farouk's nighttime burial in
Cairo, without a procession and with only a few of his closest
family members allowed to attend.
   Farouk, overthrown by the army in 1952 and sent into exile in
Italy, died in Rome on March 18, 1965. At the family's request, his
body was brought to Egypt 12 days later and was buried at Cairo's
Al-Rifai Mosque next to his father, King Fuad I.
   Farida, Arabic for unique, was the name Farouk decided to give
his bride after their marriage in 1938, two years after he became
king. He was 18 then, she 17. They had three daughters, Feria,
Fawzia and Fadia.
   What seemingly began as a happy marriage began to crack up after
Farouk started public affairs with other women and frequented night
clubs and gambling casinos in the mid-1940s. His popularity dropped
as scandal involving him became common knowledge.
   At the same time, Farida, widely regarded as the wronged
partner, gained in public stature.
   Women in Egypt could not sue for divorce at the time, but Farida
demanded a divorce, and continued in her efforts despite pressure
from government officials to dissuade her, said Al-Akhbar newspaper
columnist Mustafa Amin, who was close to the royal family.
   In 1948, Farouk granted the divorce. No reason was given, and
other reports said the divorce was caused because Farida did not
bear him a son.
   The ex-queen moved with the daughters to Switzerland and later
moved to Paris, where she took up painting.
   Farida returned home in 1982 and settled in a small apartment in
Cairo. She held several exhibitions of her paintings, which were
mainly depictions of life in Egypt.
   Al-Ahram reported today that Farida's last wish was to see her
daughters. All three were summoned from Switzerland, where they
live, and were at their mother's bedside when she died.
   Farida never spoke ill of Farouk in public, despite the anguish
she reportedly endured.
   In a eulogy published today, Amin wrote that she once told him:
   ``Remember, he was the father of my daughters. Any bad word I
utter about him would hurt them.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
