<HEAD>Seoul to Open Trade Offices in China, Soviet Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea will open trade offices in
China and the Soviet Union, the government announced Monday.
   The state-run Korea Trade Promotion Corp. told the National
Assembly that it also is negotiating with Bulgaria and four other
East European countries to exchange trade representatives.
   The offices in Beijing and in the Chinese province of Shandong
will open in December, according to trade officials. A Chinese
trade office will be set up in Seoul.
   The opening dates for the offices in Moscow and Vladivostok have
not been set.
   South Korea, which has not diplomatic relations with any
communist nation, recently exchanged trade offices with Hungary and
Yugoslavia.
