<1ST_LINE>r p AM-PledgeHistory     10-17 0772</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pledge History,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Socialist Wrote Pledge of Allegiance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scholars say few people would have been more
surprised by the Pledge of Allegiance's prominence in the 1988
presidential campaign than the man who wrote it. He was a socialist.
   The pledge first appeared in a Boston magazine, The Youth's
Companion, 96 years ago, on Sept. 8, 1892.
   Although there are competing claims to authorship, most
authorities credit the Rev. Francis Bellamy, a Baptist minister who
preached against big business and served as vice president of the
Society of Christian Socialists.
   His daughter-in-law, Rachel Bellamy, 92, of Rochester, N.Y.,
recalls him as tall, proud and ``kind of stuffy.'' She said he
eventually left the ministry because he felt the church ``was not
doing enough to help the working man.''
   Louise Harris of Providence, R.I., who has written two books on
the history of the pledge, believes Bellamy's congregation grew
tired of his political homilies _ one was entitled ``Jesus the
Socialist'' _ and forced him out of the pulpit.
   In any event, Bellamy joined the staff of The Youth's Companion
in 1891 and apparently composed the pledge a few months later,
while the magazine was in the midst of a campaign to sell American
flags.
   The Youth's Companion had pioneered the sale of subscription
``premiums'' ranging from school uniforms to silver tea services.
But it achieved its greatest commercial success, and its enduring
legacy, with its drive to put a flag in every school in the land.
   The flags were priced at $3.30 to $13, depending on size. To
help schools raise the money, the magazine provided ``flag
certificates'' that pupils could sell for 10 cents apiece.
   Starting a year early, The Youth's Companion urged school
children to prepare to celebrate the 400th anniversary of Columbus'
voyage to America, which was coming up in October 1892.
   To show it was truly companionable, the magazine even published
a suggested ``Columbian Celebration'' ceremony. Most of it just
happened to require a flag.
   Sandwiched between a presidential proclamation and an ode to
Columbus, both long forgotten, was the original 23-word pledge,
memorable both for its sentiment and its economy of phrasing: ``I
pledge allegiance to my flag and to the republic for which it
stands: one nation, indivisible, with liberty and justice for all.''
   It was not until 1923 that the words ``my flag'' were replaced
by ``the flag of the United States of America'' out of concern that
immigrant children might otherwise think they were pledging
allegiance to some other flag.
   The phrase ``under God'' was inserted in 1954 at the behest of
President Eisenhower, who said that ``in this way we shall
constantly strengthen those spiritual weapons which forever will be
our country's most powerful resource in peace and war.''
   The original version of the pledge was not signed, but once it
had caught on in the schools, rival claims to authorship quickly
emerged. One group pushed for James B. Upham, an editor of The
Youth's Companion. The other favored Bellamy.
   Harris and a few other scholars argue that Upham was the author.
But two formal investigations, one conducted by the U.S. Flag
Association in 1939 and the other by the Library of Congress in
1957, concluded that Bellamy was responsible.
   David Whitman, a researcher in Washington, D.C., says Bellamy
espoused ``a relatively benign form'' of socialism.
   ``The Nationalist Movement, which he belonged to, wanted to
nationalize chunks of the American economy but have them controlled
at the municipal level. ... He did not practice or preach violent
overthrow of the government by any means,'' Whitman said.
   Controversy over the pledge erupted in the 1940s, when Jehovah's
Witnesses refused to recite it in the public schools. Members of
the sect said swearing allegiance to a material object violated
their religious principles, which dictated allegiance only to God.
   The Supreme Court initially rejected such arguments, ruling in a
1940 case that public schools could expel children who did not
recite the pledge. The court reversed itself in 1943 and said
children could not be compelled to recite the pledge.
   Meantime, Jehovah's Witnesses had been subjected to vicious
attacks in dozens of communities. In Richwood, Va., for example,
members of the sheriff's department and American Legion forced
seven members of the sect to drink large quantities of castor oil,
then tied them together and paraded them through the town.
   ``Bellamy was an avid fan of saying the pledge,'' said Whitman,
``but I can't imagine how he would have felt about it if he had
lived to see the mob violence of the 40s.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881017-0113 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-88 1414EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-Jews     10-17 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Jews,0498</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honecker Meets With Jewish Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of the World Jewish Congress and
East German leader Erich Honecker on Monday discussed efforts to
fight anti-Semitism.
   Neither side would comment publicly on a plan for East Germany
to aid Holocaust victims.
   Before the meeting, Edgar M. Bronfman said he hoped a final
decision could be reached during his visit on reparations to Jewish
victims of Nazi persecution.
   But the state-run news agency ADN, in several extensive
dispatches, made no mention of discussions about compensation.
   Bronfman also refused specific comment on the issue, saying only
that the talk was ``pleasant, very warm and very cordial.''
   ``We agreed on all the fundamentals,'' he said, adding that
details of the discussions would be announced Tuesday.
   Bronfman has said that an admission of shared responsibility for
the Holocaust was as important as financial contributions to
victims.
   ADN said Honecker told Bronfman of East Germany's efforts to
educate its young people about the horrors of Nazi Germany.
   ``The struggle against racism and anti-Semitism belongs to the
anti-fascist tradition of East Germany,'' Honecker was quoted as
saying. ``We will never forget that many Jews, together with
communists and Social Democrats ... were active in the struggle
against the Nazi dictatorship.''
   ADN quoted Bronfman as telling Honecker that ``I believe that
today we have built a bridge.''
   The news agency said Bronfman thanked Honecker for recent
government efforts on the part of Jews, including funding for the
reconstruction of an East Berlin synagogue.
   After Bronfman arrived Sunday, he told The Associated Press he
believed the East German leadership was sincere in offering
reparations.
   Such an agreement would mark a major change in the communist
nation's previous policies.
   ``I'm optimistic,'' he said. ``What is at stake here is moral
culpability.''
   More than 6 million Jews were killed during Adolf Hitler's Third
Reich, a fact that East Germany does not dispute. Since its
founding in 1949, however, East Germany has argued that it bears no
reponsibility for Nazi atrocities because the nation was born after
World War II ended.
   In past months, East German media have reported on government
efforts to improve relations with East Berlin's Jewish community.
   In June, East Germany said it was willing to provide
``humanitarian aid'' to Jewish survivors of the Holocaust, but
negotiations have continued on the reparations themselves.
   West Berlin Jewish leaders have said that East Germany has been
considering paying up to $100 million.
   In 1952, West Germany signed an agreement with the World Jewish
Congress to compensate Holocaust victims and families. Since then,
West Germany has paid more than $48 billion to Holocaust survivors
worldwide.
   West Germany also was founded in 1949.
   Bronfman also planned to meet with leaders of East Berlin's tiny
Jewish community before departing Tuesday. There are an estimated
450-600 practicing Jews in East Germany.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881017-0114 </DOCNO>
