<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-88 1414EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-AndrewCuomo     10-17 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Andrew Cuomo,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuomo Gives Up Law Practice for Homeless Work</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ROCHELLE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Mario Cuomo's son Andrew said
Monday he has quit his partnership in a law firm to work full time
on building housing for the homeless.
   ``I believe in my heart and soul this is the right thing to
do,'' Cuomo, 30, said. ``I don't want to do this forever, but for
now, there's nothing I'd rather do.''
   Cuomo reportedly earned more than $225,000 annually at the firm
of Blutrich, Falcone and Miller, which he joined three years ago as
a partner.
   His salary as head of HELP, a not-for-profit organization, will
be between $50,000 and $60,000 annually, said Jeffrey Sachs,
director of operations for the group.
   Cuomo founded HELP three years ago to provide transitional
housing for women with children as an alternative to welfare
hotels, and worked out of the law firm's offices as its head.
   His resignation was effective immediately, he said.
   During his father's 1986 re-election campaign, questions were
raised about whether the law firm might be benefiting from having
the governor's son as a partner. The firm did not represent clients
before state agencies that were under the governor's control while
Cuomo was a partner.
</TEXT>
