<HEAD>Joint Naval Exercises Resume After 7 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Argentine warships began
joint maneuvers Monday for the first time in seven years.
   The former military junta withdrew from the annual ``Unitas''
maneuvers in 1982, following U.S. support for Britain in the war
over the Falkland Islands.
   Defense Ministry spokesman Horacio Altamirano said the exercises
in the South Atlantic are being held to ``increase the preparedness
and professionalism'' of Argentine sailors, and coordinate
procedures for aiding ships in distress.
   The daily newspaper La Nacion reported the U.S. flotilla
includes the missile-carrying destroyers Sampson and Nicholson, the
nuclear-powered attack submarine Shark, and the frigate W.S. Sims.
   A spokeswoman for the U.S. Embassy said she could not confirm
the types of U.S. warships. The maneuvers are bilateral, she said,
and not part of ``Unitas.''
   The joint maneuvers, which end Saturday, are a sign that
military relations between the two countries are warming after
years of tensions.
   The military junta that unseated Isabel Peron in a 1976 coup
also pulled out of the 1977 and 1978 ``Unitas'' drills because of
President Jimmy Carter's criticism of the dictatorship's human
rights abuses.
   The attempted reprovisioning of U.S. warships in 1984 at Puerto
Madryn, 960 miles south of Buenos Aires, sparked public protests.
   Last month, Defense Minister Horacio Jaunarena traveled to
Washington at the invitation of Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci,
and Navy chief Adm. Ramon Arosa toured the U.S. aircraft carrier
Independence off Argentina's coast.
</TEXT>
