<HEAD>U.S. Military Commander in Farewell Visit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The retiring commander of U.S. forces in the
Persian Gulf met with Kuwaiti leaders Monday as part of a farewell
visit, officials said.
   Gen. George B. Crist, who steps down next month as head of the
U.S. Central Command, called on Kuwait's Crown Prince and Prime
Minister, Sheik Saad Abdullah al-Sabah.
   He also visited Defense Minister Sheik Nawaf al-Ahmed al-Sabah,
and was a luncheon guest of Sheik Ali Khalifa al-Sabah, Kuwait's
petroleum minister and director of its state-owned oil company.
   Kuwait-based sources, asking not to be identified, said the U.S.
flagging of Kuwaiti oil tankers was discussed. But they said no
decision was expected on how long the American commitment might
last in the aftermath of the Iran-Iraq cease-fire that went into
effect Aug. 20.
   Kuwait is not likely to remove the U.S. flags from 11
state-owned tankers re-registered by the United States last year
until a ``substantive peace agreement'' between Iran and Iraq is
reached, the sources said.
   Crist had said during a visit to Bahrain that any decision on
ending the reflagging would be made by Kuwaiti officials, and until
then the ships would continue to have the ``traditional
protection'' of the U.S. Navy.
   The four-star Marine Corps officer, whose headquarters in Tampa,
Fla., controls the U.S. military operations in the gulf, came to
Kuwait from Bahrain, where he called on top officials including the
Emir, Sheik Isa bin Salman Al Khalifa.
   The Kuwaiti tankers were reflagged to qualify for U.S. naval
protection from Iranian attack. The United States recently ended
full-time convoys of the tankers, but U.S. warships in the gulf
continue to monitor their movements, U.S. officers say.
