<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--PowerOutage     10-17 0160</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Power Outage,0164</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Outage Darkens Downtown Buildings In Utah Capital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A power outage darkened buildings in
scattered pockets of downtown when a high-voltage transformer
failed Monday, but all electricity was restored within an hour,
officials said.
   Lights flickered across the Salt Lake Valley when the
transformer failed at 10:23 a.m. MDT, but only the downtown area
lost power, said Utah Power & Light Co. spokesman Dave Mead.
   The failure of the transformer in a substation blew fuses there,
knocking out power to a second substation and triggering a
``cascade effect'' in the area, he said.
   It was not known what caused the failure of the transformer,
which reduces a 12,000-volt feed to 4,000 volts, Mead said.
   Power to 90 percent of the area was restored by 10:45, with the
remainder by 11:20 a.m., he said.
   The transformer remained out of order Monday afternoon, but Utah
Power transferred power feeds to alternate circuits, Mead said.
</TEXT>
