<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FactoryUse     10-17 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Factory Use,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Factory Use Slows for First Time in Seven Months</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The strain on U.S. industrial capacity eased
in September for the first time in seven months as utilities scaled
back after the summer heat wave, the government said Monday.
   The Federal Reserve Board said the overall operating rate last
month at U.S. factories, mines and utilities fell to 83.6 percent
of capacity, down 0.2 percentage points from August.
   In July, the rate also was 83.8 percent, soaring to an
eight-year high from 83.0 percent in June as utilities produced
more electricity to run air conditioners.
   Utility operating rates fell from 83.6 percent in August to 79.9
percent last month, while electric utilities fell from 88.1 percent
to 83.5 percent.
   ``Utilities had their big surge in July and August and then they
came back to normal,'' said Robert G. Dederick, an economist with
Northern Trust Co. in Chicago.
   ``The relevant thing is what went on in the manufacturing
sector. ... There, I think we can say the pressure on resources
hasn't worsened, but it still remains relatively high and therefore
any easing of inflation pressures is unlikely,'' he said.
   The operating rate at manufacturing plants held steady at 83.8
percent, the same as August and down slightly from 83.9 percent in
July, the most recent peak.
   Economists have expressed concern that high factory operating
rates and a tight labor market are exerting inflationary pressure
on the economy. If overall operating rates get too high, overworked
factories can have trouble meeting demand, leading to higher prices.
   Capacity use at manufacturers of durable goods, ``big ticket''
items expected to last three or more years, edged up 0.1 percentage
points to 82.4 percent while the rate for non-durable goods edged
down by the same amount to 85.8 percent.
   The largest increase came at auto assembly plants, where the
operating rate rose 3.6 percentage points to 74.0 percent.
   ``The overall level of capacity utilization doesn't signal as
much price pressure as it might because the hot industries are
cooling and the cool industries are speeding up,'' said John
Hagens, an economist for The Wefa Group, a Bala Cynwyd, Pa.,
forecasting firm.
   Two areas of particular tightness _ paper and textiles _ have
cooled from levels a year ago. Capacity use among paper
manufacturers was 93.8 percent in August, the latest month
available, down from 95.7 percent in September 1987. The rate for
textiles has eased from 93.6 percent to 89.1 percent in August.
   The rate for the mining sector, which includes oil and gas
drilling, rebounded to 83.1 percent last month, up from 82.8
percent in August but still below the 83.2 percent July rate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881017-0125 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-88 1521EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ARAMCO-Discrimination     10-17 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-ARAMCO-Discrimination,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>5th Circuit: U.S. Companies Overseas Don't Have To Meet Civil
Rights Laws</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. companies operating abroad do not have
to comply with the civil rights law forbidding discrimination on
the job, a federal appeals court ruled Monday.
   The 2-1 ruling by the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld a
lower court ruling against Ali Boureslan, a naturalized U.S.
citizen who was born in Lebanon and employed by Aramco in Dhahran,
Saudi Arabia.
   He filed suit under Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964,
contending that he was fired in June 1984 after a harassment
campaign by his supervisor _ ``a campaign which took the form of
racial, religious and ethnic slurs,'' the 5th Circuit said.
   The seven-page majority ruling by Judge Eugene Davis said the
court could not find any indication in the law or in its
legislative history that Congress had meant to extend civil rights
protection to U.S. citizens employed abroad.
   Arguments that it is unfair to deny Americans employed abroad
protections to which they are entitled in this country are
appealing, but do not overcome other strong policy arguments, Davis
wrote.
   ``The religious and social customs practiced in many countries
are wholly at odds with those of this country,'' the ruling said.
``Requiring American employers to comply with Title VII in such a
country could well leave American corporations the difficult choice
of either refusing to employ United States in the country or
discontinuing business.''
   In a strong 17-page dissent, Judge Carolyn Dineen King said it
may be necessary to enforce the law abroad to be sure that
minorities and women have an equal chance at home.
   ``Today's decision means that one U.S. citizen assigned to the
Saudi office of a U.S. corporation, and another U.S. citizen
working for the same company in Texas could experience identical
acts of discrimination, but only the latter will have a remedy.
This situation creates a dilemma for minorities and women: foreign
assignments will be less attractive, while refusal of such an
assignment could limit an individual's opportunity for
advancement,'' she wrote.
   She noted that assignement to a foreign office is frequently a
required step for promotion within a multinational corporation.
This means, she said, that this country may have to enforce its
civil rights laws abroad to ensure equal chances at foreign
assignments that would affect employment opportunities in the
United States.
   Her dissent agreed with other arguments brought up by Boureslan
and the Equal Employment Opportunities Commission, which entered a
friend-of-the-court brief.
   They argued that a section exempting aliens working for U.S.
corporations in other countries showed that Congress did intend it
to apply to U.S. citizens under such circumstances.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881017-0126 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-88 1544EDT</FILEID>
