<HEAD>Soviets Announce New Jetliner</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Recasts grafs 1-2 to raise reference to plane being more
economical.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has built a quieter, more
economical passenger jet, the Communist Party newspaper Pravda
reported Monday.
   The Tupolev-204, which can carry 214 passengers and has a range
of 2,480 miles, will undergo flight trials this year and be
introduced into service by the state-run carrier Aeroflot in 1990,
Pravda said.
   Alexei Tupolev, head of the Tupolev design bureau, said the goal
was to create a plane that would consume less fuel and be cheaper
to operate. Pravda said aircraft builders believe the Tu-204 will
be the most economical Soviet plane in its class.
   Pravda also published a photograph of the airliner, showing its
two wing-mounted jet engines and a fuselage that resembles other
aircraft of the Tupolev bureau, including the Tu-154 passenger jet
that is one of the workhorses in the Aeroflot fleet.
   Tupolev said innovative production processes had ensured a
reduction in the new plane's weight and improved the performance of
its exterior.
   The Tu-204 will also be more comfortable for passengers and will
be quieter, Pravda said.
