<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-88 1458EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Quayle     10-17 0568</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Stumps Industrial Midwest Pushing `Good Jobs, Good Wages'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOUNT PLEASANT, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Dan Quayle grabbed a
Democratic line Monday as he campaigned in the industrial Midwest
pledging ``good jobs at good wages.''
   In a series of stops across Michigan, where the presidential
race is considered close, Quayle stressed economic themes, even
using some phrases that sounded more like Democrat Michael Dukakis
than the leader of Quayle's own ticket, George Bush.
   ``When we talk about the future. we're talking about jobs and
opportunity,'' Quayle told thousands of cheering high school
students in Flint. ``I'm talking about good jobs and I'm talking
about good jobs at good wages.''
   The good jobs-good wages line has been a staple in Dukakis
campaign speeches for months.
   As for the election, Quayle said the Republicans would ignore
polls showing them ahead with three weeks to go.
   ``It is down to the wire time,'' he said. ``We all think it's
going to be very competitive. We're going to run like we're 10
points behind.''
   In a state where the auto industry has been hard-hit by foreign
competition, Quayle said, ``We are talking about fair, free trade''
without resorting to ``protectionist barriers.''
   Later in the day, Quayle was traveling to Mount Pleasant,
Traverse City and Gaylord elsewhere in Michigan.
   Quayle, an Indiana Senator, appealed to regional pride at
various stops, where he was greeted by enthusiastic crowds inside
and knots of protesters outside.
   ``That man from Massachusetts may look down on us in middle
America, but come Election Day they'll be looking up to George
Bush,'' he said. ``Us Midwesterners have to stick together.''
   Quayle appreared relaxed and upbeat as he swung across the
state, surprising customers with an appearance at a fast-food
restaurant and occasionally joking with reporters on his campaign
plane.
   Questioned outside one stop, Quayle said that he was ``very
close personally'' with presidential standardbearer George Bush but
that joint appearances by the two would be ``a little bit
counterproductive.''
   ``I wouldn't ask for it,'' Quayle said. ``I want him to cover
his part of the country and I want to cover my part of the
country.''
   In his remarks to the students, Quayle said, ``My goal is the
same goal you have and that is a drug-free America.''
   ``When you have a drug kingpin involved in murder, that person
is going to get the death penalty,'' he said. ``It may sound harsh,
but those people are peddling and are merchants of death. When
they're going to murder our children and put poison in their veins,
yes, capital punishment is an appropriate response.''
   Quayle, who said last week that he had complained to Bush
campaign chairman James Baker III about anonymous criticism of him
from campaign officials, said they had had a ``very upbeat'' talk.
   Asked if Baker had offered him any advice for the final three
weeks of the campaign, Quayle said, ``No, I gave him my advice.''
   As he started his campaign day, Quayle dropped in at a Burger
King, surprising a handful of customers.
   He apologized for disturbing the relative tranquility of the
place as a crowd of reporters and photographers climbed over booths.
   ``You were sitting here nice and quiet and we ruined it,'' he
said.
   But he left with an exhortation: ``Tell them George Bush and I
will work hard for you.''
</TEXT>
