<1ST_LINE>u a PM-SwindallIndictment 4thLd-Writethru a0676</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Swindall Indictment, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0676,0809</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rep. Swindall Indicted On 10 Counts of Perjury</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `In an...', to add ages of two candidates;
adds three grafs on end with detail from indictment.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DICK PETTYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Pat Swindall was indicted today on charges
of perjury, accused of lying to a federal grand jury investigating
money laundering.
   U.S. Attorney Robert Barr said Swindall, a Republican, was
indicted on 10 counts of perjury over his testimony before a grand
jury last February about a sting in which a federal agent posed as
a money launderer.
   Swindall's office said today he had no immediate response to the
announcement. But he had said Sunday, during a television
interview, that he expected to be indicted and was glad because he
hoped it would give him a chance to clear his name before his
re-election bid goes to the voters Nov. 8.
   In an unusually bitter race, Swindall, 47, is seeking a third
term from suburban Atlanta's 4th District against Democratic
opponent Ben Jones, 46, a former actor on television's ``Dukes of
Hazzard'' who lost to Swindall in 1986.
   Jones has criticized Swindall ever since the
money-laundering-related charges were first aired, while Swindall
has assailed Jones' past conviction on a charge of wife-beating, a
conviction Jones says stemmed from alcohol abuse that he has since
overcome.
   In Sunday's interview, Swindall said he expected to be arraigned
this afternoon and planned to waive a number of rights, including
the right to charge the government with misconduct in the case, so
that he can go on trial next Monday. Barr said he did not know
whether such a quick trial would be possible.
   Swindall said he planned to represent himself at the trial.
   ``I am actually excited because it will be the first opportunity
I am going to have to clear the air, clear my name and give the
voters a legitimate race based on the issues,'' Swindall said in
the interview Sunday.
   Angered by continued reports linking his name with the grand
jury investigation, Swindall took the House floor on Oct. 3 to
demand an immediate indictment.
   Barr said the timing of the indictment ``has nothing whatsoever
to do with politics'' or Swindall's request to be indicted.
   Swindall was first linked publicly to the money laundering
investigation earlier this year when it was disclosed that his Aug.
28, 1987, meeting with an undercover federal agent posing as a
money launderer for underworld figures had been videotaped.
   ``Money laundering'' is a term for various methods of getting
around federal currency laws by transferring illicitly raised cash
_ drug money, for example _ into bank accounts in such a way that
its origin is hid.
   Swindall was introduced to the undercover agent by Charles
LeChasney, a former Atlanta businessman who was active in
Republican circles. LeChasney is one of the two men scheduled to go
on trial next week on money-laundering charges.
   LeChasney and several Swindall aides testified before the grand
jury last month. Swindall testified before the grand jury in
February.
   In June, Atlanta newspapers obtained several tape recordings
from the investigation and published excerpts from a series of
conversations between Swindall, LeChasney and the undercover agent.
   The tapes showed that Swindall continued to pursue negotiations
for an $850,000 home construction loan after being told it might be
financed with drug money he would be helping to launder.
   Swindall was quoted on the tapes as saying that the source of
the money was ``Charles' problem,'' since LeChasney would be
obtaining the money to lend to Swindall. He added, ``I frankly
don't think it's incumbent upon me to go out and find out where XYZ
Corp. gets their money, or, for that matter, where Chrysler Corp.
gets their money. If they set back the odometer, that's their
problem.''
   He ended the negotiations after being told he would have to
accept the money in person in cash and sign a receipt.
   Swindall later apologized for his role in the negotiations,
calling it a mistake in judgment, but he denied any wrongdoing.
   He also asked the House ethics committee to determine if he had
violated any law or House rule. The panel agreed to investigate,
but has not issued a ruling.
   The indictment said Swindall lied when he told the grand jury
last February that he did not have any concrete indication that
LeChasney and the undercover agent were discussing illegal
activities.
   Swindall testified that he was suspicious of the agent, but did
not have enough information to report the matter to authorities,
the indictment said.
   Another count of the indictment accuses Swindall of lying when
he denied the agent discussed keeping the large cash loan from
being reported to federal regulators.
</TEXT>
