<2ND_LINE>AM-Miners' Protest,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Miners Besiege Governor's Office</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By A.V. GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 200 miners staged a protest
rally outside Gov. Arch Moore's office Monday, complaining about
the state's black lung fund and urging that he fire his energy
commissioner.
   Moore finally appeared with a state police escort and walked
through the demonstrators, greeting some and shaking hands.
   None in the crowd tried to confront Moore with the demands,
which were a mixed bag of complaints about commissioner Ken
Faerber, a $30 million loan from the black lung fund made last
fiscal year, and Workers' Compensation Commissioner Nelson
Robinson, who oversees the black lung fund.
   The rally was called by the Coal Miners Political Action
Committee, the political arm of the UMW. The committee has endorsed
Moore's opponent in the governor's race, Democrat Gaston Caperton.
   ``I think it's nice they express themselves,'' Moore said when
asked about the protest. ``And I would hope it's sincere.''
   Just after the rally and in the opposite wing of the Capitol,
the state Supreme Court agreed to consider a petition filed last
week by UMW President Richard Trumka against Faerber and Moore. The
petition said Faerber and Moore have interfered with the operations
of the Board of Coal Mine Health and Safety, which is supposed to
review each mine fatality and issue regulations if needed to
prevent a recurrence.
   The court unanimously set arguments for Nov. 2, six days before
the election.
   Faerber denied interfering with the board and said the suit was
politically inspired.
   ``Where's Arch?'' the crowd chanted during the protest outside
the governor's office. ``Where is Moore? ... We will not be moved.''
   Charles Whited of Chesapeake, who said he was part of the Black
Lung Disabled Workers Organization, said the miners were angry
because of a high death rate in the state's mines and because $30
million was borrowed from the miners' black lung fund to help keep
state government afloat last fiscal year.
   But Faerber said last year's mine death rate of nine was the
lowest in state history. He said 10 miners have died this year.
   In addition, the black lung loan was made by the Legislature,
not the governor's office, although Moore supported it, with the
concurrence of the UMW leadership.
</TEXT>
