<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BalletWars     10-17 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ballet Wars,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Local Dance Company Feels Upstaged by Incursion By Big-City Troupe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KRISTI UMBREIT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A homegrown ballet company is hopping
mad over the city's invitation to the Cincinnati Ballet,
particularly since the larger company will perform the
``Nutcracker'' a week before its own version.
   ``We feel terrified,'' Cheryl Van Metre, artistic director of
the local Appalachian Ballet Company, said Monday. ``I hate to be
in competition with them. It boils down to having money.''
   The Knoxville Arts Council has welcomed a plan to have the
Cincinnati Ballet come south for the fall-winter season each year
as City Ballet. The council says it's a great way to bring
professional, big-city ballet to this east Tennessee city of
180,000.
   The smaller company, though, fears losing the audience for its
bread-and-butter production _ the popular Christmas classic
choreographed to Tchaikovsky's ``Nutcracker Suite.'' Its Nutcracker
is scheduled Dec. 4, a week after the Cincinnati Ballet's.
   ``We are a semiprofessional group of local dancers and we've
performed in Knoxville and all the surrounding areas for 11
years,'' said Ms. Van Metre, who studied at London's Royal Ballet
before returning home to Knoxville. ``(Nutcracker) makes the most
amount of profit for us. This is how we make our money to exist''
in addition to receiving grant money, she said.
   Her company, she adds, contributes to the community by bringing
ballet to public schools across an area often associated with buck
dancing and bluegrass music.
   Carol Hicks, project director for City Ballet, acknowledged the
struggle that the Appalachian Ballet has on its hands but said
there was little anyone could do.
   ``Our feeling is that we're bringing in a different caliber of
dance,'' she said. ``This is an opportunity for Knoxville to have a
world-renown dance troupe.
   ``It's regrettable. I know it's going to be a thorn in their
side. We've asked them to come to our meetings to talk about
things,'' she said.
</TEXT>
