<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Vietnam-Economy     10-17 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vietnam-Economy,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Says Vietnam Shifting Toward Capitalism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam is attempting to reverse a
deterioration in living standards by adopting a market-oriented
approach to its economy and by attempting to attract foreign
investment, a member of Vietnam's National Assembly said Monday.
   Nguyen Xuan Oanh, who also is a key economic adviser to the
Vietnamese government, said a major impetus to the economic policy
changes is the ``exploding'' growth rates of most capitalist
economies in East Asia.
   Speaking to a luncheon gathering at the Carnegie Endowment for
International Peace, a private research group, Oanh acknowledged
that Vietnam is one of the poorest countries in the world.
   Oanh, who once taught at two American universities and was an
official of both the International Monetary Fund and the South
Vietnamese government, said Vietnam is moving away from a centrally
planned economy in order to ``free the forces of production.''
   He added that the foreign investment code is extremely liberal
because Vietnam is entering the competition for outside business
``quite late in the game'' and more advantageous terms are required.
   Oanh has conferred with U.S. business executives during his
visit to the United States. But American investment in Vietnam is
forbidden by a U.S. trade embargo against that country.
   Visits by Vietnamese officials to the United States have been
rare. A State Department official, asking not to be identified,
said Oanh's visit apparently was part of Hanoi's policy of trying
to expand ties to the West. He is in the United States at the
invitation of several academic institutions.
   Vietnam is one of a handful of countries with which the United
States does not maintain diplomatic relations.
   Official U.S.-Vietnamese contacts have been limited mostly to
humanitarian issues. The United States has said there can be no
progress on developing political relations until Vietnam pulls its
troops out of Cambodia and Hanoi gives as full accounting as
possible of the estimated 1,700 American servicemen still missing
from the Vietnam War.
   Oanh reaffirmed Vietnam's intention to withdraw from Cambodia
and said his government also is determined to do what it can to
assist on the MIA issue.
   The two countries recently initiated joint on-site inspections
in Vietnam in the search for the missing Americans.
</TEXT>
