<HEAD>Elion 10th CUNY Grad to Cop Nobel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gertrude B. Elion, co-winner of the 1988 Nobel
Prize in medicine, is the 10th graduate of the City University of
New York to win one of the coveted awards.
   CUNY says it has more Nobel laureates among its undergraduate
alumni than any other public university in the nation.
   The winners, including their class, their category and the year
they were cited: Arthur Kornberg, '37, for medicine in 1959; Robert
Hofstadter, '35, for physics in 1961; Julius Axelrod, '33, for
medicine in 1970; Kenneth Arrow, '40, for economics in 1972;
Rosalyn Yalow, '41, for medicine in 1977; Arno Penzias, '54, for
physics in 1978; Herbert Hauptman, '37, for chemistry in 1985;
Jerome Karle, '37, for chemistry in 1985; Stanley Cohen, '43, for
medicine in 1986.
   CUNY includes nine ``senior colleges,'' among them City, Hunter
and Brooklyn colleges.
