<1ST_LINE>r w AM-EstonianEnvironmentalists     10-17 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Estonian Environmentalists,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>East-West Link Set For Environmental Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Friends of the Earth, an international
environmental organization, has accepted a Soviet organization as
an affiliate in the first East-West linkup of such groups.
   A meeting of Friends of the Earth affiliates in Krakow, Poland
earlier this month accepted the Estonian Green Movement as an
associate member, said Geoffrey Webb, international director of the
Washington-based U.S. affiliate, Friends of the Earth-USA.
   New affiliates of London-based Friends of the Earth, which now
counts member organizations in 33 countries, normally spend a year
as ``associate'' members on probation, and the Estonian group
should become a full member next year if all goes well, Webb said.
   The Estonian Green Movement, formed only in May, is the first
environmental organization in the Soviet Union seeking links to the
West that is independent of the Soviet government or Communist
Party, said Webb.
   Two years ago, Friends of the Earth accepted the Polish Ecology
Club as a similar independent affiliate.
   Environmentalists from Latvia and Lithuania, sister Baltic
republics of the Soviet Union, and from East Germany,
Czechoslovakia and the Urkaine also attended the meeting. Latvian,
Lithuanian and Ukrainian groups could become affiliates next year,
Webb said.
   ``Perestroika made possible the Estonian group,'' said Webb.
</TEXT>
