<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon     10-17 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amal Beats Up Hijacker Hamadi's Brother</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FAROUK NASSAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amal militiamen pounded the elder brother
of confessed hijacker Mohammed Ali Hamadi with rifle butts and beat
up three other security officers of the rival Hezbollah militia,
Shiite sources said Monday.
   Abdul-Hadi Hamadi, 27, Hezbollah's security chief, suffered
severe rib bruises from Saturday's beating, the sources said on
condition of anonymity.
   Both militias are Shiite Moslem, but Syria backs Amal, the
mainstream Shiite militia headed by Nabih Berri, and Iran backs
Hezbollah, or Party of God.
   Abdul-Hadi led the four Hezbollah men in a 12-member committee
that was assigned to halt a five-hour clash Saturday with Amal in
south Beirut.
   The committee also had four Amal representatives and four
officers from a Syrian army contingent in charge of south Beirut's
security, police said.
   A Hezbollah statement said on Monday, ``Hezbollah's
representatives were seized by Amal's Chiyah (district) commander
and his aides, insulted and beaten up before the Syrian brothers
stepped in and ensured their release.'' It mentioned no names.
   Police said six people were killed and 25 wounded in Saturday's
clashes with mortars, rocket-propelled grenades and machine guns.
   Abdul-Hadi is believed to have masterminded the kidnapping of
two West Germans, businessman Rudolf Cordes and engineer Alfred
Schmidt, in Beirut in January 1987 in a bid to trade them for his
brother.
   Schmidt, 47, was released Sept. 7, 1987 and Cordes, 54, was
freed Sept. 12.
   Mohammed Ali Hamadi, 24, is on trial in Frankfurt, West Germany,
on charges of air piracy and murder in the 1985 hijacking of a TWA
jetliner to Beirut. A U.S. Navy diver was killed.
   Hamadi has confessed that he was one of the hijackers but not
the one who murdered 23-year-old Robert Stethem.
   Another Hamadi brother, Abbas, was convicted by a Duesseldorf
court in April on charges related to kidnapping Schmidt and Cordes.
He was sentenced to 13 years in prison.
</TEXT>
