<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-88 1558EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Ligachev     10-17 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ligachev,0527</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Spokesman Says Ligachev Not No. 2 in Kremlin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet spokesman on Monday refused to define the
duties of former Soviet ideology chief Yegor K. Ligachev but denied
that Ligachev or anyone else is No. 2 on the ruling Politburo.
   ``All members of the Politburo are equal and some are more equal
than others,'' said Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I.
Gerasimov, paraphrasing George Orwell's satire of communist society
in the novel ``Animal Farm.''
   But he said President Mikhail S. Gorbachev has no official
second-in-command despite Western reports that Ligachev once
chaired meetings of the 12-member ruling body of the Communist
Party.
   Ligachev has been considered the top conservative rival of
Gorbachev, who is waging a campaign for economic and political
reform.
   ``What you call No. 2 doesn't exist,'' Gerasimov told reporters
at a government news briefing.
   Still, Ligachev appeared Monday at Gorbachev's right side at the
opening of a national conference of doctors in the Kremlin.
   Gerasimov left strong doubts whether Ligachev came out of a
recent Politburo power play with control over agriculture,
traditionally the nation's toughest assignment.
   After being deprived of the key ideology portfolio this year,
Ligachev was named chairman of a new Central Committee commission
on agriculture in a shake-up of the Kremlin leadership Sept. 30.
   Since the core of the powerful Central Committee apparatus will
consist of just six of these commissions, the job was hardly a
removal from power, but it clearly gave Ligachev less clout than
his former post as overseer of ideology.
   Gerasimov hedged when he was asked point-blank who is
controlling agriculture _ Ligachev, or fellow Politburo member
Viktor P. Nikonov, who had that job before the shake-up.
   ``It is the commission'' that will run agriculture, Gerasimov
said.
   Specific duties are still evolving, and those of Ligachev and
Nikonov have yet to be defined, he said.
   At a similar briefing several days ago, Gerasimov promised to
explain what Ligachev's and Nikonov's new duties are.
   Last week, Ligachev was notably absent from an important
agriculture conference where Gorbachev edged closer to dismantling
the collective farm system controlled from Moscow with a plan to
allow farmers to lease fields nationwide.
   Gerasimov said Ligachev was on vacation during the meeting and
that he didn't have to be present for all discussions of farm
issues.
   Ligachev has publicly doubted Gorbachev's policy of glasnost, or
openness on selected topics. He was reported losing his grip on
power and the ideology job in April, when reports said he was ``on
vacation'' after receiving a reprimand from Gorbachev.
   The former party bureaucrat from Siberia rose to the
policy-making Central Committee and a key job assigning party
personnel under former Soviet leader Yuri Andropov in 1983. He
joined the Politburo in 1985.
   Nikonov is an agriculture expert with roots in Gorbachev's home
soil in southern Russia, and his career climbed with Gorbachev's.
When Gorbachev became party chief for agriculture in 1978, Nikonov
became deputy Soviet minister for agriculture, essentially a top
aide in the parallel government bureaucracy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
