<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-88 1800EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Disney     10-17 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Disney,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Too Many Mickeys in Moscow, Disney Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roy Disney met Mickey Mouse in Moscow this
weekend, but it was the wrong rodent.
   ``A bad copy,'' Disney said ruefully Monday, describing the
costumed figure who has been enticing parents into ordering
pictures of their children from a state photographer on the Arbat
pedestrian mall.
   Such counterfeiting is a big obstacle keeping Soviet children
from enjoying the same Disney fantasies as their foreign
counterparts.
   A Soviet festival of Disney films is playing in Moscow but it
won't expand beyond that until the counterfeiting issue is solved,
said Disney, a vice chairman of the company.
   Disney films have not been shown in the Soviet Union since a
lone appearance in a film festival 50 years ago, according to
Soviet media. Yet, the company's cartoon characters are popular
motifs for Soviet fashion. Unfortunately for Disney, none of the
manufacturers has paid a penny in royalties.
   ``We need to talk it out,'' Disney said. Soviet officials are
aware that Disney requires protection of its ``intellectual
property'' through copyrights or similar means, he added.
   Disney would like to show its films, sell Mickey ears and
publish its familiar books and music in the Soviet Union, he said.
But Disney added that he expects no concrete deals on this visit,
because the intellectual property issue must be settled first.
   Disney is discussing possible joint productions with the Soviet
film agency, but this requires a story best filmed in the Soviet
Union, Disney said.
   Soviet officials said earlier they were discussing Disney
involvement in building ``Wonderland,'' a planned theme park.
   In answer to a question, however, Disney said he doubted his
company would ever build a Soviet version of Disneyland.
</TEXT>
