<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SoccerTrial     10-17 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soccer Trial,0470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Survivors Call For Revenge at Opening of Soccer Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIPPE NEURAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers representing 24 Britons charged
with involuntary manslaughter in a 1985 fatal soccer riot appealed
Monday for a fair trial as the proceedings opened.
   Families of some of the 39 people killed in the Heysel stadium
riot attended the trial, which was interrupted twice by bomb
threats.
   ``This trial must restore the honor which Belgium lost in the
Heysel stadium,'' said defense lawyer Serge Moureaux. ``It must be
a fair trial. The court should not try to choke the truth. Justice
must repair everything.''
   Also present were some of the survivors of the riot, which
injured 400 people. One Frenchman, who refused to identify himself,
said outside the courtroom that he survived the stampede and added:
``When I see them (the British fans) laughing, I could kill them.''
   The stampede began when the fence separating British and Italian
fans at the European Cup soccer final between Liverpool and
Juventuis Turin broke, Britons charged, Italians retreated in panic
and the 39 were trampled to death.
   Belgian police forces were blamed for their incapacity to quell
the riot. Moureaux quoted a Belgian state police sergeant as
telling investigators: ``I never saw such a lack of command.''
   The incident provoked the resignation of Belgian government
several months later.
   Moureaux quoted a Belgian state police sergeant as telling
investigators: ``I never saw such a lack of command.''
   The sergeant reportedly added that he saw a police officer run
away from the riots.
   Another defense lawyer, Georges-Henri Beauthier, asked the court
president to reject videocassettes of the incident. He also
rejected the alleged identification by Italian witnesses of the
defendents from photographs.
   ``We fear the immolation of a few of our clients on the altar of
collective frenzy,'' he said. ``We don't find it good and
comfortable to condemn a few people chosen at random from films to
reassure public opinion.''
   The defendents, if convicted, face up to 10 years in jail. The
proceedings are expected to last at least until Christmas.
   English soccer clubs have been banned competing in Europe's
three main cup tournaments since the riot.
   In Ascoli, Italy, on Monday, a 32-year-old soccer fan died from
head injuries received in clashes between rival fans on the opening
day of the Italian soccer season Oct. 9, doctors reported.
Nazzareno Filippini succumbed to heart complications which followed
two operations on his skull, the attending physicians at Umberto
Primo Hospital said.
   On Sunday, rioting broke out among hundreds of gate crashers at
an overcrowded soccer game in Cairo, Egypt, that had been blacked
out on local television. One person was killed and 50 injured,
police said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
