<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-88 1813EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ChildHunger     10-17 0584</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Child Hunger,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Survey Suggests Millions of U.S. Children May Suffer Hunger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A house-to-house survey of nearly 800
low-income families in Washington state suggests that as many as 5
million of America's children suffer from hunger, a private
activist group said Monday.
   The Food Research And Action Center is extending the study to
seven other states over the next 15 months. But on the basis of the
early data from Washington state ``... we estimate conservatively
that 2 million to 5 million children in this country could now have
a serious hunger problem,'' said Robert J. Fersh, executive
director of the center.
   ``We believe that this estimate is conservative because it
attempts only to estimate the number of children living in poverty
who might be hungry,'' said Fersh. ``It does not include any
children from families with incomes above the poverty line who
might be hungry.''
   At the same time, Fersh acknowledged that he has no way of
knowing whether the survey results in Washington state will be
replicated in larger studies.
   Similar studies are now under way in Minnesota, Florida,
Connecticut, California, Michigan, Alabama and New York.
   The survey techiques were first used in a 1986 survey in
Connecticut and refined for the Washington state and ongoing
studies, all of which involve selecting low-income families at
random and then conducting face-to-face interviews that take about
45 minutes each.
   The responses given by mothers to a lengthy questionnaire are
correlated with other information such as family income and what,
if any, public assistance such as food stamps they receive.
   Among the questions: Does your household ever run out of money
to buy food to make a meal? Do your children ever eat less than you
feel they should because there is not enough money for food?
   A respondent had to answer ``yes'' to at least five such
questions before being placed in the hunger category.
   Dr. Victor Sidel, a professor of social medicine at the Albert
Einstein College of Medicine in New York City, headed the Food
Research and Action Center's technical advisory committee and said
the survey techniques used are the best yet developed for measuring
hunger.
   ``The evidence is in. The evidence is clear. The evidence is
scientific,'' he said.
   Sidel emphasized that the kind of hunger seen among America's
children is not of the dramatic, life-threatening variety common in
African countries.
   But he said there are ``other kinds of medical and physical
consequences'' inexcusable in a country as rich as the United
States.
   ``It is a violation of equality of opportunity to force (poor)
children to go to school hungry,'' said Sidel.
   Fersh said one major finding of the Washington state study is
that it shows ``people do not supplement to the extent the food
stamp program assumes'' the amount of assistance they get from that
particular Agriculture Department program.
   The reason, he said, is that they are paying ever higher prices
for rent, child care and medical costs. ``The food budget is the
most elastic,'' he said, and that is what is cut first.
   Washington state was not singled out because hunger was believed
better or worse, but as an outgrowth of the Governor's Task Force
on Hunger created there in 1986 to try to document the extent and
nature of hunger in the state.
   The Food Action Research Center relies on the support of
foundations, religious groups, corporations, individuals and others
to carry out its hunger and poverty programs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
