<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AIDSGrants     10-17 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Grants,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>$7 Million Awarded for 19 AIDS Care Facilities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government announced the award of nearly
$7 million for construction of health care facilities specifically
for AIDS patients on Monday, the first federal money to be directed
for such programs.
   ``The awards went to facilities that were able to demonstrate a
comprehensive, cost-effective approach to providing care,'' Health
and Human Services Secretary Otis R. Bowen said in a statement. ``A
variety of traditional and nontraditional facilities received the
funds, which are to be regarded as seed money.''
   With nearly 300,000 people expected to be suffering from AIDS
within three years _ compared with about 75,000 diagnosed so far _
a major challenge facing the health care industry is for
cost-effective ways to care for such patients.
   AIDS sufferers often are not in constant need of the costly care
supplied by acute-care hospitals, yet are too sick to be cared for
at home.
   The grants announced Monday were to 19 facilities in nine states
to renovate or construct non-acute care intermediate and long-term
care facilities for patients with AIDS _ acquired immune deficiency
syndrome.
   The nine states are Arizona, California, Indiana, Maryland,
Massachusetts, New Jersey, New York, Texas and Washington.
   Bowen said the grant recipients had to guarantee that a
reasonable volume of services would be provided to patients unable
to pay and that services must be made available to all people
living or working in a facility's service area.
   The grant receipients are:
   _Phoenix Shanti Group, Inc., Phoenix, Ariz., $369,000.
   _Barlow Hospital, Los Angeles, $300,000.
   _Davies Medical Center, San Francisco, $605,858.
   _San Francisco Department of Public Health, $355,952.
   _AIDS Task Force, Inc., Fort Wayne, Ind., $100,000.
   _Earthide, Inc., Baltimore, Md., $61,268.
   _Boston Department of Health and Hospitals, $250,000.
   _St. John of God Hospital, Brighton, Mass., $350,000.
   _Hospice West, Inc., Waltham, Mass., $250,000.
   _Department of Public Health (Lemuel Shattuck Hospital), Jamaica
Plain, Mass., $250,000.
   _Integrity Inc., Newark, N.J., $205,000.
   _AIDS Resource Center, Inc., New York City, $600,000
   _Cabrini Medical Center, New York City, $401,902.
   _Housing and Services, Inc., New York City, $400,000.
   _St. Clare's Hospital and Health Center, New York City, $725,140.
   _PWA Coalition of Dallas Inc., $439,774.
   _Southwest AIDS Committee, El Paso, Texas, $488,106.
   _Bering Community Service Foundation, Houston, $50,000.
   _AIDS Housing of Washington, Seattle, $500,000.
</TEXT>
