<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-88 1921EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Nobel-Researchers     10-17 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nobel-Researchers,0531</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nobel Winners Say Helping the Sick is Their Reward</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RESEARCH TRIANGLE PARK, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two North Carolina
researchers who won the Nobel prize for medicine Monday said the
best reward for their work was seeing people overcome disease with
the medicines they developed.
   ``There's nothing that gives you a lift like seeing somebody get
better from a serious disease,'' said biochemist Gertrude B. Elion.
``The Nobel is something that is going to disappear in a few days.
But the other (seeing patients recover) is permanent.
   ``Not taking anything away from the Nobel prize, but the prize
is recognition, not reward,'' she said. ``The reward is seeing the
improvement your work makes.''
   ``I'm pleased more for my descendants than I am for myself,''
said George H. Hitchings, a colleague of Ms. Elion's at Wellcome
Research Laboratories Inc. ``I've had a lot of honors, but the most
important honors for me have been meeting patients whose lives have
been saved or whose children's lives have been saved by drugs I've
invented.''
   Hitchings, 83, and Ms. Elion, 70, began collaborating 44 years
ago, and have developed drugs for use against leukemia, malaria,
gout, organ transplant rejection, herpes virus infections and
bacterial infections. Both carry the title scientist emeritus and
are officially retired but come to the lab daily.
   The Nobel Assembly at Karolinska Institute said their ideas also
paved the way for development of azidothymidine, or AZT, which is
the best documented drug so far in the treatment of acquired immune
deficiency syndrome and the only one approved for use in the United
States.
   The two North Carolina scientists share the $390,000 prize with
Sir James W. Black of King's College Hospital Medical School in
London. His research led to a beta blocker drug for heart disease
and a drug for peptic ulcers.
   Ms. Elion said she had not known she had been nominated for the
prize and had never seriously considered that she might win it.
   ``The only people who thought I might get it was my family,''
she said. ``When I got the first call from a reporter about 6:30
a.m., I told him I thought it was a practical joke and not a very
funny one.''
   Although she officially retired five years ago, she makes daily
trips to Burroughs Wellcome to consult with other researchers.
   ``What's the use of retiring?'' she said. ``If you don't have
anything to contribute anymore, people will tell you. But as long
as you can make a contribution, you should.''
   Ms. Elion has worked at Wellcome Research Laboratories since
1944 and as a senior research chemist since 1950. Since 1983, she
has been a scientist emeritus at the laboratory and a research
professor of pharmacology at Duke University.
   Hitchings, after teaching at Harvard and Western Reserve
University, joined Burroughs Wellcome in 1942. He became its
research director in 1955 and retired in 1975 as vice president for
research. He was a director of the company from 1968 to 1984 and is
president of the Burroughs Wellcome Fund, a non-profit organization
that supports academic research.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
