<DOCNO> AP881017-0158 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-88 1927EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Children'sHome     10-17 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Children's Home,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bethel Home Open, but Pastor Could Face Assault Charges</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Christian Center Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY EYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bethel Home for Children is back in
business as a religious boarding school for troubled youths, four
months after the state tried to take custody of its students
because of reports of abuse.
   Some of the children who had been under the care of the Rev.
Herman Fountain, a former heroin addict turned independent Baptist
pastor, have returned since the June confrontations, and a few new
students have enrolled.
   Religious boarding homes aren't regulated under Mississippi law,
but several lawmakers concerned about schools like Fountain's say
they'll offer various licensing and registration bills when the
Legislature convenes in January.
   No charges have been filed against anyone at Bethel in
connection with the allegations of abuse and neglect. However,
several children's testimony of abusive practices resulted in their
removal from Fountain's custody.
   Next week, a grand jury will consider whether to charge Fountain
with assaulting law officers when they stormed his church and took
custody of some of his students.
   A girl answering the telephone Monday at the Bethel Home for
Children said Fountain was out working and unavailable for comment.
   Fountain has claimed his right to freedom of religion exempts
him from any state oversight, and says there's nothing wrong with
his ``spare the rod, spoil the child'' view of discipline.
   However, state welfare officers were ordered June 10 to take
custody of the residents of Fountain's home and school, on a
28-acre compound outhside the southern Mississippi town of
Lucedale. The order came from a Youth Court judge looking into
several allegations of beatings and other abuse.
   Some state officials say Fountain told the children to flee
before welfare officers arrived; he denies this. However, many of
the youths _ there were up to 120 at Bethel, according to Fountain
_ took off, and law officers spent several days rounding them up
from the streets.
   Fountain says 50 troubled youths have never been accounted for
and he fears they are roaming the streets as prostitutes or drug
dealers.
   On June 13, law officers stormed Fountain's locked church to
take custody of some of the children who had fled three days
before. Several witnesses, including members of the news media, saw
Fountain swing at officers during the incident.
   A Circuit Court grand jury will consider whether to bring three
counts of felony assault on a law officer against Fountain. The
pastor has been free on bond pending the grand jury session.
   He has appealed a separate disorderly conduct conviction in
Justice Court, for which he was fined $200.
   A civil contempt hearing involving Fountain's refusal to give
Youth Court authorities a list of names of children who had lived
at his home is set for Oct. 25 in Chancery Court at Lucedale, a
clerk said.
</TEXT>
