<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CatholicComa     10-17 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Catholic Coma,0449</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Rules Comatose Patient May Have Feeding Tubes
Removed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A comatose woman has a constitutional
right to have her feeding tubes removed, despite objections by a
state attorney that she would starve to death, a federal judge
ruled Monday.
   An individual has a constitutional right to control fundamental
medical decisions affecting one's own body, even if that will
result in death, U.S. District Judge Francis J. Boyle said.
   ``Medical ethics incorporates the principle that the patient,
not the health care provider, determines what the course of care
should be,'' the judge said.
   Marcia Gray, 49, has been in a coma since Jan. 4, 1986, when a
blood vessel burst in her brain. She had told her husband and
relatives on several occasions that, if stricken, she would not
want to be kept alive by artificial means, Boyle's opinion noted.
   Although she breathes on her own, doctors agree she suffered
massive brain damage and is in a ``persistent vegetative state,''
Boyle's decision said.
   The case attracted national attention last year when Bishop
Louis E. Gelineau of the Roman Catholic Diocese of Providence
approved a theologian's opinion that it was morally permissible to
withdraw Mrs. Gray's nourishment. That opinion, which has been
criticized by other moral theologians, said Mrs. Gray's feeding was
``circumventing'' the dying process.
   Her husband and guardian, H. Glenn Gray, asked to have her
feeding tube removed in March 1987. Officials of Rhode Island
Medical Center General Hospital, which is run by the Department of
Mental Health, Retardation and Hospitals, refused, setting up the
state's first legal test of a patient's right to die.
   Mrs. Gray has a constitutional right to privacy, and ``the right
to protect one's bodily integrity,'' Linda A. MacDonald, attorney
for the Gray family, argued at a June hearing.
   John L.P. Breguet, the state's attorney, argued that no federal
constitutional issues were involved and, even if they were,
implementation of those standards was ``really up to the individual
states to decide.''
   Boyle said an argument by Breguet that Mrs. Gray would suffer a
painful death was ``hollow in light of the medical testimony that
Marcia Gray is incapable of suffering any sensation, including
pain.''
   Boyle ruled that if Mrs. Gray cannot be promptly transferred to
a health care facility that will respect her wishes, General
Hospital must remove the feeding tubes.
   General Hospital will try to find another facility to accept
Mrs. Gray, and failing that, will consider appealing the decision,
Breguet said Monday after speaking with MHRH Director Thomas D.
Romeo, who was the defendant in the lawsuit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
