<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Iran-Iraq     10-17 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Iraq,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Accepts U.N. Compromise in Peace Plan, But With Condition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's foreign minister said Monday his
country would accept a United Nations formula for implementing a
peace pact in its 8-year war with Iraq but on one condition, the
official Iranian news agency reported.
   The report by the Islamic Republic News Agency quoted Foreign
Minister Ali Akhbar Velayati as saying the condition is that a 1975
accord that placed the southern border between the two countries as
running through the middle of the Shatt al-Arab waterway be
maintained.
   The dispatch, monitored in Nicosia, said U.N. Secretary-General
Javier Perez de Cuellar proposed the compromise plan and listed its
four points as: withdrawal of all forces to international
boundaries; agreement not to search ships in the Persian Gulf;
exchange of prisoners of war, and dredging of the Shatt al-Arab.
   The dispute over the estuary, which is Iraq's only waterway
access to the gulf, was a key issue in the war.
   Peace talks that started Aug. 25 stalled quickly over Iraq's
insistence that the Shatt al-Arab be dredged. Iran claimed that was
a secondary issue that could be settled later.
   Peace negotiations are scheduled to resume later this month in
Geneva.
   There was no immediate reaction from Iraq to the Iranian
announcement, but Iraq rejected the 1975 treaty years ago. Iran
insists that the pact, known as the Algiers Treaty, is valid.
   Iraqi President Saddam Hussein tore up a copy of the 1975 treaty
in a televised broadcast five days before his troops invaded Iran
in September 1980.
   Velayati was quoted as saying Monday that ``future peace talks
in Geneva will be fruitful if Iraq relents its current obstinacy
and is ready to cooperate for the implementation of the U.N.
chief's plan.''
   The agency said Velayati made the comments at a news conference
at the Foreign Ministry.
   It reported Velayati also made these statement on other matters:
   _Iran will not change its policy toward the United States as
long as Washington continues its ``hostile behavior'' toward Iran.
   _Talks with Britain about restoring relations were continuing
and ``cannot be said to have reached a deadlock.''
   _``Some difficulties'' exist in relations with Saudi Arabia,
which in April severed diplomatic relations with Iran, accusing it
of supporting terrorists.
</TEXT>
