<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Nancy-Wardrobe 2ndLd-Writethru a0747 10-17 0947</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nancy-Wardrobe, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0747,890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Lady Borrowed and Returned Gowns, Press Secretary Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: New lead to UPDATE with press secretary and ethics office
agreeing that no apparel transactions needed to be reported;
INSERTS grafs 5-7, ``Mrs. Reagan'' to show first lady's regrets,
minor editing to trim</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First Lady Nancy Reagan expressed regret
Monday that she failed to heed the advice of White House lawyers
that she formally disclose her borrowing of gowns and other
designer apparel. But her press secretary and a government ethics
spokesman said there was no legal requirement that she do so.
   Press Secetary Elaine Crispen acknowledged that Mrs. Reagan had
reported such loans when the issue first arose in November 1981,
saying the first lady then decided ``to err on the side'' of
compliance with the law.
   Since 1982, Mrs. Reagan has continued to borrow and return items
without reporting the transactions, Mrs. Crispen said, even though
White House lawyers originally had recommended disclosure as a
precautionary measure.
   ``Mrs. Reagan regrets that she failed to heed counsel's
advice,'' Mrs. Crispen said in a formal statement late Monday.
``Nevetheless, no reporting rules or laws were violated.''
   A spokesman for the Office of Government Ethics confirmed that
the office had supported a conclusion of then-White House Counsel
Fred Fielding in 1982 that such reporting was not required under
the Ethics in Government Act of 1978.
   ``The apparel Mrs. Reagan received was either paid for, given to
her personally as gifts by old friends and not subject to
reporting, or loaned to her and returned. All reporting
requirements were met,'' the statement released by Mrs. Crispen
said.
   Donald Campbell, a spokesman for the ethics office, said
officials there agreed with Fielding's contention that no reporting
was required under the act _ and said that Mrs. Reagan has been
operating under that guidance since that time.
   Campbell said officials in the federal ethics office had
received a letter from Fielding in which ``he laid out the fact
that the first lady had borrowed certain gowns for certain events
and, in his opinion, that was not something that needed to be
reported.''
   Campbell said that J. Jackson Walters, then the director of the
federal ethics office, agreed with Fielding's conclusion.
   But he also said in a telephone interview that ``since the
question has been raised, we will look at it again, to see if we
made the right decision.''
   Mrs. Reagan is not considered an official or employee of the
U.S. government, and is therefore not required to file her own
disclosure form _ as the president must do on an annual basis. She
did make the initial disclosures of clothes transactions on her
husband's disclosure form covering 1981 in what Campbell described
as ``an abundance of caution.''
   The issue was raised anew by the current issue of Time magazine.
It said that Mrs. Reagan has continued to accept and to wear
expensive evening gowns and other outfits, furnished by leading
couturiers such as James Galanos and David Hayes, without reporting
the practice.
   ``There are no taxpayers' dollars that go toward the first
lady's wardrobe whatsoever,'' Mrs. Crispen said in a telephone
interview. The spokeswoman said she thought the story was unmerited.
   ``I think she (Mrs. Reagan) has made Americans so proud'' of the
way she has represented them at official events, the press
secretary said. ``For any first lady, there have been mounds of
things that you have to go to, and you have to borrow, and it's not
illegal.''
   Mrs. Crispen said ``there have been things that have been
borrowed since 1982 _ and they were returned.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater described Reagan as
``upset over these attacks'' on the first lady. He said that no
internal review had been commenced in the wake of the Time report,
saying ``I don't know that there needs to be one.''
   The Time magazine article included pictures of Mrs. Reagan
posing with, among others, French President Francois Mitterrand and
Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney, and wearing expensive
gowns. The article said she borrowed gowns ranging in value to as
high as $22,000 for one such outfit.
   Mrs. Reagan's spokeswoman denied that the first lady had kept
any of the numerous dresses and outfits loaned to her by designers.
   ``To a typical woman, there are some gowns that are so
spectacular that you would only wear it once,'' she said.
   Los Angeles designer David Hayes said Mrs. Reagan has borrowed
60 to 80 made-to-order outfits during the past eight years. She
returned more than half and kept the others, he was quoted as
saying in the Time article.
   ``We think of it as loans. It's wonderful,'' Hayes said. ``She
has been a sensation for my business.''
   An unidentified executive at Harry Winston jewelers in New York
City told Time that Mrs. Reagan continued to borrow expensive
accessories, including a pair of diamond earrings worth $800,000.
   Mrs. Crispen said the first lady on two occasions borrowed
jewelry from Harry Winston jewelers _ for the 1981 presidential
inaugural and for the wedding of Prince Charles and Lady Diana
later that year. But the spokeswoman placed no value on the
merchandise.
   Chris Blazakis, who worked with designer Galanos and is writing
a book about the Reagans, said he has identified more than 300
photographs since 1982 showing Mrs. Reagan wearing outfits he
estimates are worth a total of more than $1 million retail.
   Reagan's presidential salary is $200,000 a year, and his 1987
tax form disclosed modest income that Mrs. Reagan had received in
talent fees and residuals from appearances on network television
shows, but no information about her clothing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
