<DOCNO> AP881017-0168 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-88 2030EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ReporterAccess     10-17 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reporter Access,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group Seeks Apology For Female Reporter Denied Access To Athletes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vanderbilt University's athletic director
should apologize to a female reporter who was denied access to
athletes after a football game, the American Society of Newspaper
Editors said Monday.
   In a letter to university Chancellor Joe B. Wyatt, the newspaper
group said reporter Karen Rosen, of the Atlanta Journal and
Constitution, had asked to interview two football players who were
available to male reporters in the locker room after the
Vanderbilt-Georgia game on Oct. 8.
   The request was ``either not relayed or ignored,'' said Jean H.
Otto, chairman of the ASNE Press, Bar and Public Affairs Committee,
noting that Ms. Rosen had not asked to enter the locker room.
   ``For any reporter to be denied reasonable access to events or
people who are available to other reporters is unacceptable in that
it limits access by the public,'' Otto said in the letter.
   Otto noted that Wyatt had apologized for the incident and had
promised it would not happen again. But the ASNE official said
Athletic Director Roy Kramer had not apologized, adding, ``Until
that is forthcoming, this incident cannot be considered closed.''
   ASNE asked Wyatt to seek an apology for Ms. Rosen from Kramer
and any other university official involved in the incident, and to
devise a rule to guarantee equal access to all reporters covering
sports in the future.
</TEXT>
