<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     10-17 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Hit Middle Mississipi Valley</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Severe thunderstorms raked Missouri and Illinois with hail and
strong winds Monday, cloudy skies prevailed in the Northeast and
sunny skies warmed the southern and far western portions of the
nation.
   Two schools and a factory near Peoria, Ill., were evacuated as
the storm battered the area, downing trees and power lines. No
injuries were reported.
   In the central Illinois community of Colfax, hail the size of
golfballs fell during the thunderstorm. The storms produced large
hail and damaging winds in Woodford County. The St. Louis area had
small hail and strong winds.
   Over an inch of rain fell at O'Hare International Airport in
Chicago.
   The thunderstorms developed near a warm front in an area of
abundant low-level moisture and strong winds in the upper
atmosphere.
   Rain also fell Monday in Minnesota, Wyoming, Nebraska, northern
Idaho and over the northern Rockies.
   Rainfall during the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT included 0.63
inches in St. Louis; 0.41 inches in Houlton, Maine; and 0.35 inches
at O'Hare.
   Afternoon temperatures Monday were in the 70s and 80s from the
south Atlantic and Gulf coastal states to the southern Plains and
as far north as Missouri and southern Kansas. Temperatures reached
the 90s in parts of Texas.
   San Francisco had 92 degrees, and Redding, Calif., had 94, both
records for the date.
   Temperatures were in the 40s and 50s from Michigan across the
upper Mississippi Valley and northern Plains into the northern
Rockies.
   Record high temperatures were recorded in Lubbock, Texas, 92;
Roswell, N.M., 90; and Wichita, Kan., 87.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 42
degrees at Duluth, Minn., and Hibbing, Minn., to 98 degress at Palm
Springs, Calif. The nation's low Monday morning was 17 degrees at
Gunnison, Colo.
   The forecast for Tuesday called for showers and thunderstorms
from New England to the Ohio Valley and mid Atlantic coastal
states. Some rain was expected to develop along the Washington and
Oregon coasts.
   High temperatures were expected in the 80s from the south
Atlantic and Gulf coastal states across the lower Mississippi
Valley to Texas, with a few readings near 90 degrees in Texas.
Temperatures were predicted in the 80s and 90s over the desert
Southwest and interior valleys of California. High temperatures
were to be in the 50s from Washington state across Montana, the
Dakotas and the upper Mississippi Valley to the Great Lakes region
with some 40s over northern Michigan and northern Minnesota.
Afternoon highs were to be in the 60s and 70s elsewhere across the
nation.
</TEXT>
