<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Philippines-Bases     10-17 0566</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-Bases,0580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Complain Philippines Settled for Too Little</HEAD>
<HEAD>with AM-US-Philippines, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers complained Monday that the
Philippines settled for too little in a pact on U.S. military bases
and warned the terms could boost those who want the facilities
closed when the lease expires.
   President Corazon Aquino urged the public to wait for more
details before judging the new agreement, which was signed Monday
afternoon in Washington by Secretary of State George Shultz and the
Philippines' Foreign Secretary Raul Manglapus.
   The pact sets the terms for the remaining two years of the U.S.
lease on the bases, which expires in 1991. Under the terms, the
Philippines will get $962 million in U.S. aid in exchange for use
of the bases.
   The negotiations were technically a review of an existing bases
agreement that the Aquino government never hinted at canceling. But
tension between the United States and its former colony were high
because of bargaining over the aid package as well as nuclear and
other issues.
   Opposition Sen. Juan Ponce Enrile said Monday the upper chamber
should have the chance to ratify the agreement as if it were a
treaty because ``there are rights and obligations growing from it.''
   He cited a constitutional provision which says no treaty or
international agreement shall be valid without the concurrence of
two-thirds of the Senate. The Aquino administration has not
indicated that the agreement needs Senate approval.
   Sen. Ernesto Maceda, chairman of the Senate Defense Committee,
said the accord showed that ``it seems this administration is not
ready yet to stand up to Washington.
   ``A publicly unacceptable compensation package certainly
strengthens the hands of those who are batting for no extension (of
the bases lease) after 1991,'' Maceda said.
   Philippine sources have said that Manglapus, head of the
Philippine negotiating panel, originally asked for $1.2 billion a
year for use of the two largest U.S. bases abroad _ the Clark Air
Base and the Subic Navy Base _ and four smaller installations.
   Mrs. Aquino refused to comment on the agreement, saying only:
``Why don't we just wait until all the details are laid out and
expressed by Secretary Manglapus.''
   She has not said whether she will support extending the
agreement after 1991, one year before her term ends. The
Constitution requires that any extension be approved by two-thirds
of the 23-member Senate, where anti-bases sentiment is strong.
   Rep. Gualberto Lumauig of the lower chamber's Foreign Relations
Committee, termed the agreement ``welcome news'' because it would
mean more money for the country's debt-strapped economy.
   The agreement represents an increase of $258 million in economic
and military aid as part of a complicated arrangement that permits
the Philippines to use a ``substantial portion'' to reduce its debt
and bars American soldiers who test positive for AIDS from serving
in the country.
   But Sen. Wigberto Tanada, a leading opponent of the bases and
chief sponsor of the senate's anti-nuclear weapons bill, said
financial compensation was not the only issue.
   ``I don't think it is enough to settle the issue of compensation
if the threat of national destruction due to nuclear weapons and
the derogation of national sovereignty is still there,'' he said.
   Left-wing groups pressing for the dismantling of U.S. facilities
branded the agreement a ``sell-out'' and said Manglapus should not
have linked continued U.S. presence here to the debt issue.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881017-0174 </DOCNO>
