<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-USDues     10-17 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-US Dues,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Officials Say U.S. Still Will Withhold Some Dues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States will continue
withholding some of its dues to the United Nations despite
President Reagan's pledge last month that they would be paid, U.N.
officials said Monday.
   The officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Washington would retain $59 million in dues to force the United
Nations to adopt an austerity budget.
   U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said the withholding of funds will
endanger U.N. peacekeeping projects, such as military observers in
Iran and Iraq and possible future missions to South-West Africa and
other areas.
   Reagan told the General Assembly on Sept. 13 that he would
release the $188 million in dues owed for last year and this year
and added he was satisfied with the organization's progress on
budgetary and administrative reforms.
   The $188 million is $44 million from the previous fiscal year
and $144 million for the current fiscal year.
   Washington paid $15 million in September and on Friday it gave
the United Nations $85.6 million.
   That still leaves more than $$87 million from the $188 million
owed. Reagan had said the full amount would be paid by the end of
the year.
   But the U.N. officials said Washington informed U.N.
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar that $59 million would be
frozen until the General Assembly's main financial committee, the
Fifth Committee, adopts an austerity budget recommended last month
by a subcommittee.
   Even if the United States pays all $188 million it will still
owe millions more to the world organization in funds withheld
during earlier years.
   Friday's payment reduced the U.S. arrears to the regular budget
to $366.3 million. And U.N. officials estimate America owes about
$300 million more for unpaid assessments for other projects
including peacekeeping forces and payments to U.N. special agencies.
   Reagan last month pledged a ``multi-year'' payment plan for all
the back dues. U.N. Undersecretary-General Joseph V. Reed has said
the State Department told him the payments would be on a
three-to-five-year plan.
   Since Reagan took office nearly eight years ago his
administration has harshly criticized the United Nation, accusing
it of having an anti-Western bias and of bureaucracy and waste.
   The United States is assessed one-fourth of the U.N.'s regular
budget, and was supposed to pay $212 million this fiscal year but
Congress only appropriated $144 million.
   U.N. officials have said that continued withholding of funds
could force the world body to close in November.
   The United Nations has no reserve funds and operates by spending
dues it collects almost as soon as it receives them.
   Eckhard said so far the United Nations has collected only a
fraction of the $35.7 million it assessed its members for the first
three month of operations of the Iran-Iraq Military Observer Group.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
