<1ST_LINE>u w AM-LibelChanges 1stLd-Writethru a0759 10-17 0821</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Libel Changes, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0759,780</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 16th graf pvs, bgng: ``In a ...'' to CORRECT spelling of
Friedheim.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Lawyers React Cautiously To Proposed Changes In Libel Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libel lawyers reacted cautiously Monday to a
proposal for sweeping changes in libel law, predicting it could
lead to many frivolous suits and saying they doubted such a plan
would be politically appealing.
   The proposal is designed to resolve disputes quickly with a
focus on deciding the truth of disputed statements, rather than on
the awarding of damages. The centerpiece of the proposal is the
``no fault'' trial where no damages would be awarded, only court
fees paid by the loser.
   While the media would get relief from the prospect of huge
damage awards, they also would give up protections that have
restricted libel rulings.
   Although many libel lawyers and media representatives were
reluctant to embrace the proposal in its entirety, they said they
were encouraged that a panel of 11 lawyers, judges, journalists and
others of diverse backgrounds and philosophies could find consensus
on the thorny issue of libel.
   ``There are a lot of aspects the media side would find
favorable, and I'm impressed that they could bring together both
sides and get them to agree'' on a package of proposed reforms,
said Henry R. Kaufman, a New York libel lawyer who also is general
counsel of the Libel Research Defense Center.
   ``But this doesn't break totally new ground. Some of these
proposals have been aired before ... and we know what the reactions
are likely to be,'' he said. ``On both sides there would be some
serious reservations.''
   The study panel was put together by the Annenberg Washington
Program of Northwestern University in Evanston, Ill.
   The panel's proposal breaks libel action into three stages. In
the first, the emphasis is on retraction and replies. If a
newspaper or broadcast station agrees to print or air a retraction
or a reply by the person complaining about news coverage of them,
then the case is settled and a lawsuit cannot be filed.
   If there is no retraction or reply, either side can demand that
a lawsuit be tried for ``declaratory judgment,'' with the loser
paying the legal costs of the winner. Such trials would have to
begin within 120 days. The only issue would be the truth _
regardless of intent or negligence _ and no damages would be
awarded.
   If neither side wants a declaratory judgment, then a lawsuit for
libel would proceed along a path similar to the current one, except
that damages would be limited to the plaintiff's actual loss _
punitive damages would not be awarded. Also, no one could sue over
statements of opinion, such as an editorial cartoon. Only facts
would be considered, and at this stage, each side would have to pay
their own legal fees.
   Kaufman said the Libel Research Defense Center, which represents
the media in libel cases, does not take positions on such matters.
But, speaking as a libel lawyer, he said neither libel plaintiffs
nor the media are likely to work aggressively to push such a
proposal through.
   ``I have no reason to think plaintiffs' lawyers would be
supportive of something that removes from them the possibility of a
pot of gold at the end of the libel rainbow,'' he said.
   The media's reluctance revolves around the proposed change that
would eliminate the requirement that public figures suing for libel
prove that defamatory statements about them were published with
``actual malice,'' meaning with the knowledge that they were false,
or with ``reckless disregard'' of whether they were false.
   ``If I were a publisher, I wouldn't willingly trade
constitutional protections for the illusion of some kind of an
expedited low-cost, dispute-resolution process,'' said libel lawyer
Richard N. Winfield with the firm Rogers & Wells. ``I wouldn't give
up constitutional protections lightly.''
   The American Newspaper Publishers Association declined to
embrace the proposal, but said ``It deserves careful review.''
   In a statement, ANPA President Jerry W. Friedheim said, ``The
search for the best way to resolve disputes between the news media
and people who believe they have been wronged in news coverage is
well worth continuing.''
   Attorney Floyd Abrams, a noted constitutional lawyer, said that
while he would like to see libel reforms, any proposal as sweeping
as the Annenberg one should be tested in a small area before it is
put into practice on a large scale.
   ``The main danger of the proposal is that it could lead to an
explosion of new libel litigation in which people seek declarations
that something that was said about them was not true,'' he said.
   Abrams also was skeptical about the chances for getting such a
proposal implemented.
   ``I think it will probably take some new disastrous libel case
before we have any major structural change, some enormous verdict
in some highly publicized case,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
