<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SouthAfrica-Press     10-17 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa-Press,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Group Protests South African Warning Against Newspaper</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Society of Newspaper Editors on
Monday criticized the South African government for ``consistent and
arbitrary'' censorship of the press in that country.
   The ASNE, in a letter to South African President P.W. Botha,
expressed ``urgent concern'' over a warning issued to the Weekly
Mail by Stoffel Botha, minister of Home Affairs and Communications.
   The action ``reinforces the fear we expressed in our last
communication that it is the intention of the government to
cripple, one by one, any inconvenient publication,'' Bill Kovach,
chairman of the ASNE International Communication Committee, said in
the letter.
   ``Censorship for whatever reason is repugnant to any people, but
it is especially so to those who profess to have some voice in
governing themselves,'' said Kovach, editor of the Atlanta Journal
and Constitution.
   ``At this most critical time in the spread of the notion of a
free press in the world it is especially deplorable that the
government of South Africa chooses to continue its course down the
road of darkness and fear,'' Kovach wrote.
   He urged the South African government not to take further steps
against the Weekly Mail and to restore the right to publish to
other publications that have been shut down.
