<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bentsen 1stLd-Writethru a0685 10-17 0710</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0685,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Hunts For Reagan Democrats Down South</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 6 grafs after 6th graf pvs, `The Texas senator,' to
UPDATE with Bentsen appearance in San Diego, comments to crowd.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEXARKANA, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, stalking Reagan
Democrats on the Texas-Arkansas border, scoffed Monday at
Republican charges that Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis favors
harsh gun controls and would weaken the military.
   ``I saw those ads about Mike Dukakis going to take the guns away
from you, confiscate the guns, not even pay for them.'' Bentsen
told 200 supporters at an airport rally during a refueling stop on
his way to California.
   ``Let me tell you, a fella like Lloyd Bentsen likes to go quail
hunting like I do,'' said the Democratic vice presidential
candidate. ``(I) sure wouldn't be running with any fella if I
thought he was going to take my shotgun away from me, no way.''
   While Dukakis does support gun control, Bentsen said, he
believes sportsmen should have guns and people have the right to
defend their homes. He said GOP nominee George Bush was ``the only
one of the four candidate who has voted for national gun control''
as a congressman in 1968.
   Bentsen said it was untrue that the Democrats wanted to cut
defense spending. He scorned Republican commercials on the defense
issue featuring former test pilot Chuck Yeager.
   The Texas senator said Yeager should return to writing books and
lobbying for a defense contractor, and stay out of politics.
   Later in California, Bentsen told a crowd of several thousand
students at the University of California at San Diego that the
Republicans were squandering America's technological future.
   In 1980, he said, 60 percent of color televisions sold in
America were made in the United States. Today, less than 10 percent
are, and the United States makes no video cassette recorders,
compact disc players or fax machines.
   He also decried what he said were Republican distortions of
Dukakis' record, invoking, as he did over the weekend, the image of
Harry Truman's come-from-behind campaign.
   ``It was Harry Truman who said that you have to appeal to the
best instincts of people, not to their worst,'' he told the crowd,
few of whom were born when Truman was in the White House.
``Sometimes you can win a few elections that way, but you really
hurt your country.''
   ``Well, some of you recall when Harry Truman ran for
re-election, he had a very arrogant opponent that knew he'd won
it,'' Bentsen said referring to Thomas E. Dewey. ``But the people
kept yelling to Harry, `Harry, give `em hell.' But Harry would say,
`I just tell the truth and the Republicans think it's hell.'
   ``Well, Mike Dukakis and Lloyd Bentsen are offering the truth,''
he said.
   Bentsen's Texarkana stopover was aimed at both East Texas and
Arkansas, which are strong in loyal Democrats but where the party
has been struggling to reverse its sagging fortunes in the
Bush-Dukakis presidential race.
   Bentsen has refused to concede Texas, although the Democratic
ticket is more than 10 points behind Bush and running mate Dan
Quayle in some polls. The contest is closer in Arkansas but the
Democrats have suffered there.
   Rep. Tommy Robinson, D-Ark., said last week that Dukakis was
``not welcome'' in his district.
   Rep. Bill Alexander, D-Ark., rode to Texarkana with Bentsen on
the campaign jet and told reporters that his state was still there
for Dukakis to win if he improves his organization and his message.
   Alexander said favorite Dukakis-Bentsen topics such as world
trade are too esoteric for many Arkansas voters.
   So far, Alexander said, the Massachusetts governor has proved to
be a disappointing campaigner who is unwilling to exploit issues
where Republicans are vulnerable, such as the war on drugs.
   ``He's got to show some passion, commitment, leadership,''
Alexander said. ``He may have made an A-plus in political science,
but so far he hasn't passed politics.''
   ``He could capture the hearts and minds of the people of the
South in the next three weeks if he'd come out swinging,'' he said.
``He can do it. ... Someone's gotta get him off in the corner, grab
him and tell him what to do.''
</TEXT>
