<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru   10-17 0724</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0783,0745</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peres Promises Palestinian Elections; 16 Shot In Clashes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-4 UPDATE with two soldiers injured by firebombs.
Pick up 4th graf pvs, It was ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Labor Party leader Shimon Peres said
Monday that if he is elected prime minister in Nov. 1 elections,
Palestinians in the occupied territories will elect delegates to
peace talks with Israel.
   Peres spoke on a day when 16 Palestinians were reported shot in
clashes with troops in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Also Monday, two Israeli soldiers were wounded, one seriously,
apparently from a Palestinian firebomb attack, an army spokesman
said. He said the circumstances of the incident in the West Bank
village of Azzun were unclear and still under investigation.
   A home-made bomb was thrown on Monday at police guarding the
home of former Defense Minister Ariel Sharon in the Moslem sector
of the walled Old City, police said. They said no injury or damage
resulted and that the attacker escaped despite police gunfire.
   It was the second unsuccessful attack on the house in less than
a month.
   Sharon, now industry minister, was away, on a private visit to
Hungary.
   Peres said balloting in the territories would be held only if
calm is restored.
   ``If the violence is restrained, we will hold free elections in
Judea, Samaria and Gaza so that a Palestinian ... delegation can be
elected to represent the Palestinian side in negotiations,'' Peres
said, using the biblical names for the West Bank.
   The suggestion was rejected by several Palestinian leaders,
including Israeli-deposed Hebron Mayor Mustafa Natsche. He told The
Associated Press that before any elections, ``Israel must recognize
our right to self-determination and our right to choose our own
representatives.''
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, whose hard-line Likud bloc is
Labor's main opponent, said ``nothing will remain'' of Palestinian
protesters if they carry out threats to use weapons against Israel.
   Likud opposes giving back any of the territories occupied by
Israel since the 1967 Middle East war. Labor favors trading some
land for peace.
   Polls say the two major parties are in a close race. Much of the
campaigning has centered on the Palestinian uprising, which has
claimed the lives of 299 Arabs and six Israelis since Dec. 8.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin, a Labor Party member who joined
Peres at a news conference to announce the peace talk election
proposal, said Palestinian representatives must be chosen ``from
residents of the territories, by residents of the territories.''
   Rabin said any resident of the territories could run in the
elections. But he said at least three months of calm would have to
precede the balloting.
   The last elections in the West Bank were mayoral elections in
1976 under a Labor administration. The elected officials supported
the Palestine Liberation Organization and refused to participate in
peace negotiations.
   Peres said that if formal peace negotiations fail, he would
transfer local and municipal affairs now handled by the army to
elected Palestinians.
   Peres continues to insist that Jordan be part of any peace talks
despite King Hussein's statement this summer that he was breaking
all links with the West Bank, which Jordan held from 1948 until
1967.
   Peres is trying to win the votes of Israeli Arabs, who comprise
17 percent of the electorate and traditionally split their votes
between Labor and the Communist Party.
   Avi Pazner, a spokesman for Shamir, criticized the Labor
proposal and said holding elections during the uprising would only
serve to give radicals the upper hand.
   Among the casualties Monday were four Palestinians in the Nablus
area, including a 13-year-old boy who was shot in the back after
youths hurled rocks at troops, an Arab reporter said.
   In the Gaza Strip, troops shot eight youths with plastic bullets
and wounded four with live ammunition during stone-throwing clashes
in four Palestinian refugee camps, Arab reports and hospital
officials said. One of the wounded was a 13-year-old boy hit in the
eye with a plastic bullet, the officials said.
   The army said it was checking the reports.
   Israel radio quoted an army medical officer as saying 575
soldiers and 321 Israeli civilians have been injured in the
uprising. Most were hit by stones.
   Israeli officials have said more than 7,000 Palestinians have
been injured in the revolt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
