<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Human Rights,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moscow to Be Site of East Bloc Human Rights Conference</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East bloc nations will hold a human rights
conference in Moscow on Nov. 21-25 as part of U.N.-sponsored
activities marking the 40th anniversary of the Universal
Declaration of Human Rights, Tass said Monday.
   The official Soviet news agency quoted Foreign Ministry
spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov as saying the seminar ``on human
rights and the administration of justice'' would be the first
organized by the United Nations with the participation of socialist
countries.
   Tass said the conference would be attended by prominent foreign
and Soviet specialists, including U.N. officials, representatives
of law enforcement institutions, legal scholars and public figures.
   Jan Maertenson, U.N. deputy director general and director of the
U.N. Center on Human Rights, will speak at the opening ceremony,
Tass said.
   The Soviet Union also has proposed holding an international
conference on human rights in Moscow, but the United States and
other Western countries have been cool to the idea.
   U.S. representatives have said they are seeking guarantees that
members of non-governmental groups will be allowed to attend, as
well as private foreign citizens who have grievances to air.
