<1ST_LINE>u p AM-SwindallIndictment 1stLd-Writethru a0738 10-17 0764</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Swindall Indictment, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0738,0782</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressman Swindall Indicted for Perjury</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with court appearance and
Swindall saying he would resign if convicted. Picks up 3rd graf
pvs, `His Democratic...'. SUBS grafs 14-15, `Barr said ... to him,'
with details from arraignment.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DICK PETTYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal grand jury indicted Rep. Pat Swindall
on perjury charges Monday, accusing the two-term Republican
congressman of lying during a money laundering investigation.
   Swindall, locked in what has been called one of the country's
dirtiest congressional re-election battles, pleaded innocent to all
counts during an afternoon arraignment and was free on his own
recognizance.
   He said he hoped to bring the case to trial next Monday in order
to clear his name by the Nov. 8 general election.
   ``When I am exonerated, obviously the only issue that remains is
whether the 4th District wants a Dukakis liberal or a Bush
conservative,'' he told reporters at U.S. District Court.
   Swindall said he would resign if he were convicted of the
charges, even though not required to by law. He said he expects to
serve a jail term if found guilty.
   He said he would step down ``because under the circumstances, I
don't think it would be fair to the voters of the 4th District'' to
remain in office.
   His Democratic opponent, former ``Dukes of Hazzard'' television
actor Ben Jones, commented, ``I feel concern for the congressman
and for his family at this point. ... It is a matter for the courts
to decide.''
   The 10-count indictment accused Swindall of lying to the grand
jury last Feb. 2 during its investigation of a proposed $850,000
home mortgage loan the congressman had discussed with an Atlanta
businessman and an undercover agent posing as a financier.
   Among other things, the indictment charged that Swindall lied
when he told the grand jury he did not go to authorities to report
the loan negotiations, because, he said, ``I never satisfied myself
of anything with respect to criminality.''
   The indictment also charged Swindall lied when he said there had
never been discussions about trying to conceal the trail of the
money, and that he lied when he denied having been specifically
informed by the undercover agent that the source of the loan could
be illicit drug money.
   U.S. Attorney Robert Barr said that if convicted, Swindall could
be sentenced to five years in prison and fined $10,000 on each
count.
   Swindall, who had been notified of the pending indictment in
advance, announced Sunday night that he expected to be indicted and
said he was excited by the prospect because it would give him a
chance to clear his name.
   He said he would waive a number of rights, including the right
to charge the government with misconduct, so the case could go to
trial next Monday. Swindall said he would act as his own attorney.
   Swindall entered his innocent plea before U.S. Magistrate
William L. Harper, who then assigned the case to U.S. District
Judge Robert Vining.
   Vining had previously been scheduled to try Atlanta businessman
Charles LeChasney and a second person accused of money laundering
next Monday. Harper said there were indications LeChasney and the
second man might step aside and allow Swindall's case to be tried
ahead of their cases.
   Swindall, who defeated Jones in 1986, this year has made an
issue of Jones' arrest record, including a conviction for
assaulting his wife. Jones has said the incidents occurred during a
bout with alcoholism that ended in 1977.
   Jones, who starred as ``Cooter'' in the long-running television
series, ``The Dukes of Hazzard,'' once suggested that Swindall
submit to drug tests, insinuating the congressman's behavior was
unstable.
   The indictment stems from negotiations Swindall undertook last
year with LeChasney to finance a mortgage loan for his $1.2 million
home.
   LeChasney, who has since been indicted on money-laundering
charges, introduced Swindall to Michael Mullaney, an undercover
Internal Revenue Service agent posing as a money broker.
   In June, Atlanta newspapers obtained several secretly made
government tape recordings of conversations among Swindall,
LeChasney and the undercover agent.
   The tapes showed that Swindall continued to pursue negotiations
for an $850,000 loan after being told that the source might be drug
money he would be helping to launder.
   He accepted a $150,000 check as the first installment on the
loan, but returned it uncashed three days later, saying he was
suspicious of LeChasney's business dealings.
   Swindall has since apologized for his role in the negotiations,
calling it a mistake in judgment but insisting there was no
wrongdoing.
</TEXT>
