<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Teamsters-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0787 10-17 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teamsters-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0787,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teamsters Break With AFL-CIO Endorsement, Back Bush</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS lede and 5th graf to CORRECT spelling of Grenelefe.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRENELEFE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the Teamsters, the nation's
largest union, voted Monday to back George Bush for president,
breaking with the AFL-CIO's endorsement of Michael Dukakis.
   However, union President William J. McCarthy emphasized that the
endorsement applied only to Bush personally, not his running mate,
Dan Quayle, nor the Republican party.
   The action came after only 21,207 of the union's 1.7 million
members returned mail-in presidential ballots giving Bush a 50.2
percent to 46.4 percent margin over his Democratic rival, said
McCarthy.
   He said the union would have backed Dukakis if the membership
poll had gone the other way, but he applauded the decision to back
Bush.
   ``We feel he is more qualified and can do a greater job for this
country,'' McCarthy said after the union's 18-member board of
directors ratified the membership vote during a meeting at the
Grenelefe Resort. ``We feel we can get a fair shake from him.''
   Reacting to the snub while campaigning in Midland, Mich., Quayle
said, ``The important thing is that they endorsed George Bush and
that's good news for me.''
   ``It's going to be important to have their votes,'' Quayle said.
   The union president insisted that the poll was fair despite the
small number of voters, saying all members had the opportunity to
register their opinions.
   The Teamsters have not backed a Democrat for president since
Vice President Humbert H. Humphrey in 1968.
   But when the union rejoined the AFL-CIO a year ago following a
30-year absence, officials for both had anticipated the Teamsters
would go along with the federation's expected endorsement of the
Democratic nominee.
   The deal apparently fell through when McCarthy took over the
union following the death of Jackie Presser.
   The AFL-CIO announced its endorsement of Dukakis in August, and
the Teamsters were one of three unions that abstained while 88
unions supported it, 87 of them unanimously.
   Teamster officials said then they expected the union to make no
endorsement, a stand the Teamsters last took in 1976 when Jimmy
Carter defeated incumbent President Gerald Ford.
   McCarthy, who headed the Teamsters in New England before taking
over the union, had crossed swords with Dukakis in Massachusetts,
backing his electoral opponents there.
   But he denied Monday that the Bush endorsement was intended to
spite Dukakis.
   ``I have no opinion of him,'' McCarthy said of the governor.
   Union spokesman Duke Zeller said the vote indicated Teamsters
are satisfied with the economy because they ``are concerned with
such bread-and-butter issues as jobs.''
   The Teamsters endorsed Ronald Reagan in 1980 and 1984, but the
union had a falling out with the administration in 1986 over
Presser's indictment.
   When he died in July after a long bout with cancer and heart
disease, Presser was under indictment in Cleveland for allegedly
hiring ghost employees for the union.
   The union is also the target of a federal civil racketeering
suit that was filed June 28. That suit seeks to have Teamsters
officials who violated racketeering laws removed from office and
replaced with a trustee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
