<1ST_LINE>u p AM-NBC-JournalPoll 1stLd-Writethru a0771 10-17 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NBC-Journal Poll, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0771,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush up by 17 in NBC-Journal Poll</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 5-9 to give comments from Dukakis, Bentsen</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A national poll Monday said George Bush held a
17-point lead in the presidential race, garnering 55 percent
support among likely voters compared with 38 percent for Democrat
Michael Dukakis.
   Bush's lead in the NBC News-Wall Street Journal poll was his
greatest of the campaign and considerably greater than in surveys
earlier this month. It was the first full-sized poll conducted
after last week's debate.
   Bush led by 10 points in smaller, overnight polls done
immediately after Thursday's debate, but they were conducted only
among debate viewers, a more Republican group. He led by five or
six points in most pre-debate polls.
   In the NBC-Journal poll, conducted Friday through Sunday among
1,378 likely voters, almost three-quarters said they expected Bush
to win the election, including half of Dukakis' own supporters.
   Dukakis and campaign chairman Paul Brountas disputed the
figures, as did running mate Lloyd Bentsen.
   ``Now we've got a new set of numbers that has absolutely no
relationship to anything that we have or other polls have, so you
spend two or three days'' answering answering questions about it,
Dukakis said.
   ``If there has been an increase in the gap it may be
attributable to some of the stories about the debate,'' Brountas
said.
   ``I don't think it's accurate,'' said Bentsen. ``You see wide
fluctuations among those polls. That's what's happening.''
   Dukakis' campaign received two blows last week: A 50-state poll
by ABC News and the Washington Post said Bush had an overwhelming
lead in the race for electoral votes, and polls said Bush was seen
as the debate winner.
   Bush was favorably rated by 55 percent in the NBC-Journal poll,
up from 50 percent a month ago. Dukakis' favorability rating
dropped to 36 percent, down from 50 percent a month ago.
   Bush's advantage was chiefly among men: They backed him by a 2-1
margin, 64-30, while the race among women was a nearly even 48-44.
A gender gap has been apparent, to varying degrees, throughout the
campaign.
   The poll's margin of error was plus or minus three percentage
points.
</TEXT>
