<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Manou 1stLd-Writethru a0668 10-17 0180</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Manou, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0668,0182</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rallou Manou, Introduced Modern Dance to Greece</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to CORRECT to Ms. Manou on second reference.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Choreographer Rallou Manou, widely
recognized for introducing modern dance in Greece, has died of a
stroke at the age of 73.
   Ms. Manou, who directed the Hellenic Chorodrama that she helped
set up with leading Greek artists in 1951, died Saturday.
   The daughter of a wealthy Greek army officer, Ms. Manou studied
dance in West Germany before working under American modern dance
pioneer Martha Graham at New York University in the 1940s.
   Works presented by the Hellenic Chorodrama, of which Ms. Manou
was the principal choreographer, blended avant-garde dance forms
with classical drama.
   She insisted that the dance group, which performed each summer
in the open-air Lycabettus theater in Athens, be inspired by Greek
tradition.
   ``I don't think ballet is the kind, type or spirit of dance that
can best express Greece,'' she once said. ``Modern dance is the
best form and also the one which comes nearest to ancient Greek
dance.''
</TEXT>
