<DOCNO> AP881017-0194 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-88 2223EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 3rdLd-Writethru a0801 10-17 0930</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0801,900</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says Bush `Sat On His Hands' While Heartland Rusted</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 9th pvs, The governor's ..., to UPDATE
with remarks in Columbus.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis reached for the common touch
on Monday, visiting a metal factory, a diner and a bowling alley as
he tried to reinvigorate a faltering presidential campaign.
   ``I want to be a president who stands up and fights for American
companies, American products and American workers,'' Dukakis said,
depicting Republican rival George Bush as the candidate of
complacency.
   The Massachusetts governor embraced the role of underdog as
polls in Ohio and elsewhere showed him losing ground since last
week's presidential debate.
   An NBC Wall Street Journal poll reported Bush leading 55 percent
to 38 percent, but Dukakis disputed the fundings.
   ``Well I can only tell you that there are other polls that say
very different things about where we are and where the race is,''
Dukakis told an interviewer for a Chicago television station.
   Dukakis, in a series of interviews, described the race as ``very
tight'' and said, ``the business of polls is really having a
terrible effect'' on the campaign process.
   ``Now we've got a new set of numbers that has absolutely no
relationship to anything that we have or other polls have, so you
spend two or three days'' answering answering questions about it.
   He declined to say what his internal campaign polling shows.
   The governor's day was designed to counter criticism that he has
failed to connect emotionally with middle class voters,
particularly those in the industrial states.
   Dukakis ended his day more than 12 hours after he began at a
rally in Columbus attended by blacks and he took a veiled shot at
Bush. ``Something is very wrong when a presidential candidate calls
Jesse Helms a hero, and Jesse Jackson a hustler,'' he said. Bush
once used that term to describe Jackson in a newspaper interview.
   His first stop was a brass and copper factory in Euclid near
Cleveland, where he toured the plant wearing a jacket that bore two
pocket patches, one saying, ``Mike'' and the other ``Next
President.''
   Addressing workers at a factory-floor rally, he criticized Bush
for opposing increases in the minimum wage and for advocating a
trade policy that he said seemed like ``a re-run of Let's Make a
Deal.''
   He said Bush has ``sat on his hands while America's industrial
heartland has been fighting for its life.''
   Next was a brief visit to Shorty's diner in Cleveland, where he
joined a patron and his daughter at a booth. ``Let's kick some ass
out there,'' said the man, Tim LaChina. ``OK, very good, we'll do
it,'' said Dukakis.
   In Dayton, he went to a bowling alley for a meeting with
families, many of whom said they were worried about the threat of
drugs and concerned about meeting the costs of higher education.
   In his factory speech, he said Bush assures the voters
``everything's fine, not to worry. ...
   ``But his record sends a very different message. ... His record
tells America's industrial heartland, `Let it rust,''' Dukakis said.
   The Massachusetts governor told reporters, ``My spirits are
good'' as he set out on a campaign swing through industrial states.
And he twice took trumpet in hand to make a stab at a few bars of
``Happy Days Are Here Again.''
   But the political news for Dukakis was anything but happy as
newspaper polls in the wake of last week's presidential debate
indicated Bush holds a double-digit lead in Ohio. Dukakis is
expected to return two or three times before Election Day to the
state, one of several in the Northeast and Midwest that form the
core of his hopes for a come-from-behind victory in the race for
the White House.
   Dukakis has decided to campaign as the underdog he is for the
final three weeks of the campaign, and in his new campaign speech,
he said he is ``fighting for the values I believe in, the values
that are at the core of this campaign.''
   He said Bush has ``sat on his hands while America's heartland
has been fighting for its life'' and now won't be specific about
what he would do as president.
   ``Take trade, for example. ... Mr. Bush's trade policy is like a
re-run of `Let's Make A Deal.' Letting the voters guess what's
behind door No. 1, door No. 2 and door No. 3,'' Dukakis said.
   ``George Bush sat on the sidelines for eight years while America
got beaten in world markets ... while a piece of America was being
sold off every day at bargain-basement prices,'' he said.
   Dukakis said he would work hard to create good jobs at good
wages, adding, ``That's not just a slogan, that comes from the
gut.''
   Bush says he believes in the dignity of work, Dukakis noted. But
he said the vice president opposed legislation mandating a 60-day
notice to workers before their factory could be closed and voted
for a budget plan that would have frozen Social Security
cost-of-living increases.
   ``...Mr. Bush saw nothing, said nothing and did nothing while
his Republican colleagues in Congress used every trick in the book
to keep the minimum wage a poverty wage,'' of $3.35 an hour, he
said.
   Dukakis taunted Bush's oft-repeated declaration that he wants a
``kinder, gentler nation.''
   ``His record tells rural America, the fewer family farmers the
better. His record tells middle class families: `The glory days are
over. Your kids may not do as well as you.'''
</TEXT>
