<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BarricadedGunman 1stLd-Writethru a0773 10-17 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Barricaded Gunman, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0773,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Barricaded Gunman Kills Two Policemen</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with details of incident, identity of
second officer.
^By JIM IRWIN</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who barricaded himself in his apartment
building shot and killed two police officers Monday before he was
killed by police to end the nearly seven-hour siege, authorities
said.
   Relatives said the gunman, identified as Charles Knowles, was
distraught because he had been beaten and robbed Sunday night.
Police spokesman Fred Zaharoff said Knowles, 50, had a history of
mental instability.
   Police went to the three-story apartment building about 8 a.m.
after receiving reports that Knowles had threatened other tenants
and was pouring gasoline inside the building, said Zaharoff.
   Knowles fired through the door of his apartment about 9:30 a.m.,
striking Lt. James L. Schmit in the chest, Zaharoff said. Schmit
died at Samaritan Hospital after surgery for a chest wound,
hospital spokeswoman Kay LeMon said.
   Negotiations with Knowles continued while about 25 families in
and near the apartment building were kept from their homes,
Zaharoff said.
   ``Exhaustive attempts by police officers and members of the
Knowles family to talk him into surrendering were of no avail,''
the spokesman said. ``The decision to enter the dwelling was made
after considering the fact that Mr. Knowles had poured gasoline
through the apartment building which may have been ignited as
children were about to be dismissed from schools in the area.''
   The police's Special Response Unit forced their way into
Knowles's apartment about 2:05 p.m., Zaharoff said. Knowles fired
as they entered and struck Officer Frank E. Walls, who died about
30 minutes later at St. John Hospital, officials said.
   Other officers returned fire and killed Knowles instantly,
Zaharoff said.
   Schmit, 41, was a 20-year veteran, and Walls, 39, was a 13-year
veteran.
   The gunman's nephew, Rick Knowles, said his uncle was retired,
lived alone and had been a victim of other crimes in recent months.
   Charles Knowles's apartment had been burglarized several months
ago after police took him into custody, Rick Knowles said. The
nephew said he did not know what offense was involved in that
arrest but added that Charles Knowles had bought a rifle afterward.
   ``The police came in today, he probably said, `Leave me alone,'
'' Rick Knowles said. ``They tried to get in anyway, and he just
popped them.''
