<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Egypt     10-17 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Egypt,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Says Egypt Agreed To Delay Taba Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Egypt has agreed to postpone talks on the
future of the disputed Taba border area until after the Israeli
elections, Israel's Foreign Ministry said Monday.
   Egypt informed Israel of its decision through its ambassador in
Israel, Mohammed Bassiouny, and through the Israeli ambassador in
Cairo, Shimon Shamir, a ministry official said. He spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Israel radio said the decision followed U.S. pressure to delay
the negotiations until after Nov. 1 parliamentary elections in
Israel and the U.S. presidential elections Nov. 8.
   The radio said talks were expected to begin at the end of
November or the beginning of December.
   Israel captured Taba, a 250-acre Red Sea beachfront resort,
along with the Sinai desert from Egypt in the 1967 Middle East war
but did not return it when Israel returned Sinai to Egypt uder a
U.S.-mediated peace treaty.
   Last month, after more than 16 months of study, an international
panel of arbitrators ruled that Taba should be returned to Egypt.
The five-member panel awarded Egypt some key border points but said
it was not authorized to determine the final position of the border.
   In addition to demarcating the border, the ongoing
Israeli-Egyptian negotiations are supposed to determine the future
of the strip's popular Sonesta Hotel and a cabana Israel has had in
Taba since 1967.
