<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon-Politics     10-17 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon-Politics,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Iraq Strike Held, Christians To Boycott Parliament</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FAROUK NASSAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syria's allies in Lebanon staged a
daylong general strike throughout the country's Moslem regions on
Monday to protest Iraq's recognition of a Christian military
Cabinet as the constitutional government.
   It came as Christian deputies decided to boycott a session of
Parliament set for Tuesday to elect a new speaker. Leaving
Parliament without a speaker would undermine one of the last
vestiges of a united Lebanon.
   The strike shut schools, stores, banks, cafes, restaurants and
other businesses in west Beirut. Police said similar shutdowns
paralyzed Lebanon's northern, eastern and southern provinces.
   Street posters in west Beirut, Tripoli, Sidon, Tyre and Baalbek
read, ``Iraq's meddling threatens to break Lebanon'' and ``Hands
off Lebanon.''
   The strike reflected Syrian alarm over Iraq's military and
political support of Christian forces seeking the withdrawal of
40,000 Syrian troops stationed in Lebanon.
   Iraq and Syria, governed by rival wings of the Arab Socialist
Baath party, have been at odds since the mid-1960s.
   Christian areas north and northeast of Beirut and a border
enclave run by Israel and its predominantly Christian militia
allies in south Lebanon did not participate in the strike.
   Iraq reportedly shipped multibarreled rocket launchers, tanks
and armored personnel carriers to the Lebanese Forces, the
Christians' main militia in Lebanon's 13-year-old civil war.
   The arms were seen as intended to stir trouble for Syria, Iran's
main Arab ally in the 8-year-old Iran-Iraq war that was halted by a
cease-fire Aug. 20. Syria considers Lebanon within its sphere of
influence.
   Iraq last week became the only Arab country to recognize the
military Cabinet of Christian army commander Gen. Michel Aoun,
appointed by President Amin Gemayel minutes before Gemayel's term
ended Sept. 22.
   In Damascus, an editorial in the English-language Syria Times
accused Iraq of collaborating with Israel to undermine Lebanon's
unity.
   Other Arab states have have remained neutral in the struggle
between Aoun's three-man Cabinet and the Syrian-backed, five-man
government of acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, a Sunni Moslem.
   The power struggle is solidifying a de facto partition of
Lebanon into sectarian cantons because of Parliament's failure to
elect a successor to Gemayel. Right-wing Christian members of
Parliament have sabotaged the required quorum by boycotting
sessions to elect a new president.
   The Christian deputies said they will boycott Tuesday's session,
called to extend Shiite Moslem speaker Hussein Husseini's mandate,
or elect a successor.
   That could lead to disintegration of the Parliament.
   The Christians also are demanding a different meeting site for
Parliament, citing security.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
