<HEAD>New Civil Rights Group Issues Manifesto</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new Czechoslovak independent political
group, Movement for Civil Freedom, issued a manifesto Monday
calling for political pluralism, a new democratic constitution and
freedom of intellectual life.
   A copy of the manifesto, made available to news media in Vienna,
said, ``The totalitarian form of government is the real cause of
the present crisis in Czechoslovakia.''
   The Czechoslovak government underwent a major reshuffle this
month.
   The document, signed by 122 Czechoslovak citizens, said the
Movement for Civil Freedom was set up in Prague on Oct.15.
   Among those listed as signing the manifesto were prominent
members of the Charter 77 rights group and other intellectuals in
official disgrace, including sociologist Rudolf Battek; journalist
Jiri Dienstbier; playwright Vaclav Havel; philosopher Ladislav
Hejdanek; Karel Srp, chairman of the Jazz Section, and writer
Ludvik Vaculik.
   Other demands in the manifesto included freedom of religion;
independent trade unions, and a demilitarized society.
