<HEAD>Japan, U.S. Agree to Trips Without Visas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan and the United States have agreed to allow
90-day visits to each country without requiring visas, Foreign
Minister Sosuke Uno announced Tuesday.
   Uno said in a ministry press release that the new accord will go
into effect on Dec. 15. It exempts from visa requirements visits of
less than 90 days for non-occupational purposes.
   The United States is the 51st country to conclude such a pact
with Japan.
   In 1987, all but 100,000 of more than 2.3 million Japanese who
visited the United States stayed for less than 90 days and 410,000
of the 440,000 U.S. visitors to Japan were short-term travelers,
according to Japanese immigration officials.
