<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-Peacekeepers     10-17 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Peacekeepers,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Call For U.N. Navy, Expanded Role For Peacekeepers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the Soviet U.N. delegation
amplified on Monday his nation's call for establishment of a U.N.
navy and an expanded role for peacekeepers.
   Deputy Foreign Minister Vladimir Petrovsky's statement to a U.N.
committee echoed Soviet proposals already put before the General
Assembly, but emphasized Soviet willingness to keep its innovations
within the current U.N. Charter.
   ``We regard as generally sound the existing order under which
U.N. peacekeeping operations are carried out,'' said Petrovsky.
   However, he reiterated a Soviet proposal for ``possible
stationing of U.N. observers along frontiers within the territory
of a country that seeks to protect itself from outside interference
at the request of that country alone.''
   Under present U.N. practice, peacekeepers are not deployed
unless all countries in the area consent.
   Petrovsky's proposal would be of interest to Afghanistan, a
Soviet ally, which has lodged numerous complaints that Islamic
rebels are using Pakistan as a base for staging cross-border raids
into Afghan territory.
   More than 100,000 Soviet troops are withdrawing from Afghanistan
under the U.N.-mediated Geneva Accords.
   Last month, however, Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze
said the next phase of the pullout depends on whether the Soviets
and Afghans receive a satisfactory response to their complaints of
Pakistan's alleged violations of the accords.
   Petrovsky also called for the use of U.N. peacekeepers in
troubled areas before conflict breaks out, and posting observers
along tense borders.
   The Soviet Union stands ready to set aside units of its military
forces for use in U.N. peacekeeping, he said, suggesting that many
nations also set aside troops who would serve as a reserve guard
for U.N. peacekeeping.
   Petrovsky offered the use of Soviet transports and logistical
support for the U.N. plan for independence for South-West Africa,
also known as Namibia, which is ruled by neighboring South Africa.
   Noting his previous calls for a U.N. naval task force for the
Persian Gulf, Petrovsky expanded the concept by suggesting the
formation of a U.N. navy, including minesweepers and escorts to
protect commercial ships in dangerous international waters.
   The United States, Britain, France and other Western democracies
have blocked similar packages of Soviet peacekeeping and
international security proposals in the last two General Assembly
sessions.
   Diplomats for the Western allies say many of the Soviet
proposals have merit, but when combined into a ``comprehensive''
security proposal, they amount to a restructuring of the U.N.
Charter, which the West opposes.
   Petrovsky's references to innovations ``in accordance with the
U.N. charter'' appeared to be intended to allay such fears.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881017-0205 </DOCNO>
