<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Extradition 1stLd-Writethru   10-17 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Extradition, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0827,0463</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Says Ng Plotted Sex Slayings with Accomplice</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to CORRECT name of prosecutor. Pick up 3rd
pvs, ``Ng, 27.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prosecutor said Monday that Charles
Ng, wanted in California for allegedly carrying out a string of
murders, joined forces with a mass murderer in the early 1980s to
kidnap targets for sex slayings.
   As Ng's extradition hearing got under way amid tight security,
Federal Crown prosecutor Bruce McFarlane told a packed courtroom he
will argue that Ng and his companion Leonard Lake ``were acting in
concert to achieve the same overall objectives.''
   Ng, 27, has been serving a 4{-year sentence in Canada since his
conviction in December 1985 of armed robbery during a botched
shoplifting attempt in Calgary. He came to Canada after Lake
committed suicide.
   Lake later was linked to the deaths or disappearances of 22
people. That investigation led to the charges against Ng.
   McFarlane told the court that Ng _ whose name is pronounced Ing
_ and Lake became acquainted in the early 1980s.
   He said the two men moved to Calaveras County, about 120 miles
east of San Francisco, and built a series of underground rooms
referred to as ``the bunker.''
   There, McFarlane told the court, Ng and Lake began to formalize
a plan to kidnap people in the California area and take them to the
bunker for what he called their own sexual gratification.
   The extradition hearing, scheduled to last 5{ weeks, is to
determine whether there is sufficient evidence to send Ng back to
California, where he faces 25 charges, including at least 10 of
murder.
   Canada has a policy of not extraditing criminals who could face
the death penalty, and is entitled to ask for leniency under the
1986 Canada-U.S. extradition treaty. The final decision regarding
extradition rests with Justice Minister Ray Hnatyshyn.
   During Monday's court appearance, Ng, a former marine, sat in
the prisoner's box, wearing a navy T-shirt, and showed no emotion.
   He was shackled at the wrists and flanked by armed officers.
Spectators entering the courtroom were searched with metal
detectors.
   Sharon Sellitto, 40, of San Francisco, whose 39-year-old
brother, Paul Cosner, is one of a dozen people Ng is accused of
murdering, said outside the courtroom Monday she wanted to see Ng
face to face.
   ``As far as I'm concerned, I don't want to hate a 2-by-2 picture
that appears in all the newspapers,'' she said. ``I wanted to see
him in person and make it real.''
   Ng's lawyer, Don MacLeod, said that even if enough evidence is
found to extradite Ng, he will press Canadian authorities to demand
a U.S. guarantee his client won't be executed.
</TEXT>
