<1ST_LINE>a i PM-Japan-Archaeology Adv19   10-17 0582</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Archaeology, Adv 19,0598</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wednesday, Oct. 19, or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>6th-Century Coffin Yields Evidence of Korean Cultural Influence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By K.P. HONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese archaeologists say a 6th-century stone
coffin opened in a previously untouched tomb contains dozens of
treasures showing a strong likelihood of Korean cultural influence
in Japan.
   A government research team lifted the two-ton lid off the
vermillion-colored coffin Oct. 8 at the Fujinoki Tumulus, or mound,
in Nara prefecture, the heartland of ancient Japan.
   Japanese newspapers and television have given the discovery
extensive coverage while the archaeologists carefully drain water
from the coffin to retrieve the encrusted articles.
   They say the treasures include at least three swords, a pair of
gilt-bronze shoes, a golden necklace, earrings, ornaments and other
accessories. The coffin also contains human bones and remnants of
cloth.
   Officials at Kashihara Archaeological Research Institute of Nara
prefecture, in western Japan, say recovery of the relics and
remains will take several weeks. The identity of the person buried
in the tomb is not known.
   Professor Kyoichi Arimitsu of Kyoto University, who directed the
Kashihara Institute in 1980-1984, said the relics were believed to
be from one of Korea's three ancient kingdoms _ Silla, Paekche or
Koguryo.
   ``They are similar to those found in tumuluses in the Korean
Peninsula,'' he said in a telephone interview after inspecting the
excavation.
   Kazu Uehara, a professor of art history at Seijo University in
Tokyo, agrees with Arimitsu.
   ``When a set of harness was found at the Fujinoki Tumulus three
years ago, some people disagreed with my view that it might have
come from Korea,'' he said. ``They said the harness looked more
like Chinese.
   ``The remains in the stone coffin, I believe, will correct their
theory. I know, of course, there are similarities between ancient
Chinese culture and that of Korea. However, they are not the same.
For instance, hexagonal ornaments extracted from the stone coffin
have been found only in Korean tumuluses.
   ``There are some Japanese scholars who would hesitate to accept
the fact that Japan received more cultural heritage from Korea than
China. ... The tendency, I believe, stems from an attitude of
looking down on a small country like Korea.''
   The tomb and mound date from the Yamato period, which ran from
early in the Christian era through 710.
   Yamato is the ancient name for mountainous Nara prefecture,
where the first unified state in Japan was based. Members of its
ruling class were buried in mounds.
   Japan and Korea made their first peaceful contacts during the
Yamato period and Japan began its long history of adopting and
adapting the cultures of others.
   Writing in Chinese characters was imported from Paekche in Korea
in 285. In the next 300 years, through contacts with Korea, the
Japanese learned of the formidable and advanced culture of the
Asian mainland.
   Arimitsu said the Fujinoki mound was believed to have been
created between 551 and 575. It is about 600 yards from the
Buddhist temple Horyuji, built between 601 and 607 in the town of
Ikaruga, 8 miles southwest of Nara.
   Excavation of the mound, which is 30 feet high, began in 1985.
About 3,500 relics have been found, including exquisite gold and
bronze objects, in addition to the stone coffin.
   Archaeologists viewed the coffin's interior in June, using a
flexible instrument with a lens on the end, and set up a
chain-and-pulley mechanism to raise the heavy, peaked cover.
   End Adv for Wed Oct. 19
</TEXT>
