<1ST_LINE>a a BC-History Adv25   10-17 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-History, Adv 25,0503</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tuesday, Oct. 25</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Today is Tuesday, Oct. 25, the 299th day of 1988. There are 67
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   In 1962, U.S. ambassador Adlai E. Stevenson demanded before the
U.N. Security Council that Soviet delegate Valerian A. Zorin
confirm or deny the existence of missile bases in Cuba, saying he
was prepared to wait for an answer ``until hell freezes over.''
Stevenson then presented reconnaisance photographs of the bases to
the council.
   On this date:
   In 1400, Geoffrey Chaucer, author of ``The Canterbury Tales,''
died in London.
   In 1760, George III ascended the British throne upon the death
of grandfather, King George II.
   In 1812, the U.S. frigate United States captured the British
vessel Macedonian during the War of 1812.
   In 1854, the Charge of the Light Brigade took place during the
Crimean War as an English brigade of 600 men charged the Russian
army against hopeless odds and suffered heavy losses.
   In 1918, the Canadian steamship Princess Sophia foundered after
hitting a reef off the coast of Alaska, resulting in the deaths of
all of the nearly 400 people aboard.
   In 1929, former Interior Secretary Albert B. Fall was convicted
of accepting a $100,000 bribe in connection with the Elk Hills
Naval Oil Reserve in California.
   In 1951, peace talks aimed at ending the Korean War resumed in
Panmunjom after 63 days.
   In 1962, American author John Steinbeck was award the Nobel
Prize in literature.
   In 1971, the U.N. General Assembly voted to admit mainland China
and expel Taiwan.
   In 1986, parachutist Michael Sergio dropped into New York's Shea
Stadium during game six of the World Series between the Mets and
the Boston Red Sox, carrying a sign reading, ``Let's Go Mets.'' The
Mets won, 6-5, and went on to win the series in the seventh game.
   Ten years ago: The Israeli Cabinet approved, ``in principle,'' a
draft compromise peace treaty with Egypt. But complications arose
when Israel said it intended to expand existing Jewish settlements
in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Five years ago: U.S. Marines and Rangers, assisted by soldiers
from six Caribbean nations, invaded Grenada at the order of
President Reagan, who said the action was intended to protect U.S.
citizens and help restore democracy on the island.
   One year ago: The Minnesota Twins won their first World Series
championship, beating the St. Louis Cardinals 4-2 in the seventh
game.
   Today's birthdays: Actor Whit Bissell is 79. Country music star
Minnie Pearl is 76. Former baseball player Bobby Thomson is 65.
Actress Marion Ross is 60. Actor Tony Franciosa is 60. Singer Helen
Reddy is 46. Actor Brian Kerwin is 39.
   Thought for Today: ``Anyone can do any amount of work, provided
it isn't the work he is supposed to be doing at the moment.'' _
Robert Benchley, American humorist (1889-1945).
</TEXT>
</DOC>
