<1ST_LINE>a i AM-ChinaConsultant Adv20   10-17 0849</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China Consultant, Adv 20,0873</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thu AMs, Oct. 20, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>American Victim Of China's Past Helps It with Future</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sidney Rittenberg came to China as a young
idealist and his reward was 16 years in prison. Now he helps other
foreigners find keys to the doors of commerce in his adopted land.
   Rittenberg, 67, is president of Kamsky and Rittenberg, a
consulting firm that helps foreign clients, most of their American,
get information and access to Chinese officials.
   Since establishing the firm a year ago, Rittenberg has found
markets and Chinese partners for U.S. makers of gas turbines,
pencils, jeans and electrical appliances, and guided them through
the enigmatic world of Chinese contract negotiations.
   He has organized tours for such as evangelist Billy Graham and
Gov. Ray Mabus of Mississippi, sometimes acting as interpreter in
impeccable Mandarin at meetings with senior Chinese leaders.
   ``I like the feeling that we're building little bridges,'' he
said in an interview.
   Rittenberg began building his bridges decades ago, with some
disastrous consequences. He is a native of Charleston, S.C., and
first came to China in 1945, as a U.S. Army interpreter after
studying Chinese at Stanford.
   Like other young American liberals caught up in the turbulence,
Rittenberg was attracted by the zeal and idealism of Mao Tse-tung's
revolutionaries.
   ``I was taken with the idea they were going to build a new kind
of just, democratic socialist society,'' he said. After leaving the
Army he decided to stay in China, at the urging of Chou En-lai and
other leaders, to help establish an English-language radio service.
   When Chinese authorities put him in the back of a truck going to
Beijing in 1949, he thought he was being enlisted to help negotiate
relations between the United States and Mao's new Communist
government. ``I was euphoric,'' he said.
   Instead, Rittenberg was imprisoned on charges of being an
American spy.
   He learned later that Soviet dictator Josef Stalin demanded his
arrest, claiming Rittenberg was an accomplice of American
journalist Anna Louise Strong, who had been arrested in Moscow for
spying. She and Rittenberg were collaborating on a biography of Mao.
   Six years in prison followed, the first of them in an unlighted
room with black cloth over the windows.
   When he was released and cleared of wrongdoing in 1955, ``Mao
apologized to me,'' he said. ``They really felt bad about it and
took me into the family.''
   Back at Radio Beijing, he was made privy to material seldom
revealed to outsiders. ``That was power, access to inside
information,'' he said in the interview.
   His world collapsed once more during the Cultural Revolution of
1966-76.
   Again he was deceived. He said he thought the Cultural
Revolution, with which Mao dislodged the entrenched bureaucracy,
``was a great day, a kind of town hall democracy.''
   But the radical leftists who gained power revived the old spying
charges and jailed him in 1968. He spent 10 years in solitary and
his Chinese wife, Yulin, was sentenced to three years in a labor
camp.
   ``There was only one real issue, keeping your sanity from day to
day,'' he said of the lost decade. ``I tried not to be bitter. In
solitary, bitterness is the enemy. But who are you going to be sore
at? It was the whole system.''
   He said he felt freedom was near when he heard Mao's widow,
Jiang Qing, yelling from a nearby cell. Jiang, who Rittenberg says
personally prolonged his prison term, was arrested in late 1976 as
ringleader of the notorious ``Gang of Four.''
   Again released and again exonerated, he was given a sinecure
with the Academy of Social Sciences, helping arrange academic
exchanges. In 1979 he returned to the United States for the first
time in 34 years.
   Rittenberg now spends about half the year in the United States.
His consulting firm has an office in New York and he has a home in
Seattle, where one of his four children also lives.
   His hope that Chinese communism would be ``different from the
Russians, more civilized and democratic,'' dissolved long ago.
   ``Mao went back on his promises,'' he said, and if the
democratic socialism he once envisioned for China ever comes, ``it
will be nothing resembling Marxist-Leninist societies so far.''
   After so many years away, Rittenberg said, he finds the United
States to be a more humane country.
   ``The leaders of the Chinese revolution didn't understand that
if not everyone is protected by law then no one is,'' he said.
``Our forefathers were smart enough to build that into the system.''
   Rittenberg worries about corruption in China, where young people
``have no 10 Commandments and no Communist ideology'' and party
officials are among the greediest. He said there are ``thieves
galore built into the system,'' but believes a ``kind of
self-correcting mechanism'' will see China through.
   China and the United States ``have a special chemistry and
there's no reason it shouldn't cement and grow,'' Rittenberg said.
``I feel kind of good it is happening now.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thu AMs, Oct.20</NOTE>
