<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-88 2348EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a p AM-Election-Women-List 1stLd-Writethru-ADV2</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Election-Women-List, 1st Ld-Writethru-ADV 20, b0449,0723</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thu AMs, Oct. 20, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Women Candidates: The Key Races</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Election-Women</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Subs 15th graf, bgng: MICHIGAN to CORRECT spelling of Pursell</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a list of key congressional races in
which women candidates are raising strong challenges. Also listed
are races in which women incumbents are facing stiff challenges.
   
   WISCONSIN: Susan Engeleiter, 36, a Republican state senator with
a law degree from the University of Wisconsin, is trailing Democrat
Herb Kohl in the race to succeed retiring Sen. William Proxmire, a
Democrat known for his shoe-string campaigns. Internal polls by
both campaigns show Engeleiter about 10 points behind, but she is
seeking to capitalize on her experience in state economic matters.
Kohl, 52, a wealthy businessman and owner of the Milwaukee Bucks,
is a political novice. Using his own money, Kohl is expected to
spend up to $7 million compared with Engeleiter's $3 million.
   
   CALIFORNIA: Anna Eschoo, a Democratic San Mateo County
supervisor, is making a strong showing in her bid to fill the House
seat of Rep. Ernest Konnyu, a one-term Republican who was the only
representative to lose in a primary. Tom Campbell, a political
newcomer who teaches law at Stanford University, defeated Konnyu in
the primary. Polls show a close race.
   
   COLORADO: Martha Ezzard, a former Republican state senator who
switched parties last year, is challenging incumbent Dan Schaefer
in a district that includes the Denver suburbs. The environment is
an issue.
   
   IDAHO: Jeanne Givens, a Democratic state legislator, would be
the first native American women in Congress if she unseats
incumbent Larry Craig, a four-term incumbent. Givens has traveled
the length of the state's first district in a bus to solicit votes.
   
   LOUISIANA: Faye Williams, a Democratic lawyer, is in a rematch
with Rep. Clyde Holloway, a one-term Republican. Williams would
become the first black woman elected in Louisiana if she unseats
Holloway in the 8th district race. Black registration in the
district is about 36 percent. Williams, who has strong support from
Democratic stalwarts, was hurt in her 1986 race by revelations that
her estranged husband had beat Williams and shot to death the man
she had been dating in 1971.
   
   MARYLAND: First-term Republican Constance Morella is facing a
challenge from Peter Franchot, a member of the Maryland
legislature, in Montgomery County, a wealthy suburb of Washington.
Morella is a moderate Republican who narrowly won a formerly
Democratic seat in 1986.
   
   MICHIGAN: Lana Pollack, a state senator, is trying to oust Rep.
Carl Pursell, a six-term Republican incumbent in the 2nd district.
The disparate district includes Ann Arbor, the home of the
University of Michigan, as well as the Detroit suburbs.
   
   NEW YORK: Nita Lowey, former New York assistant secretary of
state, faces incumbent Rep. Joseph DioGuardi, a Republican, in
heavily populated suburban Westchester County outside New York
City. DioGuardi, an accountant, was first elected by the 20th
District in 1986.
   
   NEW YORK: Rosemary Pooler, a former public service commissioner,
is running a strong race in the 27th district to succeed Rep.
George C. Wortley, a Republican who is retiring. Facing Pooler is
James Walsh, a council member from Syracuse. The district is
halfway between Albany and Buffalo.
   
   NEW YORK: Rep. Louise Slaughter, a Democrat from the 30th
district, was the only woman to defeat an incumbent in 1986. She is
facing John C. Bouchard of Rochester in the race to keep her seat
in what has traditionally been a Republican district.
   
   SOUTH CAROLINA: Rep. Liz Patterson, a first-term incumbent
Democrat, has a tough fight to keep her seat in the 4th District
where Republicans are strong. Her opponent is Knox White, a city
councilman from Greenville who has patterned his positions after
those of Vice President George Bush.
   
   WASHINGTON: Jolene Unsoeld, a Democratic state legislator, is
favored to win the seat vacated by Rep. Don Bonker, a Democrat.
Unsoeld faces Bill Wight, a former aide to Republican Sen. John
Warner of Virginia. Unsoeld, an avid environmentalist and a
mountain climber, lost her husband and her daughter in separate
mountain climbing accidents.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thu AMs, Oct. 20</NOTE>
