<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--FilmReviews ADV00   10-17 1007</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Film Reviews, ADV 00,1044</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At the Movies: ``Clara's Heart,'' ``Imagine: John Lennon''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Clara's Heart''
   
   Clara Mayfield is a brutally direct woman who colors her human
relationships with a good deal of common sense, self-righteousness
and tenacity. She also has an overwhelming humanity about her, and
that specialness attracts people to her like a magnet.
   The relationship she forges with young David Hart is bound to be
a memorable screen joining.
   Clara is a vibrant and rich role, one that could easily turn
around Whoopi Goldberg's dismal film career. After such losers as
``Burglar,''``Jumpin' Jack Flash'' and ``Fatal Beauty,'' in which
the stand-up comic was required to do little more than imitate
Eddie Murphy and be the Butterfly McQueen of the 1980s, Goldberg
finally has a chance to demonstrate her talents as a dramatic
actress.
   Robert Mulligan (``To Kill a Mockingbird,''``Inside Daisy
Clover'') restrains Goldberg in his direction of this family
melodrama, allowing none of the bits and business that have become
the trademarks of her wealth of comic stage characters. That
restraint is essential to Clara herself, a Jamaican with a dark
secret.
   Clara enters the lives of the affluent Hart family from
Maryland's Eastern Shore, shortly after the crib death of their
daughter. Leona (Kathleen Quinlan) and Bill (MichaelOntkean) have
gone to Jamaica to help get over the tragedy. Clara is their hotel
maid.
   She coaxes Leona out of her depression and encourages her to get
on with life. Leona decides to bring her back to Maryland _ she
can't quite function without Clara's island sensibilities. But son
David Hart takes an immediate dislike to Clara and accuses his
parents _ rightfully so _ of bringing her home so they won't have
to deal with him.
   The Harts are in the process of a divorce. He has taken up with
a hot cutie, and she has taken up with a pretentious bore of a pop
shrink (Spalding Gray).
   Clara eventually wins over David to the point where he'd rather
spend his weekends in Baltimore with Clara and her West Indian
friends than with his parents. He also picks up Clara's island
patois, to the delight of her friends.
   But David's dependency on Clara ultimately leads to her dark
revelation. And it is here that the movie falters. There is no
build-up to this awful experience in her life, and its unfolding is
an abrupt twist. And with the tale, there remain loose ends:
Letters hidden in a suitcase and found by David are never
explained; the father of Clara's child also is a mystery.
   Still, ``Clara's Heart'' is a warm movie with many lessons to
tell, if one is willing to listen. Its force is aided by Goldberg's
performance and a noteworthy movie debut of Neil Patrick Harris as
David.
   The Warner Bros. release of an MTM Entertainment Production
features a lilting score by Dave Grusin. But Hollywood has yet to
learn through its endless quest for authenticity that steel music
and calypso are products of Trinidad, not Jamaica, where reggae and
soca bloom.
   Martin Elfand produced ``Clara's Heart,'' which is rated PG-13.
   _ By Dolores Barclay, AP Arts Editor.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Imagine: John Lennon''
   
   Rarely has a 20th-century phenomenon been so thoroughly
chronicled in every conceivable way as the Beatles.
   Yet the new documentary ``Imagine: John Lennon'' provides
previously unseen material on the most enigmatic of the Beatles, if
not any fresh insights.
   Yoko Ono, Lennon's ever-protective widow, released 200 hours of
tapes and films from their private collection to documentary and
miniseries producer David L. Wolper (``The Making of the President:
1960,''``Roots''). Wolper and producer-director Andrew Solt culled
through the material and also searched for newsreels and TV
appearances.
   The documentary material was combined with new interviews with
Yoko Ono and Lennon's first wife, Cynthia, sons Julian and Sean,
and various associates of Lennon. None of the three surviving
Beatles was interviewed.
   ``Imagine'' provides a gold mine for Beatle lovers and
especially those who revere Lennon, who was slain outside his
apartment in Manhattan by a crazed fan in 1980.
   But the film provides marginal entertainment for the average
moviegoer. Documentaries are never easy to endure in a theater.
``Imagine'' is no exception, despite the great skill that went into
its making.
   There are some riveting moments. The most scarifying comes when
John and Yoko encounter cartoonist Al Capp (``L'il Abner'') during
the Montreal Bed-in for Peace, a meeting as deadly in its way as a
mongoose's minuet with two cobras.
   The Lennons' penchant for shock is demonstrated in a nude
love-making scene which was filmed two weeks before he died,
intended for a music video. It is antiseptically graphic, hardly
erotic at all.
   Director Solt has capably maintained the kind of pace
established in the trend-setting Beatles feature ``A Hard Day's
Night.'' Only in the final sequence does the film falter. Lennon's
murder and the outpouring of grief from his candle-holding fans is
protracted into a kind of deification that hardly suits the subject.
   There is commentary by family and friends, and Lennon's own
voice narrates much of ``Imagine.'' Whether he was excessively
narcissistic or merely had a exceptional sense of history,
posterity should be grateful for his extensive record-keeping. How
valuable it would be to have such records of James Dean, Marilyn
Monroe, Elvis Presley and other icons.
   The Warner Bros. release was co-produced by Sam Egan and written
by Egan and Solt. Rated R for nudity and language. Running time:
103 minutes.
   _ By Bob Thomas, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
