<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews ADV00   10-17 0983</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, ADV 00,1022</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Talk Is Cheap'' (Island) _ Keith Richards
   
   If Mick Jagger's solo records are Jagger without the Rolling
Stones, conversely, and somewhat symmetrically, Keith Richards'
first solo effort is the Stones without Jagger.
   Richards isn't much of a singer, but he manages a listenable
rasp on a series of tunes that wouldn't exactly tax Caruso. This is
a tough rock musicians' record, anyway, starting with Richards'
patented take-no-prisoners guitar backed by a stellar cast of
studio musicians, including Bernie Worrell on organ, Waddy Wachtel
and Mick Taylor (former Stone) on guitars, Bobby Keys and Macco
Parker on various saxes, plus the Memphis Horns.
   Charley Drayton is on bass most of the time, Steve Jordan drums
and Ivan Neville keyboards. Sarah Dash sings background. Patti
Scialfa (E Street Band and the Boss' main squeeze) is on one cut.
   All the songs were co-written by Richards and Jordan.
   ``Take It Hard'' and ``Struggle'' are especially worth blasting
loud enough to enrage the neighbors.
   Richards makes a mistake on ``Make No Mistake'' with his
impersonation of Peggy Lee on steroids. Dash comes in to save it,
though, giving Richards a Tom Waits-like charm by comparison. They
team again on the wonderfully soulful ``Rockawhile.''
   ``Locked Away'' is a real pretty tune. Richards should hire
someone else to sing it. By the last cut, ``It Means a Lot,'' it
seems Richards-Jordan had run out of ideas.
   But the closer of Side 1, ``You Don't Move Me,'' is another
four-star effort that could apply to anyone you know who needs a
verbal thrashing but here, it was obviously meant for Jagger: ``You
lost the feeling, got so appealing. Why do you think you think you
got no friends? You drove 'em all 'round the bend. Ah, yeah, you
don't move me anymore. ... It's no longer funny, it's bigger than
money, you just don't move me anymore.''
   As the record says, ``Talk Is Cheap,'' so you better be able to
move 'em yourself. And most of the time Richards does, with room to
spare.
   _ By Kathryn Baker, AP Television Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Tighten Up Vol. 88'' (Columbia) _ Big Audio Dynamite
   
   Mick Jones, once the fiery guitarist of punk heroes The Clash,
now seems a little like a roguish older brother.
   He lectures a lot, mostly about respecting the rights of others.
His music, once loud and brash, is more melodic and _ dare we say _
nearly laid back. The cover of his group's new album shows him
dressed in a tuxedo, although with a lipstick stain on his face and
clutching a wine bottle.
   Big Audio Dynamite's first album a few years back was an
exciting synthesis of rock and urban rhythms, mixed in with the
``found sounds'' of old movie clips. The second album was a less
exciting take on the same idea.
   Jones and his usual writing partner, Don Letts, are neither
melodically adventurous nor particularly good singers, so many
B.A.D. songs tend to sound the same. The group needed to stretch
out a bit, and for the most part do it successfully on ``Tighten Up
Vol. 88''
   Jones' old group wanted to save the world, now the ambitions are
scaled back. ``No one gets 10 out of 10,'' he sings on ``Other
99,'' ``You gotta strive for five.''
   In ``Funny Names,'' he sings, ``You're not like me. I'm not like
you. Don't mean we can't get along.''
   Their utopian outlook would sound naive if it wasn't so
good-natured. B.A.D. doesn't take itself too seriously, unlike the
Clash. One of the best songs here, ``Just Play Music,'' rejects
rock star trappings and suggests good music is really quite simple.
   That's not just a lyrical approach. B.A.D. uses some familiar
Chuck Berry riffs, borrows from the old standard ``Battle of New
Orleans'' and generally goes for straightforward rock on this
album. But many of the songs are sweetened by synthesizers and few
have a particularly hard edge.
   Big Audio Dynamite can consider this a rebound from the
sophomore slump.
   _ By David Bauder, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Hot Water'' (MCA) _ Jimmy Buffett
   
   There was a time when Jimmy Buffett sang cleverly, and sometimes
even movingly, about everything from life, love and loneliness to
cheeseburgers, gas station robberies and the sea.
   That was more than a decade ago now, before Buffett began a
long, sad slide that finds him, again, in ``Hot Water,''
desperately trying to breathe life into the cliche that he has
become, America's Official Tropical Hedonist.
   The new LP is cruise-line predictable. He softly sings the
praises of the Louisiana air (or, as he affectedly sings en
francais, ``L'Air de la Louisiane'') _ only a dozen years after he
sang the same song about ``Biloxi,'' one state away. Here comes the
``Prince of Tides.'' There goes the ``King of Somewhere Hot.''
   This isn't rock 'n' roll; this is the Weather Channel.
   Musically, things are little better. There's an all-star guest
list _ Steve Winwood, the Neville Brothers, even Grover Washington
Jr. _ but what you hear here, mon, is the misplaced sound of steel
drums.
   And if the pseudo-Caribbean schtick weren't wearing thin by now,
``Hot Water'' finds Buffett pretentious _ three of these songs
begin with spoken soliloquies _ and mean-spirited. When he's not
complaining that his songs aren't on the radio, he's bordering on
misogyny: complaining that ``baby's gone shopping'' when she ought
to stay home, forsaking ``bimbo limbo'' to search for a ``smart
woman in a real short skirt.''
   Buffett's magic with his audience has been that they wished they
could live their lives like his songs. Songs like these make it
hard to remember why anyone ever felt that way.
   _ By Robert Byrd, Associated Press Writer
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
