<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Star Watch: The Frank, Intense and Combative Kirk</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kirk Douglas' autobiography, ``The Ragman's
Son,'' has spent weeks on non-fiction best-seller lists, a position
generally accorded such female stars as Lauren Bacall, Shelley
Winters and Ingrid Bergman.
   How did Douglas make the magic list when other actors have
failed? The secret may be that his book is just as frank, intense
and combative as the public's image of Kirk Douglas over the past
four decades.
   Douglas has never walked away from a fight. Many a producer,
director and co-star can recall scars acquired in encounters with
Kirk. He turned his back on a seven-year contract from Hal Wallis
at a time when most actors would grab it. He defied the industry
powers by hiring the blacklisted Dalton Trumbo to write
``Spartacus.''
   As revealed in ``The Ragman's Son,'' he romanced a wide range of
Hollywood's glamour queens, including Joan Crawford, Gene Tierney,
Marlene Dietrich, Ann Sothern and Rita Hayworth.
   Douglas seems to be a man who got everything he wanted. But he
had two great frustrations. He was madly in love with Pier Angeli,
but despite their engagement, he could never escape her
ever-present parents. He starred in ``One Flew Over the Cuckoo's
Nest'' on Broadway but could never make a movie deal. He became too
old for the role, and son Michael co-produced the film, which won
an Academy Award for Jack Nicholson.
   Douglas, a vigorous 69, recently reminisced about his life and
times at the Beverly Hills offices of Bryna Productions, named for
his mother. He told of the inception of his autobiography.
   ``I was driving to Palm Springs one day, and I saw a sailor
hitchhiking. I had been in the Navy, so I picked him up. When he
got in the car, he looked at me and said, `Do you know who you are?'
   ``Well, I thought about that, and it's an interesting
question,'' he said.
   The actor's search for Kirk Douglas led him to Issur
Danielovitch, the son of illiterate, Russian-Jewish immigrants in
Amsterdam, N.Y. The father was a cold, distant, brawling alcoholic
whose love neither Issur nor Kirk could achieve.
   ``It's a terrible thing for a young kid who has a father who's
so physically strong,'' said Douglas. ``You think, `My God, I can
never be that strong, I can never be that big.' My father was a rag
man, yet to me he was somebody. So living with my six sisters and
my mother, I had no identity.
   ``When my father left, I thought, `Why am I not with my father?
I'm a boy! Why am I with the women?'''
   Young Issur escaped the ``suffocating'' female atmosphere to
attend St. Lawrence College, and he never went home again, except
for brief visits. He discovered acting in college, went on to New
York where his looks _ like carved granite _ and intense style
attracted Hollywood offers. And he went on his own terms.
   ``From the very beginning, I was always independent, a
maverick,'' he remarked. ``I didn't belong to any studio. There
were good things about that, but there were bad things, too. It was
lonely. Everybody else belonged to studios, and they were going to
singing and dancing lessons.
   ``There were a lot of good things to be said for the oldtime
studio system that I did not belong to. They developed stars and
got parts for them in movies. I wasn't part of that. I was sort of
outside.''
   Douglas' film career has been marked by an affinity for forceful
heroic roles, from his part as a calculating boxer in 1949's
``Champion'' to his depiction of Vincent Van Gogh in 1956's ``Lust
for Life.'' Both films earned him Academy Award nominations.
   In ``Spartacus,'' perhaps Douglas' greatest role, he starred as
the leader of slaves rebelling against Republican Rome. At the same
time, Douglas has shown a flair for the comic, especially as a
sharp-tongued inmate in the 1970 movie ``There Was a Crooked Man.''
   His first film role came in 1946's ``The Strange Love of Martha
Ivers,'' and his last appearance was in the 1987 NBC production of
``Inherit the Wind.'' Douglas has been known for his frankness, and
he had these evaluations about some of his friends and colleagues:
   John Wayne: ``One of the most remarkable men I ever worked with.
We never got along, though we did four pictures together.
Politically we were complete opposites.''
   Burt Lancaster: ``I like Burt. He's quite different; for
example, he's a great lover of music and opera. Most people would
never expect that of Burt. If I ever need Burt, I call him; if he
needs me, he calls me. It's a wonderful relationship.''
   Barbara Stanwyck (who starred in his first film): ``She was
pretty tough with me at first. I was new, didn't know anybody, and
she sort of ignored me for two weeks. But I always forgive any
slights like that when I see talent and a professional attitude.''
   Robert Mitchum: ``Never my kind of guy. I always kidded him
about those stories he'd tell about being a hobo; they seemed to
change every time he told them. But obviously he is a talented guy,
and listen, he's had a tremendous career.''
   Michael Douglas: ``The nicest thing I can say about Michael is
what I put in a note some time ago; he told me it's the only note
of mine he has kept. I said to him, `Michael, I'm more proud of how
you handle your success than I am of your success.' And I think
we'll still be hearing a lot from him.''
   Kirk Douglas: ``Kirk Douglas ... Issur Danielovitch, the
ragman's son. I've taken 450 pages to try to explain who I am. And
I'm not sure I know yet.
   ``The best way to sum it up would be in the character of
McMurphy in `One Flew over the Cuckoo's Nest,' the role I so
desperately wanted to play on the screen. McMurphy tries to lift
this piece of machinery and fails. They're all looking and feeling
sorry for him. He turns to face them and says, `But I tried.
Dammit, I tried.'''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Oct 28-30</NOTE>
