<1ST_LINE>a a BC-EXP--Japan-Cancer Adv20   10-17 0688</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EXP--Japan-Cancer, Adv 20,0710</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Thursday, Oct. 20, and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Japanese Doctors Shy From Giving Cancer Patients Details</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARI YAMAGUCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Almost 200,000 Japanese died last year of cancer,
most without knowing they had it _ unless they figured it out
themselves.
   Their doctors hadn't told them the truth.
   Traditionally, the Japanese have been unlikely to question the
authority of the medical profession, but that appears to be
changing as a well-educated people want to know more about what
ails them.
   And doctors are thinking about revising their ethics, which have
been based on the belief that patients are depressed if told they
have cancer, and will die happier if they don't know.
   ``I guess about 90 percent of the doctors still don't tell,''
said Toshio Takahashi, professor of surgery at Kyoto Prefectural
University of Medicine.
   But to Jinro Itami, cancer specialist at Shibata Hospital in
Okayama, the real issue is not the propriety of informing patients
but how to reduce their fear of death and increase their ``fighting
spirit.''
   Itami four years ago founded a patient-support program called
Meaningful Life Therapy. Seven of his patients attempted a
morale-building climb of Mount Blanc in Switzerland last summer,
and three of them reached the summit.
   ``The earlier patients know about their condition, the better
off they are,'' he said, adding that witholding information can
create fear and sorrow and delay recovery.
   The debate, of course, is not limited to Japan. Soviet doctors
generally avoid telling a patient directly, according to Dr.
Nikolai Napalkov, president of the U.S.S.R. Oncological Society. In
the United States, doctors tend toward disclosure, said Dr. Steven
Rosenberg of the National Cancer Institute.
   Itami said it is almost impossible to keep patients ignorant as
they hear about the disease and its treatments everywhere.
   But even he says that unless patients are ready for the worst,
telling them will only cause depression. Instead, he guides them to
want to know about their illness and its treatment. ``It is very
important for patients to know about their own lives and their
condition,'' he said.
   The public seems to agree. About 60 percent want doctors to tell
them even if there is no hope of recovery, according to a poll of
5,608 adults a year ago by the Mainichi Shimbun, a Japanese
national daily. If the disease is likely to be cured, 78 percent
want to know.
   A separate poll of 500 doctors showed 76 percent would not tell
the patient if the condition is hopeless.
   ``It should be us patients, not doctors, that decide how to live
the days left in front of us,'' said Haruyo Inouye, a 37-year-old
free-lance writer who had a breast cancer operation in April.
``Doctors should tell us so that we don't have to waste time being
scared because of ignorance.''
   She complained that her doctor had not told her the side effect
of a hormonal medicine she took after surgery. She was shocked when
her menstruation became irregular, thinking something else was
wrong with her.
   Toshiro Murase, pediatrician and executive member of the Japan
Medical Association's board of trustees, said it's important to
respect the patient's right to know but satisfying the right to
know is a different story.
   ``Some patients might be able to end their lives happier without
knowing everything,'' he said, adding that Japanese doctors' most
important task is to help reduce their patients' physical pain.
   There never has been a court ruling in Japan over the issue of a
patient's right to know, said lawyer Katsuji Hotta, who recently
was named to a committee to examine the issue for Japan's Medical
Association.
   The association has decided to investigate medical, moral and
legal aspects of medical treatment, and appointed 10 people from
various professions to talk about ``explanation and consent.'' The
group includes novelist Ayako Sono; the president of the Japan
Federation of Employers Association, Eiji Suzuki; philosopher
Yujiro Nakamura and professors of medicine.
   Cancer is Japan's No. 1 killer disease, causing 26.6 percent of
all deaths last year, with stomach cancer topping the list.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Oct. 20</NOTE>
</DOC>
