<1ST_LINE>a a BC-EXP--ColdLaboratory 1stLd-Writethru Adv20 10-17 0693</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EXP--Cold Laboratory, 1st Ld-Writethru, Adv 20, b0965,0709</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Thursday, Oct. 20, and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Scientists Seek Physics Answers at Cornell Cold Spot</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Restores dropped word `temperature' in 2nd graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM KATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ITHACA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There are no dangling icicles in Clark Hall,
no frost on the walls, and breathing doesn't produce vapor clouds.
But it's still one of the coldest known spots in the universe.
   ``It doesn't look very impressive but we are going to go a
million times colder than the coldest natural place we know of,''
says Robert C. Richardson, head of the low-temperature physics
group at Cornell University's Microkelvin Laboratory.
   Richardson and his colleagues, using a $1.5 million
super-refrigeration unit, will try to achieve absolute zero _ the
temperature at which even atoms stop rubbing together and creating
heat.
   ``We think we can take it down to between 1 and 10
microkelvin,'' he said. ``And each step of the way, we could be
finding new effects.''
   The only other U.S. deep-freeze laboratory is under construction
at the University of Florida. Labs in Japan and England have hit 12
microkelvin.
   How cold is that?
   The temperature of deep space, minus 270 degrees Fahrenheit, is
only 3 on the Kelvin scale, which uses absolute zero for a
reference point. Absolute zero in Fahrenheit is minus 459 degrees,
while room temperature would be 293 Kelvin.
   A millikelvin is a thousandth of a Kelvin, so a microkelvin is a
millionth.
   Dropping from 12 microkelvin to 10 microkelvin might seem
inconsequential, but Richardson adds this perspective: ``If you
increased room temperature by the same ratio, everything would melt
or disintegrate.''
   The researchers aren't simply out to break records, though.
   ``The importance of this type of research lies in realizing the
strange things that happen at low temperatures,'' said William
Oosterhuis, section head of the condensed matter sciences unit at
the National Science Foundation. ``One just never knows what's
going to happen. This research provides us with a probe into an
area where we've never been before.''
   Among the strange discoveries of extremely low-temperature
research has been superconductivity _ electricity with no loss to
resistance _ at 4 Kelvin.
   ``Sometimes it is the arithmetic or the theory behind the
research that has the practical application,'' said Donald H.
Liebenberg, who helped the lab get NSF funding before he left in
April for the Office of Naval Research.
   ``Sometimes the technology produced has broader applications in
other fields. The most important aspect, though, is that these
facilities will be breeding grounds of technological spinoffs for
future low temperature research,'' Liebenberg said.
   Individual scientists have conducted low temperature research
before, but the lack of a permanent facility to maintain such
temperatures indefinitely and allow for varied experiments has been
an obstacle, Richardson said. ``Now we have an adequate tool to
find _ or at least search properly _ for the answers to all the
open questions that remain in front of us.''
   The rooms adjoining Cornell's 2,800-square-foot underground
laboratory are designed to eliminate all stray heat, including that
produced from the most minute vibrations and from radio-frequency
electrical signals.
   To that end, they are lined with butcher block wood and
galvanized electromagnetic shielding and have specially grounded
electrical wiring and incandescent lighting. The low temperature
instruments are secured by concrete sewer pipes filled with sand.
   The supercooling machines themselves are rigid aluminum, filled
with liquid helium, copper and superconducting magnets. The
apparatus stands 12 feet tall and weighs about 700 pounds, but the
focus is on a 36-inch vacuum cylinder.
   To reach microkelvin temperatures, a process that takes about
two weeks, scientists first polarize copper with a superconducting
magnet, then cool it to around 10 millikelvin in the refrigerator,
which uses liquid helium rather than freon gas for cooling. Once
the copper is at 10 millikelvin, the magnetic field is reduced and
the copper nuclei, which are now aligned and highly ordered, take
over, further cooling everything in the surrounding medium.
   ``We can never be sure what will be found,'' said Richardson.
``Maybe we'll have the good fortune to stumble upon a new science.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Oct. 20</NOTE>
