<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-88 0730EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     10-17 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights,0545</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Food costs, showing further effects from the
drought, accelerated sharply in September, but a big drop in energy
costs kept the overall rise in wholesale prices at a moderate 0.4
percent, the government reported.
   The Reagan administration claimed that Friday's report showed
inflation was not heating up. But some private economists expressed
worries about what could happen if world oil prices suddenly
rebound.
   The September increase represented a drop from an August
increase of 0.6 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retail sales in September dropped for the
second consecutive month, the government said, confirming
economists' views that the confidence of U.S. consumers is slipping.
   The Commerce Department said Friday that sales fell 0.4 percent
last month to a seasonally adjusted $133.7 billion. That followed a
dip of 0.1 percent in August and was the first back-to-back drop
since September-October 1987.
   The government data is consistent with a survey earlier this
week for The Conference Board, a business research organization.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. industrial production in September failed
to rise for the first time in seven months, the government said,
suggesting to economists that the overheated manufacturing sector
is cooling a bit.
   The Federal Reserve Board said Friday that output at the
nation's facories, mines and utilities was unchanged last month
after increasing a slight 0.2 percent in August and an unusually
large 1.2 percent in July.
   The production index has gone 12 months without a decline, but
September was the first time since February that it did not rise.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators pledged $1.3 billion to
rescue 11 insolvent savings institutions in Texas, selling them to
a cable television company.
   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board said Friday that Adam
Corporation@Group of Bryant, Texas, a cable TV station operator, is
investing $65 million now and an additional $15 million by the end
of 1990 to acquire the 11 institutions.
   They are being merged under the name of Olney Savings and Loan
Association. All deposits, even those over the insurance limit of
$100,000, are transferring, the bank board said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp.'s profit
rose 3.2 percent in the third quarter, the world's largest computer
maker said in a report that lifted its stock.
   Revenue climbed 5.3 percent, an indication that IBM is
succeeding in switching customers to new large and mid-sized
computers without a big drop in sales of older models, analysts
said Friday.
   ``They (earnings) were pretty decent,'' said Steven Cohen, an
analyst for Soundview Financial Group in Stamford, Conn.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allegheny International Inc. said it still
intends to emerge from Chapter 11 reorganization by year's end or
early in 1989 even though the parties in the case have asked for a
month's delay in a key hearing.
   ``It's very common for large claims to be made, but they are
ultimately settled for significantly less,'' company spokesman
Edward Romanoff said Friday.
   Earlier, company officials told Bankruptcy Judge Joseph Cosetti
that they need time to study $2.5 billion in claims pending against
the consumer products company.
</TEXT>
