<1ST_LINE>r f PM-GoingPublic 1stLd-Writethru f0007 10-17 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Going Public, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0007,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IPOs Grind To Halt in Wake of Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs, Of the ..., with one graf to CORRECT to
Thornton sted Thorton. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, ``The number ...</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: For Release 10 a.m. EDT; time set by source</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Last year's stock market crash decimated the
hopes of nearly half the companies waiting to go public and reduced
the amount of cash others could raise in the equity market, a study
released today said.
   Of the 229 businesses on file with the Securities and Exchange
Commission on Oct. 19, 1987 to issue stock for the first time, 45
percent had abandoned those plans nine months after ``Black
Monday,'' according to the accounting and consulting firm Grant
Thornton.
   ``The number of busted (initial public offerings) we identified
is unprecedented,'' said Chet Borgida, director of the firm's
capital markets group and head of the study.
   ``We all knew that going public was tougher after Black Monday.
We just didn't know how tough.''
   Fewer than 25 percent of the companies planning to go public
were able to do so since the crash, the study showed. Another 31
percent still were on file with the SEC to go public as of July 31.
   Those companies that braved the equities market succeeded in
raising an average $15.9 million. But Grant Thornton estimated that
each of those same companies would have raised an average of $7.2
million more had they completed their public offerings before the
crash.
   Small and mid-sized companies were most severely affected,
Borgida said. ``Most of the companies that wanted to go public
couldn't, and those that did had to settle for less capital than
they needed.''
   Of 51 companies that participated in a Grant Thornton poll, 27
said they had obtained financing from alternative sources including
commercial banks, private placements and, less frequently, from
venture capitalists.
   Despite the grim environment, 86 percent of the companies
participating in the poll _ including half of the businesses that
withdrew their initial public offerings _ said they would
considering going public if they could make the choice again.
   ``As least in the view of America's entrepreneurs, there is no
substitute for going public,'' Borgida said. ``Even in this most
difficult year for financing, companies still believe that they can
raise the greatest amount of capital most efficiently through the
public equity markets.''
</TEXT>
