<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet10am     10-17 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 10am,0310</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices were mixed today, marking time in
an atmosphere of continuing caution.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials inched ahead 1.42 to
2,134.60 in the first half hour of trading.
   But losers outnumbered gainers by about 5 to 4 in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 383 up, 471
down and 486 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 17.63 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Analysts said traders took a generally upbeat view of the
current state of the economy.
   Evidence has continued to accumulate that growth has slowed of
late to a steady, sustainable pace.
   But inflation worries haven't been entirely snuffed out on Wall
Street, and brokers said investors were looking ahead warily to
Friday's scheduled report on the consumer price index for September.
   Furthermore, just about all market-watchers agree, stocks are
likely to be a tough product to sell all week with the anniversary
Wednesday of last fall's crash, and all the attendant publicity.
   Hospital Corp. of America rose ~ to 49[ in active trading. A
special committee of outside directors rejected a $51-a-share
buyout bid by management, asserting that there were other parties
that might be willing to make a higher offer.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
gained .11 to 155.57. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was up .03 at 302.58.
   On Friday the Dow Jones industrial average closed with a .18
loss at 2,133.18, finishing the week down 17.07 points.
   Advancing issues slightly outnumbered declines on the NYSE, with
714 up, 650 down and 534 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 160.24 million shares, against 154.53
million in the previous session.
</TEXT>
