<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   10-17 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures were mostly lower in
early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade, reflecting
pessimism about grain sales to the Soviet Union and an increase in
crop sales by farmers.
   But early losses were slight due to the supportive influence of
weekend rains in the Midwest and relatively dry growing conditions
in Brazil and Argentina, which are large producers of soybeans,
analysts said.
   ``Their situation is improving down there, but they still need
rain,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader in Chicago with Dean
Witter Reynolds Inc.
   The weekend rain in the Midwest slowed the U.S. corn and soybean
harvest, which is more than half complete, Lespinasse said. More
rain was expected today and Wednesday.
   On Friday, negotiators for the United States and the Soviet
Union ended two days of talks in London without a new long-term
grain agreement. Disappointment over the failure to produce an
agreement continued to weigh on the markets today, Lespinasse said.
   In early trading, wheat was { cent to 2} cents lower with
December at $4.26 a bushel; corn was unchanged to 1\ cents lower
with December at $2.93 a bushel; oats were 2{ cents lower across
the board with December at $2.50 a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent to
3{ cents lower with November at $8.02 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were mostly lower
in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .18 cent lower to .05 cent higher with October
at 72.85 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .17 cent lower to .18
cent higher with October at 82.05 cents a pound; hogs were
unchanged to .30 cent lower with October at 40.25 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .02 cent to .30 cent lower with February
at 48.80 cents a pound.
   Cattle finished mostly lower on Friday while pork futures were
mixed.
