<TEXT>
   Stock prices were little changed in quiet
trading today, getting little benefit from new evidence of a
slowing economy.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials slipped .89 to 2,132.29
by noontime on Wall Street.
   Gainers slightly outnumbered losers in nationwide trading of New
York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 610 up, 600 down and 563
unchanged.
   Analysts said traders took a generally upbeat view of the
current state of the economy, believing that growth hasasonable basis.''
   Lawyers for the Securities and Exchange Commission had contested
Drexel's motion to remove Pollack.
   ``I think the judge's opinion was in accordance with our legal
position,'' said Barry Goldsmith, an SEC deputy litigation counsel
who is handling the day-to-day affairs of the Drexel case. ``Right
now we're looking forward to getting on with the merits of the
case.''
   Attorneys for others who have sued Drexel and Boesky also
applauded the ruling of Pollack, who is widely known as a
no-nonsense judge who often rules in the government's favor in
white-collar fraud cases.
   ``I am delighted by the decision,'' said David Berger, a lead
attorney for shareholders that have filed a class action suit
against Drexel and Boesky. He described the defense effort to
disqualify Pollack as ``just a litigation ploy, an attempt to stall
the evil day.''
   Drexel spokesman Steven Anreder said in a statement: ``Our
attorneys had a professional obligation to bring this issue before
the court. Since it is their considered view that, based on the
facts in the motion, Judge Pollack's position is incorrect, the
matter will be placed before the 2nd circuit Court of Appeals.''
   The SEC filed a civil suit against Drexel, its high-yield bond
financier Michael Milken and three other employees of the firm
Sept. 7, alleging they schemed with Boesky to profit on insider
trading, manipulate stock, cheat Drexel clients and commit other
frauds.
   The defendants denied the allegations. Up to now the case has
largely been stalled over disputes about Pollack's impartiality and
pretrial evidence requests by both sides.
