<1ST_LINE>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv18   10-17 0570</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 18,0588</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 18</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Tuesday Oct 18</NOTE>
<HEAD>A House or a Bank?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some housing and real estate folks are prepared
to quash any attempts to lessen the tax deduction of home mortgage
interest, suggesting that such efforts would be an attack on the
American dream itself.
   Others in the industry, however, question the threat to home
ownership, mainly because the current indebtedness cap _ the limit
on mortgage interest that may be deducted from taxes _ is $1
million.
   In their view, an allowance of that size benefits very few
Americans and, as a corollary, provides a huge tax deduction for a
privileged few _ one that may have very little to do with providing
shelter.
   The issue is controversial even within the industry.
   A commentary by Nestor R. Weigand Jr., president of the National
Association of Realtors, warning that some members of Congress
wished to cut the million-dollar cap, drew both negative and
positive responses.
   Perhaps typical of the negative responses was a letter to the
editor of Realtor News, the association's weekly newspaper, stating
that ``those fortunate enough to own a lavish home do not need the
large tax savings.''
   The most commonly cited reason for opposing any cut in the
deductibility seems to be that one cut might be followed by more,
perhaps even leading to eventual elimination of any deduction of
home mortgage interest.
   Defending that stand, another letter to Realtor News cautioned
that when Congress is thwarted in attempts to raise taxes, members
``could merely lower the cap on the mortgage interest deduction and
then tell their constituents that they were able to stave off any
attempt to raise taxes.''
   Whatever the merits or lack of them, the tax deductiblity has
produced some situations that are difficult to equate with the
promotion of home ownership.
   It can, for example, encourage homeownership as an investment
rather than shelter.
   In one instance, an individual can invest in a home far more
expensive than he or she might have purchased without the
deduction. The purpose: To obtain a maximum mortgage that generates
enough deductions to offset taxes on income.
   Moreover, any increases in the home's value is tax-deferred,
meaning that no tax is paid until the house is sold. The same money
invested in interest-bearing securities would be taxed annually.
   A big mortgage _ perhaps encouraged by the tax deductiblity _
also offers unusual leverage for an investor.
   If, for example, a $1.5 million house is purchased with the
assistance of a million-dollar mortgage, and in a year's time rises
4 percent in value to $1.56 million, the original $500,000 cash
investment has earned 12 percent.
   That $60,000 gain is, of course, tax deferred so long as the
house is not sold. Moreover, the homeowner may obtain an
additional, relatively low cost equity loan up to $100,000 for any
purpose, and deduct all the interest.
   While the issue of the $1 million cap is fairly dormant at the
moment, various proposals have been circulating through Congress,
convincing Weigand and others that sometime next year another
suggestion will be made to cut.
   As they see it, their stand is an effort to defend homeownership.
   As some critics view it, however, the issue is really whether a
house should be a home, or a personal bank instead.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Tues Oct 18</NOTE>
</DOC>
