<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Kodak-Japan     10-17 0410</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kodak-Japan,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kodak Planning First Manufacturing Facility in Japan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastman Kodak Co. announced plans Monday
to open its first manufacturing plant in Japan, a move that could
be viewed as a tit for tat with rival Fuji Photo Film Co. Ltd.
   Kodak expects to open its finishing and packaging facility for
certain graphic arts films by the end of the year, said company
spokesman Ron Roberts. It is in Yokohama and will initially employ
10 workers.
   ``There may be some thought that this will send a message to
Fuji that if they do more in the U.S., Kodak will do more in
Japan,'' said Peter Enderlin, a stock analyst with Smith Barney,
Harris Upham & Co. in New York.
   Kodak's announcement comes 10 days after Fuji held
groundbreaking ceremonies for its first manufacturing plant in the
United States, said Fuji spokeswoman Carol O'Laughlin.
   That plant, located in Greenwood, S.C., will also make products
for the graphic arts industry. It will employ about 150 people and
be about seven times larger than Kodak's facility.
   Roberts said Kodak's decision to open a plant in Japan had
nothing to do with Fuji or any other competitor.
   ``This is not a reaction to that. The two are not related,''
said Roberts. ``Our decision is a business decision, a response to
what we see in the market.''
   Roberts said Kodak is opening the plant, which will cut and
package huge rolls of the company's film shipped in from Rochester,
to become more efficient in making several graphic arts products
that come in sizes unique to the Japanese market.
   Enderlin said the primary reason Kodak is planning to open a
plant in Japan is most likely to take advantage of currency
fluctuations between the dollar and the yen.
   Eugene Glazer, an analyst for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in New
York, said it was clear that the small plant is ``the forerunner of
a greater effort'' and a way for Kodak to try out running a
manufacturing operation in Japan.
   ``It will also keep Fuji nervous, keep Fuji on its toes in
Japan,'' Glazer said.
   Analysts also said the Japanese manufacturing facility also
continues Kodak's increased emphasis in Japan, where the company
recently opened a large research and development facility.
   Kodak also has introduced its new ``Ektar'' line of color film
for serious amateur photographers in Japan before putting it on
shelves in the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
