<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Close Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mostly
higher Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade in reaction to wet
weather in the Corn Belt, dry conditions in South America and new
wheat demand from China.
   Showers slowed the rapid harvest pace in the Midwest, where corn
and soybean gathering is approaching completion. Forecasters
predicted more rain on Wednesday, which sparked additional buying.
   Soybean prices received an additional boost from reports of
lighter-than-expected weekend rains in the soybean-growing regions
of Brazil and Argentina.
   ``The situation has improved down there, there's no doubt about
that, but they're not out of the woods yet. They need more rain,''
said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   The wheat market rallied on news that China had submitted a bid
for 280,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat, he said.
   At the close, wheat was unchanged to 4 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.30{ a bushel; corn was \
cent lower to 1\ cents higher with December at $2.95 a bushel; oats
were 1{ cents to 2} cents higher at $2.55\ a bushel; soybeans were
5 cents to 8 cents higher with November at $8.10{ a bushel.
