<DOCNO> AP881017-0269 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-88 1511EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet3pm     10-17 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0299</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices showed a modest gain in quiet
trading today, aided by new evidence of a slowing economy.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 8.18 to 2,141.36 by
3 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Gainers slightly outnumbered losers in nationwide trading of New
York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 730 up, 664 down and 531
unchanged.
   Analysts said traders took a generally upbeat view of the
current state of the economy, believing that growth has slowed of
late to a steady, sustainable pace.
   Those hopes drew some fresh support from government statistics
issued this morning that showed a drop in capacity use in September.
   But inflation worries haven't been entirely snuffed out on Wall
Street, and brokers said investors were looking ahead warily to
Friday's scheduled report on the consumer price index for September.
   Furthermore, just about all market-watchers agree, stocks are
likely to be a tough product to sell all week with the anniversary
Wednesday of last fall's crash, and all the attendant publicity.
   Hospital Corp. of America rose { to 48} in active trading. A
special committee of outside directors rejected a $51-a-share
buyout bid by management, asserting that there were other parties
that might be willing to make a higher offer.
   Other gains among the volume leaders included Chrysler, up } at
26[; International Business Machines, up 1| at 121], and American
Telephone & Telegraph, up [ at 26}.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.47 to 155.93. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .57 at 303.12.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 99.37 million shares with an
hour to go.
</TEXT>
