<DOCNO> AP881017-0270 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-88 1617EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-UN-WorldDebt     10-17 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-UN-World Debt,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Says Governments, Private Banks Must Slash Debt Of Third
World</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Governments and private lenders must write
off part of the Third World's debt if they hope to see those
nations recover from economic stagnation, Secretary-General Javier
Perez de Cuellar said in a report released Monday.
   Perez de Cuellar is scheduled Wednesday to address the U.N.
committee dealing with the world debt crisis, and the committee's
resolution will go to the floor of the General Assembly for debate.
   In introducing the secretary-general's report, Jean Ripert, head
of the U.N.'s office of Development and International Economic
Cooperation, said that ``the service of their debt is killing
investment in these (developing) countries.''
   ``The report before you relates the debt problem squarely to the
current crisis of development in a large part of the world,''
Ripert said. ``Lack of finance, low commodity prices, high interest
rates, severe protectionism are leading to substantive net transfer
of resources from developing and debtor nations to the developed
countries.
   ``If the present trends continue, the debt crisis will remain an
obstacle to growth in the indebted countries for at least another
decade.''
   Writing off debt, unthinkable in the financial community a year
ago, ``is no more a taboo'' since the seven major industrial
democracies advocated forgiving part of Africa's debt at their
summit in Toronto last summer, according to the report.
   The secretary-general's report notes the so-called ``moral
hazard'' of forgiving debts if that leads to new borrowing, but
notes that ``politicians are not generally considered successful by
their constituents if they need an international rescue.''
   If the 15 most indebted developing countries received
forgiveness of 30 percent of their private bank debt or interest
payments due, about $10 billion would be available for
growth-producing investment, the report says.
   Those 15 countries are Argentina, Bolivia, Brazil, Chile,
Colombia, Ivory Coast, Ecuador, Mexico, Morocco, Nigeria, Peru,
Philippines, Uruguay, Venezuela and Yugoslavia, which together owe
about $300 billion to commercial banks.
   Developing nations owed a total of about $1.2 trillion to
governments and commercial lenders at the end of 1987.
   Much of the new investment ``could be expected to be channelled
into imports of capital goods from developed market-economy
countries,'' benefiting their economies, says the report.
   The report estimates that those orders would boost the economies
of the developed countries by about 1 percent of their industrial
output.
   Governments in developed countries should also forgive debt owed
to them as a result of foreign aid loans, the report says.
   The secretary-general's report was prepared with analysis by the
U.N. Conference on Trade and Development in consultation with
leading financiers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881017-0271 </DOCNO>
