<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Germany-SovietCredit     10-17 0204</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Germany-Soviet Credit,0211</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>German Banks Sign Soviet Credit Pact</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A consortium of West German banks
on Monday signed a $1.6 billion credit agreement for the Soviet
Union.
   Deutsche Bank AG, West Germany's largest commercial bank which
is heading the consortium, said it signed the agreement with
Moscow's Bank for Foreign Economic Affairs.
   The bank in May announced it was heading an effort to extend the
credit to the Soviets to boost their consumer goods production and
delivery systems.
   The $1.6 billion credit line is set up to finance West German
exports aimed at expansion and modernization of the Soviet consumer
goods industry, notably the food, leather, textile and clothing
sectors.
   The agreement will be finalized with another signing ceremony
scheduled for Oct. 24 in Moscow, when Chancellor Helmut Kohl
arrives in the Soviet capital for an official visit.
   Separately, the West German Economics Ministry said it was
encouring German companies to seek more joint ventures with Soviet
enterprises as a means of boosting economic relations.
   Trade between West Germany and the Soviet Union dropped to $8.3
billion in 1987 from $10.30 billion in 1986, but the Economics
Ministry said total trade volume is expected to stabilize this year.
</TEXT>
