<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SoftwareFight     10-17 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Software Fight,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AT&T May Gain Support Tuesday In Contest Over Software</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hopes appeared to fade on Monday for an
agreement to end a computer industry split over the future of Unix,
a base layer of software that makes it easier for different brands
of computers to communicate.
   The fight over Unix has dismayed computer users, who are left
undecided about which rival version of Unix they should adopt as
their own. Programs that work with one version of Unix may not work
with the other.
   Several companies involved in the high-stakes tussle are
planning to issue a statement Tuesday rallying around American
Telephone & Telegraph Co.'s version of Unix, the weekly trade
newspaper Computerworld said in Monday's editions.
   Such a group would be a rival to the Open Software Foundation,
which includes such giants as International Business Machines
Corp., Digital Equipment Corp. and Hewlett-Packard Co.
   Although AT&T invented Unix, members of the Open Software
Foundation say its development should be controlled by an
industrywide organization so AT&T does not have an unfair advantage
with it.
   AT&T has said it will not join the Open Software Foundation
unless it uses AT&T's version of Unix as the core of a new
operating system. But the foundation is sticking with plans to use
IBM software as the core.
   Robert Kavner, president of AT&T's Data Systems Group, told
Computerworld that AT&T and 10 other companies will form a group to
develop jointly future versions of Unix.
   AT&T spokesman Dick Muldoon confirmed the accuracy of the
article, although he said Kavner has denied that the new group is
intended to counter the influence of the rival Open Software
Foundation.
   Kavner would not identify the companies that would belong to the
new Unix group, but said candidates would include Unisys Corp., NCR
Corp., Amdahl Corp., Ing. C. Olivetti & Co. SpA, Sun Microsystems
Inc., Fujitsu America Inc. and others.
   NCR spokesman Kelly Kramer said there were tentative plans for
some kind of joint statement by several companies on Tuesday. He
said he did not know what it might say.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
