<DOCNO> AP881017-0275 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-88 1744EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Upjohn     10-17 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Upjohn,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Upjohn's Profit Up 20 Percent in Third Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KALAMAZOO, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Upjohn Co. reported a 20 percent rise in
its third-quarter profit from a year earlier, due largely to an
increase in foreign sales and favorable foreign-exchange rates.
   The pharmaceutical company said Monday that its net income in
the three months ended Sept. 30 rose to $89.6 million, or 49 cents
a share, from $74.6 million, or 40 cents a share, a year earlier.
   Third-quarter sales were up 7 percent, to $651.8 million from
$608.5 million.
   Foreign sales, which account for 39 percent of Upjohn's total
sales, jumped 14 percent in the quarter while U.S. sales rose only
3 percent. The continued slide in the dollar against other major
currencies made Upjohn's products cheaper and more competitive
overseas.
   Upjohn said its Rogaine anti-baldness formula led its major
products in foreign sales growth.
   Rogaine was approved Aug. 17 for marketing in the United States
and is expected to contribute to continued foreign and domestic
gains, Chairman Theodore Cooper said.
   Rogaine now is sold in more than 50 countries including Canada,
where it is called Regaine.
   ``But the U.S. approval was critical to realizing the product's
full potential,'' Cooper said.
   Upjohn announced last week that Rogaine was available in
pharmacies for men whose doctors prescribe it. The company said it
was briefing physicians on the product in preparation for a public
promotional campaign.
   Upjohn also reported third-quarter sales gains for its Xanax and
Halcion central nervous system agents and its Micronase oral
antidiabetes medication.
   A 19 percent increase in sales of agricultural items, including
animal health products and seed, also helped sales, the company
said.
   In the first nine months of the year, net income rose 17 percent
_ to $272.8 million, or $1.47 a share, from $234.1 million, or
$1.25 a share, a year earlier.
   Nine-month sales grew 9 percent, to $2.04 billion from $1.87
billion.
</TEXT>
