<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Earns-Banks     10-17 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Banks,0497</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chase, Morgan, First Chicago Report Higher 3rd Qtr Profit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Chase Manhattan Corp., the nation's second-largest banking
company, on Monday reported its third-quarter profit jumped 25
percent, while earnings rose 6.6 percent at No. 4-ranked J.P.
Morgan & Co. and 80 percent at First Chicago Corp., the nation's
11th-largest banker.
   Chase said it earned $283 million, or $3.09 a share, during the
three months ended Sept. 30, up from $226 million, or $2.55 a
share, in the same period a year earlier.
   For the first three quarters of 1988, Chase said it had earnings
of $784 million, or $8.62 per share, compared with a loss of $1.05
billion for the same period last year. The results for the 1987
period included a second-quarter charge of $1.6 billion to cover
shaky Third World debt.
   Morgan said its third-quarter net income totaled $233.6 million,
or $1.25 a share, up from earnings of $219.2 million, or $1.18 a
share, in the same period a year ago.
   For the first nine months, the company had a profit of $743.7
million, or $4 a share, compared with a $140.8 million loss in the
same period of 1987. The year-earlier results included an $875
million loan-loss provision similar to those taken by Chase and
other major banks.
   First Chicago said its third-quarter profit jumped 80 percent,
to $111.1 million, or $1.73 per share, from $61.8 million, or $1.05
a share, in the same period of 1987.
   For the nine-month period, First Chicago earned a record $375.8
million, or $6.13 a share, compared with a $474.2 million loss last
in the first nine months of last year, when it added $855 million
to its loan-loss reserves.
   Chase said its third-quarter earnings included an after-tax gain
of about $103 million from changes in its pension plan. The company
said the results also included higher foreign exchange trading
income, investment banking fees and trading account gains.
   The company reported a decline in net interest income because it
placed about $538 million in credit to Argentine borrowers on
nonaccrual status. That means the bank will no longer include on
its own statements the interest and other charges due on the loans
until the money is actually received.
   Morgan attributed its improved earnings performance partly to
higher non-interest operating income, due largely to foreign
exchange and trading profits, which more than doubled from a year
ago.
   The company's provision for credit losses of $20 million was
unchanged from the 1987 quarter.
   First Chicago said its provision for loan losses declined to $50
million from $75 million a year ago, and that helped improve the
earnings picture in the third quarter.
   ``Our progress ... is shown by the improvement both in capital
ratios and in credit quality, where we have the lowest provision
for credit losses in four years,'' Chairman Barry F. Sullivan said
in a statement.
</TEXT>
