<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-88 1920EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-LaptopComputers     10-17 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Laptop Computers,0200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sharp Unveils New Laptop And Reveals Tie To Compaq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sharp Electronics Corp. introduced a laptop
computer on Monday and revealed that it is the source of the
high-quality screens used on a laptop from Compaq Computer Corp.
that was also unveiled Monday.
   The Compaq and Sharp machines are the first laptops capable of a
high standard of graphics display known as VGA, for Video Graphics
Array.
   Compaq said its flat screen was from a Japanese source, but had
declined to say which company. ``We're the ones,'' said Sharp
spokesman Ted Smits.
   Compaq says companies that use the same flat screen it uses
would not necessarily have as good graphics, because the display
quality also depends on a Compaq-designed chip. The company said it
could not compare its screen with Sharp's because it had not seen
Sharp's yet.
   The machines from Sharp and Compaq are similar in other respects
as well: both weigh 14 pounds and have the same kinds of
microprocessors, main memory, data storage and batteries. Sharp's
suggested price is about $400 lower, at $5,595 for a version with a
40-megabyte hard disk drive.
</TEXT>
