<1ST_LINE>r f AM-NissanResearch     10-17 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nissan Research,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Nissan Research Center to Develop New Vehicle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FARMINGTON HILLS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new, $50 million Nissan
research and development center, planned for operation by 1990,
will design and create a new vehicle for the United States, Nissan
officials said Monday.
   ``If we weren't going to do this next project, then we'd have no
reason to do this research and development,'' Duane Miller, vice
president for design engineering for Nissan Research & Development
Inc. said at a ground breaking for the new center northwest of
Detroit.
   ``Sometime next year, we will begin the next vehicle to be
manufactured in the Tennessee plant,'' Miller said of Nissan Motor
Corp. in U.S.A.'s factory in Smyrna, Tenn., where the company makes
its Sentra cars and light trucks.
   He declined to characterize the new vehicle. The Smyrna plant
has room for another assembly line and enough land for new
factories.
   Also at the ceremony, Takeshi Tanuma, president of the research
and development company, said the center will provide design and
other research work for a minivan to be assembled as a joint
venture between Nissan and Ford Motor Co. and the unspecified
vehicle.
   Tanuma and Miller said the new vehicle would not be exported
from the United States.
   ``Our main objective is to design a car and truck for this
country,'' Tanuma said. He said the decision to put the center in
the Detroit area came because of the number of automotive engineers
in the area.
   Tanuma also said the company was considering putting an engine
plant in the United States, a move some people have seen as
essential to broadening the company's assembly capabilities in the
United States.
   The center, to occupy 200,000 to 250,000 square feet at the site
of a former golf club, will employ about 400 people, three-fourths
of them U.S. citizens, officials said. Construction is to begin
next spring.
   Nissan Research is a joint venture between Nissan Motor Ltd. of
Japan and its U.S. automaker. Nissan Research now has offices in
Ann Arbor and Plymouth, some which will be consolidated at the
center in Farmington Hills.
   Officials said Monday that design work on the new vehicle and
other projects are going on now in Ann Arbor. Nissan operates other
research and development facilities in Tokyo and Newcastle, England.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
