<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-CorningGlass     10-17 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Corning Glass,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Corning Glass Reports Record 3rd-Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CORNING, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corning Glass Works more than doubled its
net income in the third quarter to a record $123.9 million from $50
million during the same period last year, the company said Monday.
   Corning Chairman James Houghton said ``the excellent results
came from equity companies as well as strength across the board in
virtually all Corning businesses, where the rate of profitability
was the best we've seen for a third quarter in the last decade.''
   Even without one-time gains of $59 million stemming from
transactions in Japan, the third-quarter results were a company
record.
   On a per-share basis, Corning returned $2.74 compared to $1.08 a
year ago. Sales for quarter totaled $625.4 million, up 2.5 percent
from $610.1 million in the same period a year ago. The company said
the figure was up 11 percent if adjusted for the disposition of the
electronics business in 1987.
   For the 40 weeks ended Oct. 9, the company reported net income
of $243 million, up from $148.5 million, and sales of $1.58
billion, up from $1.54 billion.
   Charles Ryan, analyst for Merrill Lynch in New York, said
Corning's restructuring efforts during the past few years have paid
off. The glass maker based in upstate New York has focused its
research and development in four main areas _ fiber optics and
telecommunications; medical diagnostic services; ceramics and
specialty glasses; and household products.
   Optical fiber sales were modestly improved, according to Stephen
Albertalli, a Corning vice president.
   ``We projected a flat year in the volatile fiber optics
market,'' Albertalli said. ``We're doing a little better than we
expected.''
   The company's clinical testing service subsidiary, MedPath,
Inc., expanded exports to Latin American and Asia and was part of
the reason for a 31 percent increase in income from equity
companies.
   A new manufacturing facility being built by Corning and Asahi
Glass in Osooka, Japan is expected to expand Corning's presence in
the world market for specialty glass. The plant, which is due to
open in 1989, will manufacture glass used in the display modules of
portable computers and other electronic devices.
   The companies household products unit, which manufactures
Corning Glassware, also showed strong sales gains.
</TEXT>
