<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Computer, 1st Ld-Writethru,0527</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unisys, NCR Report Record Quarterly Profits; Lotus Declines</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after lede and adds 3 grafs at end to update
with Lotus earnings.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Unisys Corp. and NCR Corp. reported record third-quarter profits
on Monday, but both of the computer makers said they expected a
slowdown next year. They said demand was softest in the United
States.
   Meanwhile, Lotus Development Corp., the maker of personal
computer software, said its profit fell 25.1 percent and blamed the
decline on the cost of promotions for its 1-2-3 spreadsheet program.
   Unisys said it expected its results next year to be hurt by
``weak conditions'' in the U.S. computer market, the tight U.S.
defense budget and the renewed strength of the dollar, which makes
American-made goods more expensive in foreign markets.
   Unisys said it was aiming for single-digit revenue increases but
double-digit earnings gains in 1989.
   NCR also said it expected single-digit percentage gains in
revenue next year, but made no profit forecast. The company said
its orders had fallen in the latest quarter from the record levels
of a year earlier.
   Unisys, which has headquarters in Blue Bell, Pa., and Detroit,
said its profit rose 16.4 percent to a record $151 million, or 72
cents per share on a fully diluted basis, from $129.7 million, or
65 cents per fully diluted share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 2
percent to $2.27 billion from $2.22 billion.
   Fully diluted refers to the number of shares that would be
outstanding if all convertible preferred stock were converted into
common shares.
   For the first nine months of its fiscal year, Unisys said its
earnings rose 28.1 percent to $462.6 million, or $2.22 per fully
diluted share, from $361.1 million, or $1.84 a fully diluted share,
a year earlier. Revenue rose 1.6 percent to $7.03 billion from
$6.91 billion.
   NCR, based in Dayton, Ohio, said its revenue and earnings were a
record for a third quarter. Earnings rose to $103.1 million, or
$1.26 a share, from $97.8 million, or $1.05 a share, a year
earlier. Revenue rose to $1.41 billion from $1.34 billion.
   For the nine months, profit rose 12.3 percent to $289.7 million,
or $3.49 a share, from $257.9 million, or $2.74 a share, a year
earlier. Revenue to $4.19 billion from $3.82 billion.
   Lotus, of Cambridge, Mass., said it took a charge against its
earnings to reflect the costs it will incur when it gives free
upgrades to its upcoming version of Lotus 1-2-3 to the people who
purchased existing versions under a special promotion.
   Lotus, which repeatedly has postponed introduction of the new
software, said it earned $14.3 million in the quarter ended Oct. 1,
or 31 cents a share, down from $19.1 million, or 42 cents a share,
a year earlier. Sales rose to $116.8 million, from $101.2 million.
   For the first nine months of its fiscal year, Lotus said its
profit rose to $49.9 million, or $1.08 a share, from $49.1 million,
also $1.08 a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose to $356.2 million,
from $280 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
