<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-88 2022EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-MineLayoffs     10-17 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mine Layoffs,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mine Lays Off 140 Workers; Blames Feds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REDSTONE, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mid-Continent Resources Inc. laid off 140
miners Monday and blamed federal mine inspectors for oppressive
enforcement.
   The coal company claims that excessive inspections by the U.S.
Mine Safety & Health Administration, including 273 safety orders
and 1,381 safety citations in the past year, prevents Mid-Continent
from filling a South Korean coal contract.
   The layoffs came four days after a federal judge declined to
issue an injunction requested by Mid-Continent to halt what the
company views as overzealous inspections by MSHA.
   However, the top federal inspector for western coal mines said
he put round-the-clock inspectors at the Coal Basin mines because
Mid-Continent continually failed to meet safety standards.
   In 1981, 15 miners died in a methane explosion at a
Mid-Continent mine. The company's property is in the Crystal River
Valley of western Colorado, about 40 miles from Aspen.
   John DeMichiei, western manager for MSHA, said Mid-Continent
miners shouldn't be exposed to the hazards he's found in the deep,
gassy mines.
   ``We're not fabricating problems,'' he said. ``A failure to
comply will inevitably result in another incident.''
   Diane Delaney, spokeswoman for Mid-Continent, said the layoff of
29 percent of the company's work force was ``too bad, because it's
not necessary. But until we get this worked out with MSHA, we can't
work.''
   The company is backing out of its hard-won, 10-year coal
contract with Pohang Iron and Steel Co., Delaney said, citing a
loss of $30 million in trade each year.
   Delaney said the South Korean company bought 80 percent of the
mine's coal in 1987 and kept Mid-Continent afloat during the
13-month steelworkers' strike at Geneva Steel in Orem, Utah,
Mid-Continent's other major customer.
   A company news release described ``an increasingly adversarial
and counterproductive relationship'' between Mid-Continent and MSHA.
   The judge who heard company arguments about MSHA advised
mediation last Thursday and estimated a ruling might be made in
three or four months.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
