<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SEC-Plotkins     10-17 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SEC-Plotkins,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Computer Officials Settle with SEC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two former officials of a computer software
company accused of misusing $1.1 million from a stock offering to
buy securities and a condominium for themselves settled charges
with the Securities and Exchange Commission on Monday.
   Frederick S. Plotkin of New York, former chairman of Intex
Software Systems International Ltd., and his brother, Arthur J.
Plotkin of Guttenberg, N.J., a vice president and director of
Intex, were charged in an SEC civil complaint with making false
statements in disclosure documents between May 1986 and February
1987.
   The complaint, filed in U.S. District Court in New York, says
the documents failed to disclose that the Plotkins used $1.1
million from a stock offering to purchase securities for Frederick
Plotkin and repay loans that he incurred and to purchase a
condominium apartment in Guttenberg, N.J., for use by Arthur
Plotkin.
   Without admitting or denying the charges, the brothers agreed to
a court order forbidding them from further securities law
violations. They were dismissed by Intex' board of directors in
March 1987.
   Awni K. Abboushi, the current president of Intex, which is based
in New York, said it was ``heartbreaking'' that the SEC was not
extracting a financial penalty from the Plotkins. He said Intex has
sued the brothers for damages and compensation but said the company
lacks the money to pursue the suit.
   Harry J. Weiss, SEC assistant director of enforcement, said the
Plotkins were not charged with using corporate funds for their
personal benefit, but rather with failing to disclose the misuse.
He said there were no penalties possible under the charges in the
complaint.
   Arthur H. Christy, an attorney for the Plotkins, said his
clients had no comment.
   Intex sells computer word-processing packages that permit the
operator to enter text in one or more languages.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
