<2ND_LINE>AM-GE Engines-Japan,0176</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GE Lands Major Japanese Jet Engine Order</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EVENDALE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Electric Co. announced Monday that
it has landed a $150 million order from All Nippon Airways of Japan
to provide GE engines for six Boeing 747-400 jet planes.
   Officials at GE's jet engine plant in this Cincinnati suburb
said the order was for the company's CF6-80C2 engine. They said the
CF6-80C2 remains the best-selling engine worldwide for the 747-700
widebody jets.
   Three jets will be delivered to All Nippon in both 1990 and 1991.
   GE officials said the order solidifies the company's position in
the Japanese market. In October 1987, GE announced that it had
nosed out a major competitor, the Pratt & Whitney division of
United Technologies Corp., and obtained an order to provide engines
to Japan Air Lines for five new Boeing 747-400 jets.
   Japan Air Lines has been the largest operator of the four-engine
747s. Until the October 1987 deal with GE, all its 747s had used
Pratt & Whitney engines.
