<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Boeing, 1st Ld-Writethru,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Airways Weighs Purchase Of Boeing Aircraft</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: adds Boeing comment in new 8th graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Airways may purchase a number of Boeing
737 aircraft to replace its aging fleet of short
takeoff-and-landing passenger planes, a spokesman for the airline
said Monday.
   The small, two-engine 737 is among several aircraft British
Airways is sizing up as a successor to the BAC 1-11s due to be
removed soon from London's main airports, Heathrow and Gatwick,
said the spokesman on condition of anonymity.
   The 99-seat BAC 1-11s, manufactured by British Aircraft
Corporation Ltd., will be transferred to provincial airports, said
the spokesman.
   A decision from top British Airways management on which
replacement aircraft to purchase is expected soon, the spokesman
said. Other aircraft under consideration are the British Aerospace
BAe-146, the Fokker 100 and the Airbus A320.
   ``Historically, we've tended to be a Boeing airline,'' said the
spokesman. ``Their aircraft fit the profile we want.''
   The spokesman denied a report in London's Times newspaper that
British Airways directors had already decided to purchase 35
aircraft from the Seattle, Wash., aircraft manufacturer.
   The newspaper said British Airways would purchase 25 of the 737s
worth more than $750 million and about 10 longer-distance 767
medium-sized jets. The 737 aircraft would be from the 300, 400 and
500 series, providing between 110 and 160 seats, the story said.
   In Seattle, Boeing Commercial Airplanes spokesman David Jimenez
declined comment on the report. Boeing's policy is not to discuss
aircraft sales or negotiations until a customer announces them.
   In May, Boeing and Airbus Industrie of Europe split the biggest
commercial aircraft order in history, a 130-plane purchase by
International Lease Finance Corp. of Beverly Hills, California.
   Boeing got the largest part of that contract, selling 100 planes
for $3.69 billion. Among the aircraft were 72 of the 737 series.
</TEXT>
