<1ST_LINE>r f AM-AlleghenyInternational     10-17 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Allegheny International,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stockholder Sues Allegheny International Board</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major stockholder in Allegheny International
Inc. has sued the company's board of directors, claiming they hid
the firm's deterioriating financial position from investors and
sold off subsidiaries at below market value.
   Spear, Leeds & Kellogg, a New York brokerage and investment firm
which owns 25 percent of preferred stock and 7 percent of common
stock, filed suit in U.S. District Court on Friday, naming 11
current and former directors as defendants.
   The New York firm said it and others ``had invested millions of
dollars in Allegheny in reliance on defendants' material
misrepresentations, omissions and acts of fradulent concealment.''
   It charged Allegheny International began selling
income-producing assets in 1986 to pay its debts because of failed
investments in real estate and in oil and gas. It charged the
company then overstated the value of its remaining operations.
   Although the Pittsburgh-based conglomerate realized more than
$500 million from the sales, the money representated ``far less
than ... their real market value,'' according to the lawsuit.
   The lawsuit also charged that a March 1987 tender offer by a
subsidiary of the investment banking firm First Boston Inc. of New
York relied on inflated projections of Allegheny International's
performance.
   Spear, Leeds & Kellogg purchased additional shares of Allegheny
International stock based on the projections, according to the
lawsuit.
   The lawsuit charged that the true financial state of the company
was reflected in Allegheny International's announcement that it has
lost $285.4 million for the fiscal year ending Sept. 27, 1987.
   Allegheny International spokesman Edward Romanoff declined
comment on the lawsuit.
   Allegheny International sought protection under Chapter 11 of
federal bankruptcy laws in February. The company manufactures
Sunbeam and Oster products, among others.
</TEXT>
