<1ST_LINE>r f AM-CaterpillarTalks     10-17 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Caterpillar Talks,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UAW, Caterpillar Negotiators Meet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIDGETON, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Auto Workers and Caterpillar Inc.
negotiators met Monday for extended contract talks amid speculation
that the two sides had agreed at least in principle on an
acceptable job-security package, considered a major roadblock.
   ``It's my understanding they're just working out the language on
the details,'' one UAW source, who declined to give his name, said
of the reports that accord was near on 85 percent job security.
   ``Progress has been made,'' Local 974 bargaining chairman Jerry
Brown said. ``We're moving. That's good.''
   Bill Casstevens, international UAW secretary-treasurer, said
negotiators were to meet again Monday night with hope of ironing
out more contract details.
   ``I'd like to get out of here tonight, not physically but at
least with an agreement,'' Casstevens said. `We're going to work at
it (and) try to do it, but I don't know if it will happen. I got
out of the prediction business a long time ago.''
   Casstevens declined to confirm the 85 percent job-security
provision in the new contract, instead noting that several issues
remained on the table.
   ``We're not going to pick and choose. We're going to work on all
of them,'' he said. ``Just when you think the minefield is clear
you end up stepping on one if you're not careful.''
   Also still to be resolved is whether provisions concerning
special job classifications will be decided at the local or the
national level. The union has said that Caterpillar wanted to
create new special job classifications that would restrict workers
from transferring to other jobs within the company.
</TEXT>
